<DOCNO> AP881108-0002 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 2343EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ELN--ExitPolls 3rdLd-Writethru a0904 11-08 0938</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ELN--Exit Polls, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0904,930</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts lede to reflect Bush victory. Updates throughout with
new poll data. Revises NBC-Journal sampling error in last graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush crafted a watered-down version of the
Reagan revolution Tuesday, drawing independents and a sixth of the
nation's Democrats to his cause and capitalizing on prosperity as a
campaign theme, exit polls said.
   Bush's experience weighed in his favor, the polls said, and his
candidacy appeared to be boosted by affection for his boss,
President Reagan.
   But Bush was nowhere near re-creating the 18-point Reagan
landslide of 1984. The polls said a majority of women voted for
Michael Dukakis, as did just more than half of the Democrats who
voted for Reagan last time.
   Overall, though, Bush was winning about 17 percent of the
Democratic voters _ down from Reagan's 24 percent in 1984, but still
a sizable share, ABC News polling found. Dukakis, by contrast, drew
8 percent of Republicans.
   As pre-election polls anticipated, Bush led with several of the
groups that went with Reagan in 1980 and 1984. Bush was leading
among independents by 54-44 percent in ABC's exit polls, and a CBS
News-New York Times survey said Bush narrowly won Catholics, once a
strongly Democratic group.
   Bush mirrored Reagan down to the gender gap, running strongly
among men but less well among women, the polls found. ABC found Bush
leading with men, 56-43 percent, but Dukakis narrowly ahead among
women, 51-48 percent.
   Dukakis won support from some reliably Democratic groups _ nine
in 10 blacks, two-thirds of Hispanics and nearly six in 10 members
of union households. He also narrowly won 18- to 24-year-olds in NBC
News-Wall Street Journal polling, a group in which Bush had been
strong.
   Bush did not appear to be seriously hamstrung by his selection of
Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana as his running mate. While 16 percent in
the NBC-Wall Street Journal poll said they may have voted for Bush
if he had not picked Quayle, almost all of them were Democrats.
   NBC News pollster Sheldon Gawiser said his conclusion was that
Quayle had little effect on the voting: ``Did it make a point
difference? Yeah, maybe.''
   Economic well-being was a key factor. In NBC-Wall Street Journal
polling, voters split evenly over whether they benefited from
Reagan's economic policies the past eight years. Of those doing
better, 84 percent backed Bush; of those doing worse, 80 percent
backed Dukakis.
   But Bush held a solid edge, 54-46 percent, among the 12 percent
of voters who were not sure whether Reagan's policies had helped
them.
   ``This is very much an economic election. People are in fact
voting their pocketbooks,'' said Gawiser. ``People who have
benefited are much more likely to vote for Bush.''
   ABC News polls found a similar result: Among those who said they
were better off than eight years ago, Bush won, 78-21. Those who
were worse off went for Dukakis, 87-12.
   More than half of the voters polled approved of Reagan's
performance as president _ 53 percent in the NBC-Wall Street Journal
poll _ and 86 percent of them backed Bush. The 38 percent who
disapproved of Reagan's work went for Dukakis in similar numbers;
the 9 percent who were unsure supported Dukakis.
   Even with Reagan's approval rating, voters by 50-44 percent said
in the NBC-Wall Street Journal poll they wanted the country to
change rather than continue its course. While 82 percent who favored
change supported Dukakis, Bush got the rest of them, as well as 91
percent of those who opposed change.
   Those who counted experience as the most important factor in
their choice backed Bush by an overwhelming 94-6 percent in ABC News
polling. He also was highly rated for being trustworthy in a crisis
and as a strong leader.
   The NBC-Wall Street Journal poll, similarly, found the greatest
share of Bush's backers _ 29 percent _ saying they based their
choice on the candidates' competence and experience. Another 24
percent cited national security and defense policies; 17 percent
named economic policies.
   Forty percent of Dukakis' supporters, meanwhile, said they based
their choice on domestic issues such as education and health; an
additional 15 percent cited economic policies. In ABC's poll,
Dukakis was the choice of voters looking for someone who cared about
people and offered a vision for the future. He also won for good
judgment, by 56-43 percent.
   There was some negative voting, as well: Thirteen percent of the
voters who backed Bush, and 19 percent of those who favored Dukakis,
said they made their choice primarily out of dislike for the other
candidate.
   Asked to single out one issue where they most liked their
candidate's stand, 17 percent of the voters in ABC's polls said the
economy, and they picked Bush, 57-43. Sixteen percent said national
defense, and they were for Bush, 88-11. Eleven percent said taxes,
and they were for Bush, 73-26.
   Eleven percent were most taken with their candidate's stand on
the problems of the poor, and they were in the Dukakis camp, 91-8.
The Democrat also was favored, 82-18, by the 10 percent most
impressed with health care stands.
   The ABC results were based on an initial 7,000 interviews with
voters across the country, of more than 10,000 planned. The margin
of error was plus or minus three percentage points. The CBS-Times
results were based on more than 11,000 interviews; that poll had a
two-point margin of error.
   The NBC-Wall Street Journal results were based on about 11,000
interviews and had a margin of error of plus or minus three
percentage points.
</TEXT>
