<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-Khomeini     11-08 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Khomeini,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Khomeini Approves Free Social Expression If Not Extreme</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, in a move
that surprised many people in Iran and neighboring countries, has
declared that free social expression is the best way to settle
disputes.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency reported Monday that
Khomeini said ``academic argument should ... be encouraged rather
than suppressed in the interest of dogmatic interpretation and
authoritarian outlooks.''
   But it said that in an open letter published in the Jomhuri
Islami newspaper, Iran's revolutionary patriarch also advised
advocates of differing opinions ``not to go to extremes or try to
defame the other side.''
   Jomhuri Islami is usually the mouthpiece for hardline Islamic
revolutionary factions.
   The agency, monitored in Cyprus, said Khomeini's letter was a
reply to a prominent Moslem cleric, Hojatoleslam Ansari, who asked
for his ``conclusive judgment'' on the divergent ideological
orientations among Iran's leaders.
   That referred to the differences between pragmatic leaders such
as Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani and hardliners led by Prime
Minister Hussein Musavi and Interior Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi.
   The differences have centered mainly on economic matters, but
intensified after the Khomeini-dominated government accepted a
U.N.-sponsored cease-fire in July in its 8-year-old war with Iraq.
   Khomeini generally had sided with the hardline elements that
support a centralized economy, an isolationist foreign policy and
absolute adherence to the Koran, the Islamic holy book. They also
opposed the cease-fire, which took effect Aug. 20.
   But Iran's economy has been devastated by the war and its
isolation from the West, and Rafsanjani's group appears to have
gained strength.
   Mousavi attempted to resign in July, citing differences within
the regime, but Khomeini publicly rebuked him, telling him to stop
complaining and stay at his post.
   Rafsanjani has encourged more links with the West and in
September Iran began negotiations aimed at restoring full diplomatic
ties with Britain.
   Hardliners objected to the move and Iran's decision to continue
the talks was considered a victory for Rafsanjani's faction.
   Iran has been under tight control and a strict Islamic code since
the revolution organized by Khomeini ousted the Shah Mohammad Reza
Pahlavi in 1979.
   A major issue now is if the government should maintain its firm
grip on the economy and foreign trade or adopt more open policies
toward trade with the West and Western participation in post-war
reconstruction.
   Sources inside Iran have reported a relaxation of the strict
social code based on Islamic tenets. Under those religious
principles, women who do not wear head-to-foot robes can be jailed
or fined and Moslems convicted of drinking liquor can be publicly
flogged.
   The sources said those rules remain in effect, but are not being
as rigidly enforced as they were up to a few months ago.
</TEXT>
