<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 0042EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-IntheBeginning     11-08 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-In the Beginning,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mixture of Sadness, Relief as Years-Long Campaign Ends</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Election Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It started on St. Patrick's Day in 1985.
Ronald Reagan had been inaugurated two months earlier, and Richard
Gephardt was at the Iowa City VFW hall opening the race to replace
him.
   The precise dates vary, but it's as good a point as any to mark
the beginning of the presidential campaign that ends, finally,
today. It was mind-numbing in length, rich in color and left
political activists yearning for a little peace and quiet.
   ``It's hard to believe this is going to be over, but it's time
for it to be over,'' said Iowa Republican Chairman Michael Mahaffey.
``There'll be a little letdown.''
   The race between Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis and
Republican nominee George Bush was just the final matchup of the
campaign for Iowans, who look back at nearly four years of rallies,
coffee klatches and barnyard tours.
   They watched Jesse Jackson milk a cow, Robert Dole drive a
tractor and Bruce Babbitt pedal a bike _ in summer and the dead of
winter.
   Iowa was the first testing ground for Gephardt's tough-talking
trade policies, Pat Robertson's ``invisible army'' of Christian
followers, Dole's ``I'm one of you'' theme and Paul Simon's return
to liberalism of earlier years.
   In the early rounds of the caucuses on Feb. 8, Bush suffered a
stunning loss, finishing third behind Dole and Robertson. Dukakis
also finished third behind Gephardt and Simon in a closer Democratic
contest.
   If today's decision brings a respite, the popular consensus is
that the peace and quiet could last all of 48 hours before yet
another campaign begins.
   ``They won't have time to rest because they get about a month off
and we're right back at it,'' said State Democratic Party Chairwoman
Bonnie Campbell.
   ``I'm not sure it ever comes to an end in Iowa. We have this kind
of perpetual campaign here,'' said Phil Roeder, who was spokesman
for the state Democratic Party until this spring.
   ``We'll have period of 24 or 48 hours for either celebration or
mourning, depending on what happens. It's the end of the end, and
then it's going to be the beginning of the beginning,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
