<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TreasuryBills     11-08 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Bills,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yields on Short-Term T-Bills Soar to Three-Year High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities soared in the latest auction to the highest levels in
more than three years.
   The Treasury Department sold $7.2 billion in three-month bills
Monday at an average discount rate of 7.54 percent, up from 7.37
percent last week. Another $7.2 billion was sold in six-month bills
at an average discount rate of 7.71 percent, up from 7.48 percent
last week.
   The rates were the highest since May 13, 1985, when three-month
bills sold for 7.69 percent and six-month bills averaged 7.9 percent.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 7.79 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for
$9,809.40 and and 8.13 percent for six-month bills selling for
$9,610.20.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said the average yield
for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index for making
changes in adjustable rate home mortgages, edged down to 8.10
percent last week after averaging 8.13 percent the week before.
</TEXT>
