<DOCNO> AP881108-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 0123EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HijackingSuspect Bjt   11-08 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hijacking Suspect, Bjt,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Student Identifies Man As Hijacker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American student who was aboard a Jordanian
airliner seized by terrorists in 1985 says he is positive that
hijacking defendant Fawaz Younis led the ``horde of men'' who
stormed the plane in Beirut.
   ``I recognize him as the leader of the hijackers,'' said William
L. Slade, pointing across a courtroom toward Younis, who was seated
at the defense table.
   ``How sure are you about that?'' asked Justice Department
prosecutor Karen Morrissette.
   ``Positive,'' replied Slade, whose testimony Monday in U.S.
District Court marked the first time Younis had been publicly
identified by one of the victims of the June 11, 1985 hijacking of a
Royal Jordanian Airline jet.
   The Boeing 727 was seized by five heavily armed men as it was
preparing to take off for Amman, Jordan.
   ``About two minutes before takeoff, I heard a great deal of
gunfire outside the aircraft,'' Slade testified. ``A whole horde of
men stormed onto the airplane.''
   ``My gut instinct was to duck, I crouched into my chair,''
recalled Slade. The group started ``beating everything in their way
onto the floor.''
   When things calmed down, Slade, 21, said he noticed that two
hijackers were standing at the rear of the plane and another was
stationed in first class. A fourth hijacker patrolled the aisle
between the two sections of the cabin and the group's leader was in
the cockpit.
   The hijackers who took over the passenger section identified a
group of five or six Jordanian sky marshals and ``proceeded to beat
them thoroughly and torture them.''
   None of the passengers was attacked by the hijackers, he said.
   Slade said he could see the leader in the cockpit from where he
was seated in the back of the plane next to his father, Landry
Slade, a former professor at the American University in Beirut.
   Slade said the hijackers' leader emerged from the cockpit 10
times during the 39-hour ordeal in which the plane was ordered flown
to Cyprus, Tunisia, Sicily, back to Cyprus and then to Beirut.
   Slade testified that Younis came within four or five feet of him
several times during the flight and that he got a good look at his
face when he left the plane.
   ``I shook his hand at the end of the ordeal. I was very close
him,'' Slade said, recalling that he looked at Younis in the eye.
   The hijackers blew up the plane at Beirut International Airport
shortly after the aircraft's 72 passengers and crew members were
released. Younis was also photographed reading a statement at a
press conference that the hijackers held before the plane was blown
up.
   The videotape is expected to be played at the end of this week's
hearing, after five other hijacking victims, including Slade's
father, testify.
   U.S. District Judge Barrington Parker convened the hearing to
determine whether to admit the eyewitness identification of Younis
as evidence when the case goes to trial next year.
   The trial had been scheduled to begin Nov. 14, but the government
is appealing an order that it turn over some classified documents to
the defense.
   Slade said he knew Younis was the leader of the group because he
carried a two-way radio and barked orders when he emerged from the
cockpit.
   Slade said Younis was ``dressed in a flak jacket with a black
headband around his head'' and wore green khaki pants.
   The defendant was ``heavily armed'' and wore ``a vest that
contained ammunition clips as well as hand grenades,'' Slade said.
   Younis mostly went to the passenger section of the plane to tell
his fellow hijackers to stop beating the Jordanian sky marshals,
Slade said.
   He said they followed Younis' orders, but when he left the cabin,
the hijackers ``would start laughing and begin doing it again.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
