<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ImeldaMarcos     11-08 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Imelda Marcos,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Imelda Marcos Arrives Home in Hawaii</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine first lady Imelda Marcos
returned Monday night from a week-long trip to New York, tearfully
calling her court appearance on federal racketeering charges the
``most inhuman experience of my life.''
   Mrs. Marcos traveled to New York to plead innocent to the
charges. She and her husband, 71-year-old Ferdinand, are accused of
plundering $103 million from the Philippine treasury, funneling it
to foreign bank accounts and using it to buy prime New York City
real estate and art.
   ``I've just come back from the most harrowing and most inhuman
experience of my life,'' she told reporters and about two dozen
supporters waiting at the Honolulu International Airport.
   Mrs. Marcos, wife of former Philippine President Ferdinand
Marcos, arrived aboard a jet owned by tobacco heiress Doris Duke, a
long-time friend who also arranged for a $5 million bond so Mrs.
Marcos could return to Hawaii.
   Mrs. Marcos got out of a black limousine which picked her up at
planeside and met with a group of supporters, hugging two of them
who gave her roses.
   One supporter carried a sign reading: ``Praise the law. Justice
for the President and first lady Marcos will prevail.''
   Choking back tears, Mrs. Marcos addressed the group and reporters.
   ``I now pray ... you (the U.S. government) will honor the
territorial integrity of the Republic of the Philippines, a Third
World country, respect our constitution and our laws and above all,
give every human being our right to our dignity,'' she said.
   Sobbing, she said ``God bless America. God Bless the
Philippines,'' and got into the limousine for the 15-minute ride to
the Marcoses' hillside estate overlooking Honolulu.
   After spending several days at Miss Duke's New Jersey estate,
Mrs. Marcos and her 12-member entourage left Sunday aboard the
Boeing 737 and spent Sunday night at the home of her daughter, Irene
Araneta, in a suburb of San Francisco.
   Ferdinand Marcos remained in Hawaii after his attorneys told a
federal judge Marcos was too ill to make the trip.
   The Marcoses are required to appear before FBI agents here
Wednesday to give fingerprints, palm prints as well as voice and
handwriting samples under the terms of a court order issued in New
York.
</TEXT>
