<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--USJews-Israel     11-08 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--US Jews-Israel,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conservative Movement Criticizes Orthodox Pressure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Conservative movement of Judaism has called
on Israel's Likud bloc and Labor party to withstand demands by
Orthodox parties that hold the balance in Israeli politics.
   Neither Likud nor Labor emerged from last week's parliamentary
elections with enough seats to form a majority. The 18 seats won by
several small Orthodox parties could give either side a majority.
   Among demands being made by the Israeli religious parties are
outlawing abortion and autopsies and halting mass transit on the
Sabbath. They also want automatic Israeli citizenship be available
to converts to Judaism only if their conversions were performed by
Orthodox rabbis.
   The statement by the Conservative movement was released at the
Jewish Theological Seminary in New York and urged Labor and Likud to
``reject the blackmail demands,'' The New York Times reported today.
   Orthodox Rabbi Max Schreir, the president of the Rabbinical
Council of Anmerica, responded saying, ``Remember, their (Orthodox)
gains were won in a democratic election.''
</TEXT>
