<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 0140EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel     11-08 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Soldier, Two Palestinians Die</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Palestinian revolt claimed victims on both
sides when an Arab worker stabbed an Israeli soldier to death and
was himself killed, and Israeli troops shot and killed a Palestinian
woman in a separate clash.
   Cpl. David Danieli, 28, a teacher from the coastal town of
Ashkelon, was on army reserve duty guarding a Jewish cooperative
farm in the occupied West Bank when he was killed Monday by a
21-year-old Palestinian worker.
   The farm, Massua Moshav, is 26 miles northeast of Jerusalem and
about one mile from the Jordanian border. It relies on the day labor
of about 100 Palestinian workers to cultivate bananas, grapes, dates
and flowers.
   Residents of the farm said the young Palestinian approached the
soldier and demanded back wages of about $100, but the soldier asked
to see identification papers before letting the worker into the farm.
   At that point, the witnesses said, the worker shouted ``Allahu
Akbar'' _ Arabic for ``God is Great'' _ then stabbed the soldier
repeatedly. A Jewish farmer shot and killed the assailant moments
later, they said.
   ``In the beginning there was a struggle. In the end, the Arab
just kept stabbing all the time, he didn't stop,'' said Tanya
Ben-Ami, a settler who witnessed the attack from the cooperative's
central office.
   The Palestinian was identified as Ahmad Hussein Abdullah Basharat
of Tamoun village, near Jenin. Troops imposed a curfew on Tamoun
following the incident and blew up Basharat's house, a military
spokesman said.
   The Israeli army routinely demolishes houses as a punishment for
attacks. The measure is also viewed as a deterrent for future
attacks.
   Responding to the Israeli soldier's death, Defense Minister
Yitzhak Rabin said: ``We cannot go on without a proper response to
what happened here today.''
   Also Monday, the army raided dozens of West Bank villages, and
troops shot and killed a 23-year-old Palestinian woman during a
clash with protesters in Salem near Nablus, a military spokesman
said.
   At least 21 other Arabs were wounded in the day's unrest, Arab
hospital officials said.
   The 1.5 million Palestinians who live in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, seized by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war, have been
protesting Israeli rule for almost 11 months. Monday's deaths raised
the number of victims in the revolt to 309 Palestinians and 11
Israelis.
 
</TEXT>
