<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama     11-08 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama Begins Accepting Nominations For May Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced that it will
begin accepting nominations for elections May 7 to fill posts
including the presidency, which the armed forces has dominated since
a 1968 military coup.
   Neither acting President Manuel Solis Palma nor Gen. Manual
Antonio Noriega, who as Defense Forces commanders controls Panama,
have said if they will run for president.
   Five parties have said they will nominate candidates, while three
say they will boycott the elections.
   Voters will cast ballots for a president, two vice presidents,
the 67 members of the National Assembly and local government
officials.
   Solis has been acting president since February, shortly after a
federal grand jury in Florida indicted Noriega on drug trafficking
charges. Then-President Eric Arturo Delvalle tried to fire Noriega,
but the Noriega-dominated National Assembly dismissed Delvalle and
replaced him with Solis.
   The United States, which has imposed economic sanctions against
Panama in an unsuccessful attempt to force Noriega to resign, still
recognizes Delvalle as president.
   If Noriega should run he would by law have to resign as Defense
Forces commander by Feb. 7.
   Nicolas Ardito Barletta, running as the government candidate, won
the presidential election in 1984. He resigned in 1985 under
pressure because of differences with the Defense Forces and Vice
President Delvalle succeeded him.
   Solis told the party leaders Monday to choose their candidates
carefully.
   ``Let's not see the same sad situation of the great country to
the north,'' he said, referring to the United States. He claimed
most elected U.S. officials do not represent the American people.
   In another apparent reference to the United States, he told party
officials not to ``accept corrupt money from outside sources that
could change the destiny of our nation.''
   The three legally registered parties that have declared they will
not participate in the May balloting are the Christian Democrats,
the Liberal Republican Movement and the Authentic Panamanian Party.
   Five parties have said they will nominate national and local
candidates. They are the ruling Revolutionary Democratic Party, the
National Action Party, the Democratic Workers Party, the Republican
Party and the new People's Party.
   Solis on Monday formally accepted documents to legalize the
People's Party, which had been the Communist Party.
   The Communist Party participated in the 1984 presidential
election, but lost its official standing because it didn't receive
the 10,000-vote minimum required to maintain its legal status.
   The president and vice president to be elected in May will serve
five-year terms beginning June 7.
   More than 1.2 million people are registered to vote. There were
917,000 registered for the 1984 presidential election, of which
about 640,000 cast votes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
