<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 0144EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MedievalDictionary     11-08 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Medieval Dictionary,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grant To Further Work On 58-Year-Old Dictionary Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new $950,00 grant should help scholars
complete a dictionary of late Middle Ages English by the mid-1990s,
more than 60 years after the project began, officials say.
   The grant is the third awarded to the University of Michigan
Middle English Dictionary project by the Andrew W. Mellon
Foundation, said Editor in Chief Robert E. Lewis, a professor of
English at the Ann Arbor school.
   ``When completed, the MED will be the definitive historical and
descriptive treatment of the lexicon of the Middle English period, a
seminal period in the history of English both in its own right and
as the threshold to modern English, the language we speak and write
today,'' Lewis said.
   Work on the 15,000-page dictionary, a compilation of English
vocabulary between the years 1100 and 1500, began in 1930.
   The dictionary began serial publication in 1952. The 11,000 pages
of completed portions bring the dictionary halfway through letter
``S'' entries.
   The Mellon Foundation already awarded $950,000 to the project in
1974 and $600,000 in 1982.
   Researchers needed four years to complete part of the ``M'' and
``N'' entries, said Professor Sherman M. Kuhn, who directed the
project in 1979. A computer-assisted production system added in 1984
has doubled their output, Lewis said.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
