<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua-US     11-08 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-US,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Say They Will Seek Talks With New U.S. Adminstration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defense minister and a former
ambassador to the United States say the leftist Sandinista
government will seek negotiations with the new U.S. administration
regardless of who wins today's election.
   ``We hope that they accept what the whole world clearly
understands: the defeat of the war policy and civilized
negotiations,'' Defense Minister Gen. Humberto Ortega said Monday.
   The general, brother of President Daniel Ortega, made the remark
after an army promotion ceremony in Managua.
   ``Facing a new administration, whether it be Democrat or
Republican, Nicaragua's position will be the same: The search for a
negotiated solution,'' former Ambassador Carlos Tunnerman wrote in
Monday's Barricada, the official Sandinista newspaper.
   Wilfredo Montalvan, a Contra leader, said the rebels too will
seek a meeting ``to determine if the new government of either Bush
or Dukakis will continue to support the war to defeat once and for
all the Sandinista government.''
   Sandinista leaders say neither Vice President George Bush nor
Gov. Michael Dukakis would be better than President Reagan.
   Washington cut off economic aid to Nicaragua in 1981, declaring
the country a beachhead for communism in Central America and a
threat to U.S. national security. The Reagan administration supports
the Contras, whom the Sandinistas claim are a creation of the United
States.
   There has been no serious contact between Washington and Managua
since early 1985, when the United States broke off direct talks.
   Tunnerman said: ``If Bush wins, he has already said he is
disposed to solicit more military aid for the Contras ... It's
possible that he will not have the same fervor or the same
enthusiasm of Reagan.''
   He said Dukakis' vow to end aid to the Contras ``does not mean he
can dismantle from one day to the other what has been the policy for
eight years.''
   Tunnerman was expelled from the United States in July in response
to Nicaragua's expulsion of U.S. Ambassador Richard Melton.
   Montalvan, a director of the Nicaraguan Resistance, said the
rebels would reject U.S. military aid if it were provided only to
pressure the Sandinistas into democratic reforms.
   ``We cannot allow our people to continue to sacrifice themselves
just to keep pressure on the Sandinistas,'' he said in a telephone
interview from Miami.
   Most Contras fled Nicaragua for Honduras after U.S. military aid
expired in February. They currently draw on a $27-million
humanitarian aid package approved by the U.S. Congress.
   The Sandinistas and rebels signed a cease-fire pact in March, but
each side accuses the other of violations. Talks on a permanent
truce in the 7-year-old civil war broke down in September.
   The conflict has claimed 26,500 lives, by government count.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
