<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 0209EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CampaignTV     11-08 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign TV,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presidential Candidates Make Final TV Pitches For Votes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Election Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush offered a reprise of his
speeches and television ads and Democrat Michael Dukakis confessed
that ``I don't wear my heart on my sleeve,'' as the presidential
candidates took their final shots at the living-room audience.
   The candidates' half-hour television programs Monday night were
as different and typical as their campaigns.
   Dukakis subjected himself to blunt and unflattering questions
from well-meaning people all around the country, while Bush
presented a highly polished documentary that drew extensively on his
convention acceptance speech and several commercials dropped
virtually unedited into the program.
   Dukakis showcased his running mate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, along
with the citizen-questioners and a few scenes with his family. Bush
featured his wife, his children, his grandchildren, police chiefs,
Charlton Heston and President Reagan. Even his media adviser, Roger
Ailes, had an off-screen speaking part. But there was no mention of
Bush's running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle, considered a drag on the
ticket.
   Within the first few seconds of his program, Dukakis was shown
both in shirtsleeves at a town meeting and in a book-lined room
wearing a red pullover sweater. He later appeared playing the
trumpet, dancing with his wife and doing an imitation of a radio
broadcaster who wrongly announced that Dewey had defeated Truman.
   ``Maybe I don't wear my heart on my sleeve, but my passion is in
my service to the public,'' said the Massachusetts governor,
explaining himself to a questioner who asked why he didn't show
emotion.
   Dukakis also defended himself against many of the issues raised
by Bush, including his crime record and his military policy. If
elected, he told one questioner, ``you can bet your life... that
this nation will be defended and defended well.''
   Surrounded by his family, he pledged to be ``a fine president, a
good leader, and somebody you can be proud of.''
   Bush, with background music and rhetoric echoing Reagan's
campaigns, vowed that ``if you elect me president, you will be
better off four years from now than you are today.'' He also said he
had the experience ``to be a steady hand guiding our country.''
   While the tone of the programs was not harsh, the candidates did
not refrain from criticizing each other.
   The vice president, in an excerpt from his acceptance speech,
attacked Dukakis for opposing the death penalty, school prayer and a
Massachusetts bill that would have required teachers to lead the
Pledge of Allegiance.
   Elsewhere in the broadcast Bush reiterated his criticism of the
Massachusetts prison furlough program. And he said Dukakis ``has no
experience in national security affairs. I don't believe we can take
a risk on an issue as important as our national security.''
   Dukakis attacked Republican agricultural policy and charged that
the GOP would balance the budget by cutting Social Security. And he
belittled what he called ``the only new idea George Bush has had
since this campaign began _ a new $40 billion, five-year capital
gains tax giveaway for the very rich.''
   ``Now who is going to pay for that tax break?'' Dukakis demanded
of an enthusiastic audience at a rally. ``Look beside you. Look
behind you. Look in the mirror and ask yourself, is George Bush on
your side?''
   It was left to Bentsen to complain about Bush's hardball media
strategy. ``The people of Texas have been outraged by the
distortions the Republicans have made with their commercial TV,'' he
said. And he contended that voters are also ``deeply concerned''
about the choice of Quayle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
