<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Greece-Scandal     11-08 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Scandal,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cabinet Minister Resigns After Indicted Greek-American Banker Flees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's top law and order official
resigned after a Greek-American banker indicted in a $30-million
scandal escaped police surveillance and fled the country.
   Opposition conservatives immediately demanded the resignation of
Premier Andreas Papandreou's socialist government, claiming George
Koskotas was permitted to escape so he would not implicate top
government officials in allegedly illegal financial deals.
   Koskotas, 34, fled Sunday, apparently by yacht, said a police
officer.
   Speaking on condition of anonymity, the officer said Koskotas
sailed from the village of Megalo Pefko, 20 miles from Athens, and
his whereabouts were unknown.
   Public Order Minister Tassos Sehiotis, whose ministry was
responsible for police surveillance of Koskotas, said he submitted
his resignation Monday ``since such omissions ... create an issue of
political sensitivity.''
   He said a warrant has been issued for Koskotas' arrest.
   One week ago, the banker was banned from leaving Greece while
officials investigated alleged financial irregularities at the Bank
of Crete, which he had controlled.
   Greek newspapers' have charged that senior socialist officials
have been involved in illegal deals set up by Koskotas.
   ``The Greek people are left with the conviction that George
Koskotas was spirited away so that he would not speak. The
responsibility goes all the way to the top of the government
pyramid,'' said Constantine Mitsotakis, leader of the main
opposition New Democracy party. He demanded the government resign.
   The government last week pledged to uncover the scandal and
warned there would be no pardons for members of the governing
Panhellenic Socialist Movement who may be implicated.
   Critics also have lambasted the government for permitting
Koskotas to build a multimillion dollar banking and media empire
without adequately checking his financial background.
   Koskotas was suspended Oct. 20 as Bank of Crete chairman and
indicted on five counts of forgery and embezzlement. He was given
until Nov. 14 to prepare his defense.
   Koskotas, who holds both American and Greek citizenship, bought a
controlling interest in the Bank of Crete in 1984 after working in
its central Athens branch for six years as an accountant.
   Rival newspapers claim Koskotas illegally used Bank of Crete
money to finance his publishing group Grammi, which controls three
daily newspapers, five magazines and a radio station.
   Last weekend, shipowner Aristides Alafouzos paid $6.3 million for
the most presitigious Grammi title, the conservative daily
Kathimerini.
   Koskotas' parents, brother, wife and five children all have left
Greece during the past week.
   The banker grew up in the United States. In 1975, he was fined
$200 in New York for falsifying college letterheads.
   In October 1987, he was arrested in Washington D.C. for alleged
social security fraud but was allowed to return to Greece after
posting $1 million bond. That case attracted wide publicity in
Athens. But the government ignored calls for a thorough
investigation of Koskotas' affairs.
</TEXT>
