<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HijackSentence     11-08 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hijack Sentence,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Women Thanks Judge For His Six Month Sentence In Hijacking Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNIONDALE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who said her former husband
terrorized her into helping him hijack a jetliner to Cuba nearly 20
years ago thanked the judge who sentenced her to six months in jail.
   Linda Joyce Grinage, 39, will have to serve only 32 more days
because she was credited with time served at the Metropolitan
Correctional Center in New York. After her release she will be on
probation for five years.
   ``I think you earned it,'' U.S. District Court Judge Jacob
Mishler said of her sentence. ``I hope you prove it.''
   Mrs. Grinage had been living in the Albany area for about 10
years under the name Haziine Eytina, with her second husband, Mylo
Eytina, and five children. She was arrested in July after the FBI
received an anonymous tip.
   ``Over the last 20 years, I have suffered greatly,'' she told the
judge. ``I've been forced to abandon my two children by my first
marriage and I've been forced to live a double life with my husband
and five children.
   ``I'm now an honest, hardworking woman.''
   Mrs. Grinage, a preschool aide the past five years, pleaded
guilty to a charge of interfering with the crew of a Miami-bound
Eastern Airlines jet from New York. She could have been sentenced to
a maximum 20 years in prison and a $10,000 fine for the plea.
   Charges of air piracy and interference with a flight crew with a
deadly weapon, for which she could have been sentenced to life in
prison, were dropped.
   She admitted helping her first husband, Tyrone Ellington Austin,
hijack the plane on Jan. 2, 1969, by taking a 2-year-old boy hostage
at gunpoint.
   In a tearful plea for leniency at her sentencing Monday, Grinage
expressed remorse for holding a gun to the boy's head, and said she
understands how his mother feels.
   ``I realize I endangered the lives of innocent people and I
frightened them,'' she said.
   The child, his mother and the other 146 people on board were
freed unharmed when jetliner landed in Havana.
   But Mrs. Grinage also claimed Austin had beaten and terrorized
her into cooperating with him.
   ``I knew what my husband had planned,'' Mrs. Grinage said. ``I
was terrified of my husband. If he told me to walk off the side of a
building I would have done so.''
   She and Austin lived in Cuba for an unknown period of time.
   Austin was killed by New York City police in a shoot-out in 1971
following a bank robbery.
</TEXT>
