<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Shuttle     11-08 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Shuttle,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Launch of Soviet Shuttle Scheduled Soon, Radio Moscow Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radio Moscow said today that the Soviets will try
again in the next few days to launch their space shuttle, whose
maiden voyage was scrubbed last month by a last-minute technical
malfunction.
   The state-run radio, in a news broadcast, said the shuttle
orbiter Buran (Snowstorm) and booster rocket Energia are in launch
position at the Baikonur space center on the steppes of Soviet
Kazakhstan.
   ``Their launch and test flight are to take place in the next few
days,'' the radio said, without giving a definite date.
   An earlier attempt to send the Buran on what is to be an unmanned
mission was aborted just 51 seconds before blastoff on Oct. 29 when
a fault appeared in ground equipment. A computer sensed that an
equipment platform had not pulled far enough away from the Energia,
and automatically stopped the countdown.
</TEXT>
