<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Israel     11-08 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Israel,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leftists Claim Assassination Attempt On South Lebanon Army Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition of Syrian-backed leftist
militias claimed responsibility today for an attempt to assassinate
Maj. Gen. Antoine Lahd, commander of the Israeli-backed South
Lebanon Army.
   Beirut newspapers published the Lebanese National Resistance
Front's claim the day after a woman shot and wounded Lahd at his
home in Israel's self-designated security zone in south Lebanon.
   Lahd's troops caught the attacker and were questioning her and
the army commander was flown by helicopter to an Israeli hospital in
Haifa, where a spokesman said he was in stable condition today.
   Zvi Ben-Ishai of Rambam Hospital told army radio that surgeons
operated on Lahd's right arm and upper chest.
   Gen. Yossi Peled, head of Israel's northern command, called the
assassination attempt ``a serious incident.''
   Israeli media said Israeli army intelligence suspected the
assailant, Soha Fawaz Bishara, was paid by a guerrilla organization.
   The Lebanese National Resistance Front statement identified
Bishara, 21, as a Christian from the south Lebanon village of Deir
Mimas, which is inside the security zone.
   It said she was a member of the Lebanese Communist Party from
1982 until 1987, when she joined the Lebanese National Resistance
Front. The front, which cuts across religious lines, includes the
Communists.
   The statement said the attempt on Lahd's life supports the
11-month-old Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied West Bank
and Gaza strip.
   There were no other claims of responsibility. Lahd and his
militia have been the target of Palestinian guerrillas, pro-Syrian
leftist and Iranian-backed Shiite Moslem factions all trying to
drive Israel from the zone.
   Israel carved the zone six to 10 miles deep when most Israeli
troops were withdrawn from Lebanon in 1985 after a three-year
occupation.
   Voice of the South, radio of the South Lebanon Army, said Bishara
works at a health club patronized by Lahd's wife, Minerva, who had
invited her for tea.
   When Lahd, 61, arrived at his home in Marjayoun town Monday
night, Bishara shot him twice in the shoulder, the radio said.
Marjayoun is four miles north of the Israeli border.
   Lahd, a Maronite and retired officer of Lebanon's regular army,
took over his command in September 1984, after his predecessor died
of cancer.
   His predominantly Christian force of 2,000 troops patrols the
zone with about 1,000 Israeli soldiers. The militia has been allied
with Israel for about 12 years.
</TEXT>
