<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0462 11-08 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0462,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede KANSAS CITY</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bentsen Returns To Native Texas At Campaign's End</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Bentsen rally in Austin in first 5 grafs; picks
up 3rd graf pvs, Bentsen was; May stand</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lloyd Bentsen ended a final, marathon
campaign swing in his home state today, still defiant of polls
showing the Democratic ticket trailing.
   More than a hundred supporters greeted him at the Austin airport
for a welcome home ceremony that featured sparklers, a spotlight
entrance, and a Buddy Holly tune.
   To the end, as he stumped through Texas, Louisiana, Arkansas and
Missouri on election eve, he insisted the polls were turning around
and that he and Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis
would win.
   He raced through eight cities in 19 hours, finally winding up a
day of virtually continuous campaigning with the upbeat rally at 3
a.m. EST.
   ``No retreat, baby. No surrender,'' vowed the 67-year-old
chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, quoting a song by rock and
roll star Bruce Springsteen.
   Bentsen was to spend election evening in Austin, visiting with
campaign workers and then waiting for the results in his hotel room.
The Democratic celebration was being held in the Driskill Hotel,
where Lyndon Johnson spent election eve in 1960.
   Also like LBJ, Bentsen was on the ballot today for re-election to
his Senate seat. Under Texas law, he can run for both offices and he
has promised to resign the Senate if he wins the vice presidency.
   Polls released just prior to Election Day indicated the ticket
was still trailing Republicans George Bush and Dan Quayle, although
the gap narrowed to just a few points.
   Dukakis was campaigning around the clock and Bentsen wasn't far
behind. His day started at about 7 a.m. Monday and didn't end until
past 2 a.m. CST Tuesday. He hit eight cities, five in Texas and one
each in Arkansas, Louisiana and Missouri.
   In Kansas City, his last major campaign stop, several hundred
supporters jammed into a hotel ballroom when he spoke at nearly
midnight.
   ``The momentum is with us, it's going our way,'' he told them.
   The final message was simple.
   ``We're on your side, and they're not,'' he repeated at every
stop, echoing Dukakis' class-conscious argument that the Democrats
care more about middle-income needs such as health care, housing,
and Social Security. Republican negative advertising was distorting
that message, he said.
   In Houston, where a crowd of 3,000 greeted him, Bentsen said he
could ``remember how Jack Kennedy and Lyndon Johnson carried
Texas.'' Surrounded by family and political allies, he asserted,
``We carry Texas and we carry it all.''
   Late in the day, Bentsen added to his stump speech the
Springsteen line. Reporters asked afterward if he were a Springsteen
fan.
   ``I am now,'' he replied, upbeat despite the grueling schedule.
``You bet, baby.''
   Bentsen's wife, B.A., quickly grabbed him by the mouth, cutting
short any further explanation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
