<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Graham     11-08 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Graham,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Billy Graham Celebrates 70th Birthday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evangelist Billy Graham, who has preached
to more than 107 million people around the world, celebrated his
70th birthday quietly with relatives.
   ``The family has really wanted to make this a private affair,''
said Graham spokesman Larry Ross. ``They're going to keep it
low-key.''
   Graham, whose birthday was Monday, has said he won't retire until
his health or that of his wife, Ruth, makes it necessary.
   This year, Graham went to China in April, where he visited his
wife's birthplace in Jiangsu province, spoke with university
students and professors, visited a Bible printing plant in Nanjing,
preached at churches in Beijing and Shanghai and met with government
leaders, including Premier Li Peng.
   He was in England and Scandinavia in May and in the Soviet Union
in June to speak during the 1,000th anniversary celebration of the
Russian Orthodox Church.
   Graham appeared at the Republican and Democratic national
conventions, then embarked on a busy crusade: Buffalo, N.Y., in
August; Rochester, N.Y., in September; and Hamilton, Ontario, in
October.
   The Rochester tour stayed on schedule even though Graham was
hospitalized for several days after being bitten on the leg by a
brown recluse spider in Montreal.
   Two weeks ago, he told students at McMaster University in
Hamilton about brown recluse spiders.
   ``If you hear of one, don't go near him because he bit me, and
when they bite they put eight different kinds of poisons into your
bloodstream,'' Graham said.
</TEXT>
