<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 0641EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Prison     11-08 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Prison,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nanny, Granny Start Work As First Women Guards At Grim Dartmoor
Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRINCETOWN, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 182 years as an all-male
preserve, grim, high-security Dartmoor Prison has appointed a granny
and a nanny as its first women guards.
   ``It's just a job. We have always known we could do these jobs
just as well as the men,'' Lynn Draper-Rush, 40, told a news
conference Monday.
   She and ex-nanny Melanie MacCallum, 26, began work after a
13-week training course at the Home Office, the government
department responsible for police and prisons.
   The jail, built in 1806 to house French prisoners captured during
the Napoleonic Wars, has a reputation as one of Britain's grimmest
and toughest.
   Murderers and rapists are among the 630 inmates it confines in
the middle of Dartmoor, a remote area of high, windswept moorland in
southwest England. In the past, when convicts were sentenced to the
now-abolished punishment of hard labor, gangs of Dartmoor prisoners
spent their days breaking rocks out on the moors in all weathers.
Many had their health permanently wrecked by the arduous toil.
   The village of Princetown consists mostly of the homes of the 250
prison guards and their families.
   Prison governor John May said he requested two women guards for
the prison under Britain's equal opportunities legislation, which
abolishes sexual discrimination in the work place.
   He said their appointment would be good for morale in the prison.
   It is rare for women to work in men's prisons. May said Mrs.
Draper-Rush, a former police catering officer, and Mrs. MacCallum
would work on equal terms with the male guards in most respects but
would not go into the prisoners' bathhouse or search inmates.
   Like the male guards, the two women will earn $23,541 a year and
work a 47-hour week.
   Severe overcrowding, poor facilities, old buildings and
increasingly rebellious inmates have contributed in recent years to
escalating rioting and other violence in Britain's ailing prison
service.
   Guards are unarmed in British prisons, but trained in unarmed
combat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
