<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 0700EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StudentTeachers     11-08 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Student Teachers,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nebraska Find A Hard Life During Inner-City Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Future teachers from a small Nebraska
college are seeing firsthand what their students may be like by
spending time in some of this city's worst neighborhoods.
   The visits are part of a course at Hastings College to educate
future teachers about the difficulties faced by urban minorities, as
well as the positive aspects of their lives.
   The lastest group, a class of 18 mostly white, middle-class
students, ends their five-day visit today.
   They saw abused and neglected children, homeless people, drug
busts, and a single mother taking care of seven children in a
one-room house.
   ``It's so easy to look the other way,'' said Kim Sperber, who
grew up in a white, middle-class family in a Denver suburb. ``I
never had a reason to go down to the city, so I didn't.''
   ``You may see some bums and some bag ladies, and that's enough,''
said student John Roebke. ``You don't want to see any more. You
don't want to find out how bad it really is. People who live in
suburbs or better areas are just isolated and ignorant that
situations like that exist in their own cities.''
   The course is required of all education majors at the small,
liberal arts college in Hastings in south central Nebraska.
Enrollment is about 800.
   ``The majority of our students come from small-town and ranching
families,'' said Jan Watkins, an education professor who directs the
course. ``Even those who come from large urban areas do not look at
the city and ethnic groups as this class forces them to do.''
   The students visited minority schools, toured a shelter for the
homeless, attended Sunday services at a black church, ate Mexican
and soul food, watched counselors work with abused children and rode
the streets with police officers.
   ``Everybody's blind to what's going on down there,'' student
Scott Rezac said. ``People wait until the last minute to do
something; people wait to help the kids in detention until they're
in detention. I didn't see one place for the kids to go at night,
like a gymnasium or any (recreation) centers.''
   The class, called the Multi-Cultural Experience, started about
eight years ago after national accrediting organizations told
colleges to develop courses for a greater understanding of minority
issues.
   It was offered as an elective during a winter before it was
developed into a semester-long requirement.
   Through the negatives, the students did find some signs of hope.
   At a detention center, workers ``were really trying to make a
change in the kids' lives,'' Wayne Wiens said. ``It wasn't just a
place to lock them back up.''
   And at a school, ``all the students seemed like they were glad to
be there. They wanted to learn,'' Angie Life said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
