<1ST_LINE>u i PM-TyphoonSkip 1stLd-Writethru a0476 11-08 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Typhoon Skip, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0476,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storm Sweeps Out To Sea After Killing At Least 22</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with one graf to UPDATE with at least 22 dead. Pickup
2nd graf `Skip's center...'; SUBS 11th graf `On Panay...' with 1
graf of details. Pickup 12th graf `Government officials...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Typhoon Skip roared into the South
China Sea today after killing at least 22 people and forcing
thousands to flee their homes in a nation still reeling from a storm
that killed hundreds last month.
   Skip's center passed about 100 miles south of Manila, sparing the
capital from the high winds and flooding that Typhoon Ruby brought
two weeks ago.
   But officials said Skip triggered tornadoes, landslides and
widespread flooding across part of the country's midsection known as
the ``typhoon belt'' _the central Visayas islands and the Bicol
Peninsula of Luzon island.
   The government weather service said that at mid-morning Skip was
about 150 miles southwest of Manila. Maximum sustained winds,
clocked at 108 mph when Skip hit the islands Monday, weakened today
to about 93 mph as the storm crossed the Visayas, the weather
service said.
   Reports of damage and casualties from Typhoon Skip were sketchy
because of poor communications to the affected areas.
   The Social Services Department said at least 400,000 people were
``affected'' by the typhoon, meaning their homes or property were
damaged or destroyed. It said most were on Leyte Island, which was
without electricity because Skip's winds blew down power lines.
   Telephone operators in Manila said all lines to Leyte were down
today.
   The Office of Civil Defense said seven children were killed in
flooding late Monday in the Manila suburb of Pasig, where
floodwaters from Typhoon Ruby have still not receded.
   The Red Cross said at least six people were killed Monday in
Camarines Sur province on the Bicol Peninsula. They included three
bodies recovered from a landslide in Pasacao about 210 miles
southeast of Manila in Camarines Sur. Twenty other people were
missing and believed buried in the slide.
   The Red Cross said the other fatalities in Camarines Sur include
at least two children who died when a tornado triggered by Skip tore
through another town in Camarines Sur. One person drowned elsewhere
in Camarines Sur, the Red Cross said.
   On Panay island, the government's Office of Civil Defense said
six people drowned in Capiz province and two died in Aklan province.
One person died on Marinduque island.
   Government officials said more than 3,000 people were left
homeless on Cebu island and altogether 20,000 were ``affected'' by
the storm. Shelters were set up in schools and churches to care for
the homeless.
   On Mindoro island, the Red Cross said 80 percent of San Jose, a
city of about 70,000 people, was under water today.
   Skip came ashore early Monday on Samar island, 410 miles
southeast of Manila, and moved across the islands of Masbate,
Romblon, Tablas and Mindoro.
   Departmental spokeswoman Teresita Padua estimated damage on Leyte
alone at about $400,000.
   In Manila, the government ordered schools closed today. Most
domestic flights from the Manila airport were canceled but
Philippine Airlines said service would be restored by tonight.
   The typhoon passed well south of the six American military
installations, including Clark Air Base and the Subic Bay naval
base, where damage was reported minimal.
   Skip is the 20th typhoon or tropical storm to hit the archipelago
this year. Typhoon Ruby struck Oct. 24 and tropical storm Tess swept
through the Visayas Islands on Saturday.
   Officials said Ruby killed at least 181 people on land. At least
64 others were killed and more than 200 are missing from the
passenger ship Dona Marilyn, which sank 300 miles southeast of
Manila during the typhoon.
   Government officials said at least 11 people were killed Saturday
during floods caused by Tess.
</TEXT>
