<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Harry'sElection     11-08 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Harry's Election,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush-Quayle Win At Harry's Bar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush and Dan Quayle swept to victory today
over Michael Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen, winning 55 percent of the
vote in the traditional U.S. presidential election straw poll
conducted by Harry's New York Bar in Paris.
   Coming each year hot on the heels of Dixville Notch, the results
of Harry's straw vote is something of a bellwether, wrong only once
since it began in 1924. The goof was in 1976, when the traveling
Americans gave the nod to President Gerald Ford over Jimmy Carter.
   The poll was opened at Harry's Bar on Oct. 27 and closed at 1:30
p.m. today.
   According to owner Andy MacElhone, whose father Harry established
the famed watering hole in 1911, the Republican ticket won 579 of
the 1,050 votes cast, or 55 percent. The Democrats got 471 votes, or
45 percent.
   MacElhone was gearing up for his all-night election bash.
   ``There seem to be a lot more Americans in Paris this year,'' he
said. ``More than last year, and a lot more than the last election
year. I guess they are starting to get used to the six-franc
dollar.''
</TEXT>
