<DOCNO> AP881108-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 0804EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Amnesty-Residency     11-08 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amnesty-Residency,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Phase of Immigration Reforms Under Way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Illegal immigrants who took advantage of the government's amnesty
program can now apply for permanent residency, and the first
applicants included a cowboy in Texas, a teen-ager in Arizona and a
laborer in Illinois.
   Turnout at immigration offices was light Monday, but Immigration
and Naturalization Service officials expect about 1.5 million of the
1.8 million non-agricultural amnesty recipients to eventually apply
for permanent residency.
   Permanent residents receive a so-called green card _ they've
actually been white since 1976 _ which allows them to leave and
enter the country at will and to eventually apply for citizenship.
   ``It's just exciting, I guess, getting something like this,''
said Shane O'Neil, a 31-year-old cowboy. ``It's liberty for me.''
   A native of Yugoslavia, O'Neil received his card after passing
the required tests and and having his fingerprints taken at the El
Paso, Texas, office. He illegally entered the country when he jumped
a ship in Chicago 15 years ago.
   With television cameras documenting the moment, O'Neil calmly
recited the colors of the U.S. flag, explained what the flag's 13
stripes symbolize, told how many states are in the union, identified
Ronald Reagan as the president and defined the Constitution as the
supreme law of the land.
   Amnesty recipients who apply for permanent residency must either
take a 60-hour English and civics class from an INS-certified school
or pass an oral and written test similar to the citizenship test
given to permanent residents who enter this country legally.
   All have to pay an application fee of $80 a person or a maximum
$240 for a family. They have a year to apply.
   ``Today marks the next step on the road to American citizenship
for hundreds of thousands of legalized aliens, and it is with great
pleasure I accept your applications for permanent residency,'' said
Harold Ezell, western regional commissioner of the INS in Los
Angeles.
   Ezell accepted several applications at a morning news conference,
where he handed out buttons labeled ``1994, your first vote,'' a
reminder of the first general election in which amnesty applicants
can vote.
   Charlie Troy, spokesman for the New York District of the INS,
said scores of people mistakenly crowded the legalization office in
Manhattan, but weren't eligible yet to apply for their green cards.
   In Chicago, Alejandro Garcia and his family received permanent
residency on Monday, six days before his 40th birthday.
   ``It's early, but it's a great present,'' said Garcia, a pallet
loader from Hammond, Ind. ``We love the United States.''
   Sergio Molina, 13, and his mother, Molly Molina, were the first
applicants in Phoenix. Mrs. Molina passed the required English and
civics test. Sergio was exempt because of his age.
   Under the Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986, people who
had lived illegally in the United States since before Jan. 1, 1982,
were allowed to apply for amnesty from deportation and were given
temporary permission to work.
   The yearlong program ended for most immigrants last May 4, though
special agricultural workers have until Nov. 30 to apply.
   Those who waited until the last day to apply for amnesty have
until Nov. 4, 1990, to apply for permanent residency.
   People who have completed 40 hours of an approved 60-hour course
don't have to take the test for permanent residency. Neither do
agricultural workers who applied for amnesty under a separate
program, children under 16, adults 65 and older or people who are
physically unable to take the course or test.
   Aliens can apply for citizenship after five years of permanent
residency. Those who are married to U.S. citizens can apply for
citizenship after three years of permanent residency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881108-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 0805EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-Politics     11-08 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Politics,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sources Say Chun Doo-hwan Ready to Surrender Most Wealth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Chun Doo-hwan is ready
to surrender most of his wealth to buy peace from opponents' demands
for his arrest, government party sources said today.
   In the latest anti-Chun protest, eight students armed with
homemade firebombs occupied a prosecutor's office in central Taejon
city today to highlight calls for Chun's arrest. Police arrested all
the students within 30 minutes.
   ``Mr. Chun still thinks he has no ill-gotten wealth, but he is
willing to donate most of his assets if he is assured that it would
quiet down the raging public protests,'' said one of two party
sources who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   In return, the Democratic Justice Party source said, Chun wants
assurances he will be left alone by investigators from opposition
parties and those representing his friend and successor, Roh Tae-woo.
   The second party source said that by giving up most of his
wealth, Chun hopes to atone for major financial scandals in which
some of his relatives have been implicated.
   Chun is accused of corruption and human rights abuses during his
seven years of authoritarian rule which ended in February. The
National Assembly is conducting an unprecedented probe into the
corruption allegations.
   The former president, his associates and relatives are accused of
diverting huge sums in stocks and land and sending much of it
overseas to the United States and Australia.
   Chun, a former general who took power with military backing in
1980, has denied involvement in any corruption.
   The two party sources said Chun has personal assets of $5.7
million, including a $1.4 million residence _ about twice as much as
the amount he officially registered with authorities in 1983.
   They attributed Chun's greater wealth to increases in land prices
during the past five years.
   President Roh, in Australia on an official visit, reportedly
asked the Australian government to check if Chun has any personal
assets there.
   Last week, thousands of people tried to march on Chun's house to
press for his arrest. Opponents are planning another march on Chun's
house Thursday after a major rally in central Seoul.
   On Monday, another member of the ex-president's family was
arrested on corruption charges. Chun Soon-hwan, 67, a cousin, was
charged with taking $52,000 in bribes from a businessman.
   The former president's younger brother, Chun Kyong-hwan, 46, was
sentenced in August to seven years' imprisonment for taking bribes
and embezzling millions of dollars in official funds.
   Government sources said two other family members may be arrested
soon on corruption charges.
