<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SentencingGuidelines     11-08 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sentencing Guidelines,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds Federal Sentencing Guidelines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals has
upheld federal sentencing guidelines, rejecting the argument that
the commission that set the standards violates the separation of
powers mandated by the Constitution.
   The court's decision Monday reversed a U.S. district judge's
ruling that the guidelines were unconstitutional because the
commission was ordered by Congress, appointed by the president and
contains three federal judges.
   An economist, a lawyer, a sociologist and a prison administrator
also are on the seven-member commission.
   The decision upholds the conviction of a Pittsburgh man and
orders the district judge to resentence the man under the guidelines.
   The panel has been developing guidelines for individual federal
crimes since 1985 and is now working on guidelines for criminal
charges against corporations.
   There is a 25 percent sentencing range in the guidelines, but in
cases with unusual mitigating factors, judges are allowed to go
outside them.
   Since the guidelines were introduced, 265 district judges
nationwide have rendered decisions on their constitutionality. Of
those, 150 have said the guidelines are unconstitutional, according
to John Steer, general counsel for the United States Sentencing
Commission.
   A case from Missouri addressing the issue was argued before the
U.S. Supreme Court on Oct. 5. The court has not announced any
decision.
   Monday's decision involved Pittsburgh attorney Alan Frank, who
had been sentenced to 302 days in prison for interstate flight to
avoid prosecution for theft and forgery.
   Although the guidelines called for Frank to be sentenced to 30 to
37 months in prison, U.S. District Judge Donald E. Zeigler on April
1 sentenced him to 302 days. The appeals court ordered Zeigler to
resentence Frank under the guidelines.
</TEXT>
