<HEAD>81-Year-Old Former Legislator Wins $39 Million</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto CX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PERKISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 81-year-old former legislator says he is happy
he won more than $39 million in the state lottery, although he was a
bit skeptical about having to wait six weeks for his first check.
   ``Look at that,'' quipped James Soper, a Cicero Republican who
served in the Illinois Senate from 1966 to 1978. ``The state's
getting all that interest on my money.''
   At a news conference Monday, Soper said he would share 20 percent
of his winnings _ the second largest Lotto jackpot in state history
_ with his longtime secretary, Lois Anderson, who buys lottery
tickets with him.
   Soper, a lawyer, said he would donate some of the money to
various charities for senior citizens and young people, and Mrs.
Anderson said she would travel ``if he gives me some time off.''
   Soper described his prize as ``better than a stick in the eye.
It's not going to change my life. I'm too old. I can't get in
trouble.''
   He will receive his first payment in about five to six weeks,
lottery officials said. The prize will be distributed in annual
installments of $1.95 million over 20 years.
   Mrs. Anderson, 60, who has been Soper's secretary for 38 years,
said she was annoyed at first when her boss called her Monday,
because it was her day off. ``From now on I'll take all his calls,''
she joked.
   Soper said he let an Illinois State Lottery computer at a Cicero
grocery store near his office pick the six winning numbers for
Saturday's Lotto drawing: 33, 35, 43, 44, 45, 52.
   The $39,060,000 jackpot was second only to the $40 million won by
Michael Wittkowski on Sept. 1, 1984.
   Soper said he usuallly spends between $20 and $30 a week on
lottery tickets, but for the large jackpot he bought 100 $1 tickets.
   Soper said though the money wouldn't change his life, he was not
so sure about Mrs. Anderson. ``She's liable to leave me and I won't
have a secretary,'' he worried.
</TEXT>
