<HEAD>Service Held To Mark Anniversary Of IRA Bombing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENNISKILLEN, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A memorial church service
was held today one year after an IRA bomb explosion in this small
town killed 11 people.
   Relatives and friends of the victims and survivors attended the
service of hymns, prayers and readings at the town's Presbyterian
church.
   The bomb exploded Nov. 8, 1987, in a community center where
people had gathered to attend a memorial service for Britain's war
dead.
   The outlawed Irish Republican Army said the bomb was set to
explode as soldiers marched by, but an army device set it off early.
The army denied the claim.
   The Rev. David Couples described today's memorial as ``a strictly
private affair.''
   A memorial wreath-laying ceremony and another church service were
planned for Sunday in this town near the border with the Irish
Republic.
   The IRA is fighting to force the British from Northern Ireland
and unite the Protestant-dominated province with the mainly Roman
Catholic Irish Republic.
