<2ND_LINE>PM-Mother Teresa,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Teresa Begins First Visit To South Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nobel laureate Mother Teresa
was greeted by a kindergarden children's choir when she arrived
today for her first visit to this racially divided nation.
   The 78-year-old nun, who said she hoped to steer clear of
political controversy, plans to establish a mission in Khayelitsha,
an impoverished black township outside Cape Town.
   ``To tell the truth, I don't know anything about politics,'' she
told reporters at Johannesburg's Jan Smuts Airport. ``What is
important is that we love one another.''
   Mother Teresa declined to comment on South Africa's political
situation and said she plans no meetings with government officials
during her weeklong stay, which will include visits to the major
cities.
   Asked if South Africa's poor had suffered because of the
white-dominated government's policy, she replied: ``We are the
government, all of us. It is our duty to love and serve the poor,
not only the duty of some people.''
   Accompanying Mother Teresa were four nuns from India, England and
Burundi, who will run the new mission that is to provide food,
clothing, shelter and what she called ``tender, loving care to the
poorest of the poor.''
   Archbishop Stephen Naidoo of Cape Town, who has repeatedly
invited Mother Teresa to come to South Africa, welcomed her.
   ``We need someone to show us how to live together, how to
transcend the barriers of race and religion,'' he told the news
conference.
   Among the 300 people greeting Mother Teresa at the airport were
about 70 kindergarten children who sang in her honor.
   Born in Skopje, Yugoslavia, of an ethnic Albanian family, Mother
Teresa founded the Missionaries if Charity order in 1950 and became
known as the Saint of Calcutta for her work with the poor in that
Indian city. She won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1979 and has traveled
widely since then to establish 384 missions in 84 countries. Forty
of the missions are in Africa.
</TEXT>
