<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ElectionBriefs     11-08 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Election Briefs,0387</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Chandler, whose name is on the ballot
today for re-election as a state representative, has been asking
people not to vote for him.
   Chandler is serving his third term in New Hampshire's House and
the Concord Republican initially decided to seek re-election. But
when House Clerk Carl Peterson announced his retirement, Chandler
decided he'd rather have that job _ a full-time post he held
previously.
   The only hitch was that Peterson's announcement came too late for
Chandler to drop his name from the ballot.
   So Chandler, 57, has taken down his signs, run no ads and
encouraged people not to vote for him. His is one of 10 names on the
ballot for five at-large seats from Concord.
   State representatives will elect Peterson's successor in
December, and Chandler knows he could lose his House seat and still
not get the clerk's job back.
   ``But it's not fair to hedge your bets,'' he said. If he became
clerk and left the House, it would cost Concord the price of a
special election.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fearful that one of the longest ballots in
state history would create long lines at the ballot booth, hundreds
of San Francisco voters crowded the registrar of voter's office to
request last-minute absentee ballots.
   About 25 percent or 93,000 of the city's voters requested
absentee ballots, according to Acting Registrar Germaine Wong, who
said Monday that she expects about 75 percent of those to be
returned.
   A record number of voters are resorting to absentee ballots to
avoid the crunch at polling places today. The Field Institute said
the phenomenon may mean that some results of some close races ``may
not be known for days and possibly weeks'' after Election Day.
   Absentee ballots take longer to process because the signatures
often must be verified by hand.
   A steady stream of voters poured out of the registrar's office
Monday and snaked through the rotunda of City Hall, confident that
they would save time in the long run.
   But with the counter finally in view after a 45-minute wait,
David Bartholomew, 33, was having second thoughts.
   ``I think now I've learned my lesson and next year I'll send in
for it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
