<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 4thLd-Writethru a0538 11-08 0968</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0538,970</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says He'll Surprise The Experts Tonight</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS pvs 3rd graf bgng, ``I voted,'' to give complete quote.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Underdog Michael Dukakis ended his marathon run for
the presidency today with a cross-country journey home, predicting
that he'd surprise the pollsters with an upset victory over
Republican George Bush.
   Arriving sleepless from a nightlong flight from California that
included stops in Iowa and Michigan, the Democratic nominee was
publicly optimistic as he cast his ballot at a hometown housing
project.
   ``I voted for Mike Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen and I'm proud of
it,'' he said leaving the polling booth with his wife, Kitty, and
their three children. His mother, Euterpe Dukakis, raised her hand
in a V for victory sign.
   At a Boston airport welcome-home rally, Dukakis told his audience
to expect the unexpected.
   ``I think tonight we're not only going to surprise a few people,
but we're going to be doing the celebrating,'' Dukakis told several
hundred cheering supporters. ``It's been an incredible experience.''
   He was equally feisty at a rain-swept rally at the Detroit
airport, his last stop before Boston.
   ``We always knew this would be a tough, competitive race,'' he
said. ``Democrats win tough, competitive races. ... Let's go out
there and make sure that we're the ones who are popping the
champagne corks and preparing for a new era of American greatness.''
   Earlier, about 3,000 partisans braved sub-freezing temperatures
to greet Dukakis before dawn in Des Moines, Iowa, in the state where
the Massachusetts governor began his bid for the White House 20
months ago.
   ``There is so much we can do working together, just so long as we
remember that we are one nation, one community, one people,'' he
told them.
   The rallies were part of a grueling, virtually non-stop schedule
Dukakis has kept up since the weekend in his uphill bid to defeat
Bush.
   ``I come away from all of this even more optimistic about the
future of this great country of ours than when I started,'' he told
supporters before flying to Detroit and then home to Boston.
   Dukakis began the campaign's last trip back across the country
after spending a final day in California.
   ``Don't let them tell you this campaign is over,'' Dukakis said
Monday night in a speech to more than 10,000 supporters in Los
Angeles before heading home. ``It won't be over until the people of
California have their say. ... I know this race is within our grasp
both here and across this country.''
   Dukakis told his California audience they may hear news reports
calling the race in Bush's favor based on exit polls in Eastern
states. But he urged them to work until polls close in the West.
   ``It's yours and the hands across America that will win this
election for us,'' Dukakis said.
   He also took another swipe at Bush's selection of Indiana Sen.
Dan Quayle as his running mate by noting that the GOP nominee did
not mention Quayle during a half-hour network commercial broadcast
on election eve.
   ``I've heard of the secret ballot. This is the first time I've
heard of the secret candidate,'' Dukakis told the star-studded rally
that included performers Ted Danson, Chevy Chase, Kris
Kristofferson, Stephen Stills, Lloyd Bridges, Sally Field, Hal
Linden and Rob Lowe.
   The trip home, which began in California and includes stops in
Iowa and Michigan, will end a 8,500-mile non-stop campaign journey
that began Saturday in Colorado and that by its end will bring
Dukakis to 11 cities in nine states.
   In that time, Dukakis traveled from the West Coast to the Midwest
back West and then across the country one last time on the way home
to cast his ballot late this morning in Brookline, Mass., and await
the results.
   Polls have shown Dukakis closing on Bush but still trailing the
vice president, particularly in the Electoral College count, which
heavily favors the vice president.
   But the Massachusetts governor and aides remained upbeat to the
end of the race, the self-described marathon Dukakis began some 20
months ago as a virtual unknown campaigning in snowy Iowa.
   ``We're here tonight, but tomorrow we're going to slam dunk Bush
and Quayle,'' Dukakis told a boisterous rally at Pauley Pavilion,
the storied basketball arena at UCLA.
   ``The race is closer and it's getting closer every hour,'' the
Massachusetts governor said.
   Dukakis traveled overnight Sunday to campaign Monday morning in
Ohio and Missouri and then flew back to the West Coast for rallies
in San Francisco and Los Angeles before heading back East.
   In San Francisco he spoke to about 30,000 people, pausing for
several minutes at the end of his speech, as he did later in Los
Angeles, to enjoy the cheers.
   Pauley Pavilion at UCLA was the scene of the second and final
debate between Bush and Dukakis _ a contest in which Dukakis was
widely perceived as the loser in a battle he so much needed to win.
   ``I think California is going to lock George Bush right out of
the White House,'' he told the outdoor rally in San Francisco and
the indoor event in Los Angeles.
   Dukakis' long shot strategy is dependent on the race coming down
to California and its 47 electoral votes _ the largest Election Day
prize.
   As the race closed, Dukakis did something he did few times during
the lengthy campaign _ discuss his vision of America.
   ``America is not just a place,'' he said in a solemn tone. ``It's
not just a piece of land or just another country. It's the noblest
experiment ever undertaken on this planet. It's a symbol of what we
human beings can do when we unleash the will of our people, our
nation and our country.''
</TEXT>
