<2ND_LINE>PM-Hospital Kidnapping,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father Of Kidnapped Baby Encourages Tipsters; Reward Increased</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT CHARTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of a baby taken from her arms
at a hospital by a woman posing as a nurse says she has no animosity
toward her son's kidnapper.
   ``I don't hate this woman. I don't know why she did it. I know
she's sick and if there were other people involved in it, they need
help, too,'' Annette Thomas-Jones said. She said the ``nurse'' told
her the baby had to be weighed.
   The baby's father, Willie Jones, issued a new appeal Monday for
leads as the reward for the return of 11-day-old Christopher Michael
Anthony Jones went up by another $10,000.
   So far, $26,500 has been offered for information leading to
recovery of the baby. The $10,000 was put up by the nationally
syndicated ``USA Today: The Television Show,'' said Lynn Matthews,
director of public relations at Doctors Hospital, where the baby was
abducted Nov. 1.
   Two hotlines had received more than 300 calls by Monday,
according to spokesmen for the Little Rock Police Department and the
hospital.
   The infant was born six weeks prematurely Oct. 29.
   ``I appeal to the community to continue to help us by responding
to the composite (drawing), and don't worry about making a
mistake,'' said the father.
   ``If you see someone who fits the description of the composite,
please respond to it. If it is a mistake, the person will
understand,'' he said.
   Mrs. Jones again asked the abductor to consider the infant's
fragile condition and return him to medical care.
   No solid leads have been received, according to Lt. R.L. ``Bert''
Jenkins, spokesman for the Little Rock police.
   ``All these leads were checked out and they're dead ends,''
Jenkins said.
   Jenkins said the police hotline had received more than 200 calls
since it was established last week and a special number at Doctors
Hospital had 114 calls by Monday.
   The public is being asked by police to watch for neighbors and
acquaintances with newborn children, especially if those people had
not been seen with babies or were not pregnant before the abduction.
</TEXT>
