<HEAD>Man Acquitted in Drag Racer's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 59-year-old insurance salesman has been cleared
of charges that he caused a fatal accident by slicking a street with
motor oil to stop local drag racers.
   A jury in state Supreme Court acquitted Andrew Romano of Queens
of second-degree manslaughter and reckless endangerment in the death
of 20-year-old Kenneth Miret of Queens.
   Miret was killed when his car spun into a violent crash while
speeding Nov. 3, 1987.
   It was alleged that Miret's car struck oil that Romano spread on
the roadway after neighbors repeatedly complained about drag racers.
   On the witness stand, Romano denied pouring oil onto the street.
   He could have received up to 15 years in prison if convicted.
