<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0417 11-08 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0417,640</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: TOP 9 grafs new with Quayle voting, picks up 7th graf pvs,
Quayle, seeking x x x</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede: FORT WAYNE, Ind.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quayle Given Hero's Welcome At Hoosier Hometown</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Election Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Sen. Dan Quayle, saying
``Well, we got one sure vote,'' cast his ballot today in his
hometown where he ended his occasionally rocky campaign for the vice
presidency.
   Returning to Indiana Monday night, Quayle told about 2,000
supporters nearby Fort Wayne that he was ``finally at home'' after a
campaign that began when he was picked for the No. 2 slot at the
Republican convention in August.
   ``Well, we got one sure vote,'' Quayle said as he emerged from
the Huntington County Courthouse where he and his wife, Marilyn,
voted.
   ``Two,'' said Mrs. Quayle, adding it was a ``very exciting'' day
for the couple.
   Before voting, Quayle went to the family dentist for a routine
check-up and teeth-cleaning. Aides said the visit to the dentist has
been an election day ritual since Quayle was elected to the House of
Representatives in 1976.
   As he walked from the dentist to the courthouse, elementary
school children cheered Quayle, who was raised in the town.
   Huntington also was the scene of one of Quayle's most trying
campaign moments: a tension-filled confrontation with reporters who
questioned him about his past the day after he accepted the vice
presidential nomination.
   At the rally Monday night, Quayle did not mention accusations
that he had used family influence to get a slot in the Indiana
National Guard to avoid the draft during the Vietnam war.
   But he said, ``There have been weeks of wild exhilaration along
with personal testing, and we knew you were there.''
   Quayle, seeking to become the first Indiana native to become vice
president since Thomas R. Marshall served under President Woodrow
Wilson from 1913-1921, was praised by several state party figures as
a political survivor.
   ``You have been subjected to the white-hot test of politics and
the national press, and you stood the test,'' said Rep. Dan Coates,
R-Ind.
   The rally took on the look of a political convention, with a huge
wooden replica of the American flag used as a backdrop, a videotaped
narrative about Quayle and a series of speeches by gubernatorial
candidate John Mutz and his running mate, Steve Goldsmith.
   ``Fellow Hoosiers, I've been in 38 states and made more than 235
stops,'' Quayle said. ``For the last 10 weeks, I've felt like I've
been strapped to the back of an Indy 500 car. But now I can see the
checkered flag, and with your help my friends, George Bush and I
will be seeing you in the winner's circle.''
   Quayle, accompanied by his wife and his three children, Tucker,
14, Benjamin, 12, and Corinne, 9, dined with his mother and father,
James and Corinne, and spent the night at their home.
   The senator also scheduled a visit today with Martha Pulliam, his
97-year-old grandmother, at the Methodist Nursing Home in
Indianapolis, before returning to Washington to await tonight's
election returns.
   Quayle had been besieged by questions from news organizations
about the circumstances surrounding his enlistment in the Indiana
National Guard at the height of the Vietnam war in 1969 and the
question of whether he benefited by undue influence in getting
admitted into the Indiana University law school with a ``C'' average
on undergraduate work at Depauw University.
   Quayle has said that his campaign went much more smoothly once
the questions were laid aside.
   Campaigning earlier Monday in Roanoke, Va., Quayle said Americans
must ``say good night'' to Democratic presidential candidate Michael
Dukakis if they want to savethe changes wrought during President
Reagan's eight years in office.
   During a rally at an aiport hangar in Roanoke, nestled in the
Blue Ridge Mountains, he declared: ``Let me say to the citizens of
Virginia: Michael Dukakis is not on your side.''
   The senator said he was ``cautiously optimistic'' about the GOP's
election prospects and said he was satisfied with the way he handled
his role as Bush's running mate.
</TEXT>
