<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Maldives     11-08 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Maldives,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>13 Hostages Return Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MALE, Maldives (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirteen hostages returned to this island
nation today, recalling their 56-hour ordeal at the hands of
mercenaries fleeing a failed coup attempt. Hundreds of people
greeted them.
   ``It is a second life for us,'' said V.A. Vincent, second officer
of the cargo ship Progress Light, which was hijacked by the fleeing
Sri Lankan mercenaries Friday.
   ``We had lost all hope. The mercenaries were very ruthless,''
Vincent said.
   Maj. Mohammed Zahir of the National Security Service, the
Maldivian national militia, said seven bodies were found on the ship
after the mercenaries gave up Sunday to two Indian warships 60 miles
off the Sri Lankan coast.
   ``All of the victims were hostages shot by the mercenaries,''
Zahir said.
   Fourteen hostages, including Transport Minister Admed Mujithaba,
were flown to India on Sunday to be treated for injuries suffered
before the mercenaries surrendered.
   Officials said 14 people were killed and 40 wounded in Thursday's
attempted overthrow of President Maumoon Abdul Gayoom. The
mercenaries fled after Indian paratroopers assisted Maldivian forces.
   Hundreds of people crowded the half-mile long jetty in Male as
the Indian frigate Godavari arrived. President Maumoon Abdul Gayoom
greeted the returning hostages.
   At least 65 mercenaries or supporters, their hands bound, were
counted by reporters who went aboard the Godavari. The mercenaries
were to be questioned by authorities.
   Zahir said all those captured were Sri Lankan Tamils with the
exception of two Maldivians. He identified the Maldivians as
Abdullah Luthufi, an aide to former President Ibrahim Nasir, and
businessman Sagar Nasir.
   Nasir has denied involvement in the failed coup.
   Maldivian officials, including Foreign Minister Fathulla Jameel,
have accused Luthufi of recruiting the mercenaries in Sri Lanka
where Tamil guerrillas have waged a 5-year separatist war against
the Colombo government.
   Luthufi told reporters the coup was planned by members of the
People's Liberation of Tamil Eelam, a Tamil militant group in Sri
Lanka.
   ``I met Uma Maheswaran several times in Colombo,'' Luthufi said,
referring to the militant group's founder and leader. ``He provided
the men and the arms.''
   Luthufi said Maheswaran feared his group would be driven out of
Sri Lanka by rival Tamil militias.
   Anthony Jesudasan, a Tamil from Sri Lanka, said he and his
colleagues were informed that they were going to attack the Maldives
only after they set asail.
   He refused to disclose the port from where they sailed but said
two trawlers full of mercenaries were involved in the attack.
   Indian naval officers recovered Chinese-made T-56 rifles,
Soviet-made rocket-propelled grenades and carbines from the
mercenaries, the Indian Foreign Ministry reported in New Delhi.
   Earlier reports by Indian and Maldivian officials put the total
number of hostages at 27, of whom four were reported killed, and the
number of mercenaries aboard the Progress Light at 46. There was no
immediate explanation for the discrepancy, but today's figures were
based on head counts and body counts.
</TEXT>
