<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru a0535 11-08 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0535,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Strikes Protest Plans To Close Lenin Shipyard</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with two strikes, new quotes from Walesa. No
pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at two Gdansk shipyards went on
strike today to demand that the government drop plans to close the
Lenin Shipyard. Solidarity leader Lech Walesa called the strikes ``a
warning to the authorities.''
   Walesa said the strikes defied his banned trade federation and
prove he is losing control of Poland's restive workers. He called
for moderation and indicated he might be willing to conduct talks
with authorities even before the shipyard question is resolved.
   His statement appeared to be a retreat from his earlier demand
that the Lenin Shipyard closure be suspended before the talks begin.
   Speaking to reporters after strikes began at two smaller Gdansk
shipyards, Walesa said he had urged the workers not to strike but
they defied him.
   ``This situation indicates that Lech Walesa and his group are
losing control. It is a warning for myself and a warning to the
authorities,'' he said.
   ``I don't want to go on strike. I want to settle the problems of
the round table and the Solidarity trade union, not to get the
country deeper into crisis,'' Walesa said.
   The government said the nation's largest shipyard, the birthplace
of Solidarity, will be closed in December because it is losing
money. Solidarity said the closure is a politically motivated
attempt to cripple the movement.
   Some workers at the Wisla Shipyard and the Repair Shipyard today
declared strikes in a show of unity to demand preservation of the
Lenin yard. Earlier, Walesa led more than 6,000 workers in a rally
at the Lenin yard opposing the government closure order.
   Wisla Shipyard management would not confirm any work stoppage,
but reporters saw banners at the yard and were told by strike
committee leader Jan Stanecki that nearly half the 1,000 employees
were refusing to work.
   Walesa said about 500 workers were striking at Repair Shipyard.
   He also stopped short of proclaiming a nationwide ``strike
alert,'' which he had threatened Sunday.
   In addition to demanding preservation of the Lenin Shipyard, the
workers who went on strike today called for the rehiring of those
fired for striking in August. They also called for reinstatement of
Solidarity, which was created in August 1980 and banned after a
December 1981 military crackdown.
   After today's rally at the Lenin Shipyard, Walesa said: ``The
Lenin Shipyard is not going on strike for the time being. We are not
even announcing an alert. We are just waiting for reaction all over
the country. We are ready to execute any maneuver, at any moment.''
   On Sunday, he threatened to order a nationwide ``strike alert''
at today's rally. Instead, workers approved a resolution urging a
struggle to preserve ``the cradle of reforms and cradle of
Solidarity,'' Walesa said.
   The state-run news media has accused Walesa of blocking the start
of talks on the country's future. Communist authorities agreed to
the talks in exchange for Walesa's helping end Poland's most serious
labor unrest in seven years.
   As a condition for Solidarity's participation in the talks,
Walesa has demanded the scuttling of plans to close the shipyard and
the rehiring of workers fired because of the August strikes.
   Poland's inflation rate is running about 60 percent and workers
have demanded wage increases to protect their buying power. The
country also faces a foreign debt of more than $39 billion.
</TEXT>
