<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 1207EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-IslandFerries     11-08 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Island Ferries,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vineyard, Nantucket Residents Debate Fate of Boston-based Ferry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of Nantucket and Martha's Vineyard, split
over limiting the tourism that supports their economies, squared off
at a public hearing over the rejection of a direct ferry link
between Boston and the resort islands.
   ``I live on Martha's Vineyard. I consider it a special place. But
that doesn't make me a special person,'' Sherman Goldstein, who owns
the Tisbury Inn, said Monday of the move widely viewed as an attempt
to limit tourist traffic.
   At a daylong Statehouse hearing, the joint Transportation
Committee heard comment on a bill introduced by state Sen. William
Q. MacLean Jr. that would strip the Woods Hole, Martha's Vineyard
and Nantucket Steamship Authority of some licensing powers.
   MacLean, who owns a house on Nantucket, filed the proposed
legislation after the three-member authority board rejected Oct. 20
a private catamaran service to the islands that carried 11,500
passengers between Boston and Martha's Vineyard on a trial basis
last summer.
   Opponents of the high-speed line sought by Bay State-Provincetown
Cruises said it would add to crowds and development problems on the
islands off southern Cape Cod. Defenders said direct access would
alleviate mammoth summer traffic problems on the Cape.
   ``Our streets are jammed,'' steamship authority Chairman Bernard
Grossman of Nantucket said. ``Downtown Nantucket in the three summer
months is like Filene's Basement (department store) between
Thanksgiving and Christmas.''
   MacLean initially sought to strip the authority of its right,
granted by legislation in 1960, to license private ferry service
between the mainland and two islands.
   But under an amendment added Monday, the bill would limit boat
sizes to from 300 to 500 passengers and would limit service to two
round trips daily on the Boston runs.
   The lively hearing prompted charges of elitism on Nantucket,
reports of a movement afoot to issue ``passports'' for year-round
Vineyard residents and Grossman's claim that many Nantucket tourists
arrive ``with $5 and a dirty shirt and don't change either.''
   ``The board of selectmen wants to revoke my citizenship there,''
MacLean, who has come under fire from some Nantucket residents for
proposing the legislation, said to some boos. ``Maybe I'll give it
back to them. I'm not an elitist.''
   Joseph G. Pallotta Jr., who heads Bay State-Provincetown Cruises,
said the Vineyard Spray carried 11,500 passengers from July-October,
less than 2 percent of the 2 million steamship authority passengers.
   He defended service on grounds that the 300-passenger catamaran
carried no cars, motorcycles or mopeds.
   ``The boat keeps thousands of cars off the Cape highways,'' he
added.
</TEXT>
