<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Pasztor     11-08 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Pasztor,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jan Pasztor, One of Only Four Bishops in Czechoslovakia, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bishop Jan Pasztor, one of only
four Roman Catholic prelates in Czechoslovakia, died Tuesday at the
age of 76.
   Pasztor, who was consecrated bishop of the Nitra Diocese in
western Slovakia in 1973, had been ill for some time, according to
the official CTK news agency.
   His death leaves 10 of Czechoslovakia's 13 Roman Catholic sees
without a bishop.
   In June, he attended the consecration of Jan Sokol as bishop and
apostolic administrator of the Archdiocese of Trnava, known as the
``Rome of Slovakia'' for its many historic churches.
   Vatican representative Archbishop Francesco Colasuonno presided
at the ceremony, attended by 15,000 believers, and issued strong
demands for more priests, religious education and bishops to fill
Czechoslovakia's nine empty sees.
   Negotiations between the Vatican and the Czechoslovak government
have always been thorny due to Prague's unwillingness to approve
clergymen proposed by the Vatican to become bishops.
   Apart from Sokol, who is in his mid-50s, all the incumbents are
over 75.
   Earlier this year, about 600,000 people signed a petition calling
for religious freedom and the appointment of new bishops.
   Sokol is in his mid-50s but the other bishops are over 75.
   About 60 percent of Czechoslovakia's 15.5 million people are
Catholics, church officials said.
</TEXT>
