<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Begin     11-08 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Begin,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Begin Breaks Seclusion to Visit Wife's Grave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Prime Minister Menachem Begin broke his
self-imposed seclusion Tuesday to visit the grave of his wife on the
sixth anniversary of her death.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and about 100 other friends and
relatives joined Begin for the 20-minute ceremony on the Mount of
Olives, where his wife, Aliza, is buried.
   Begin shook hands with well-wishers as he left the cemetery
walking arm-in-arm with his daughters, Hassia and Leah.
   ``I haven't seen you in a long time,'' Begin told friends.
``Thank you all very much for coming.''
   Begin, known for lively oratory while in politics, looked haggard
as he stood beside the grave with his family. Long gray hair
protruded from under the rim of his black hat.
   Uri Porat, head of Israel's broadcasting authority and a
long-time friend, said Begin's state of mind appeared improved.
   ``He seemed less indifferent than he once was,'' Porat said. ``He
looked good.''
   Begin, founder of the right-wing Likud bloc who rose to power in
1977, signed a peace treaty with Egypt in 1979 and shared a Nobel
Peace Prize with the late Egyptian President Anwar Sadat. He then
led Israel into a three-year war in Lebanon.
   Begin resigned in 1983, and aides explained the decision as an
outgrowth of his depression over the death of his wife in 1982 and
the loss of nearly 700 soldiers in Lebanon.
   Begin, who has lived as a recluse in his modest home on the edge
of the Jerusalem Forest since his resignation, never said why he
left office.
   His most recent public appearance was in July, when dozens of
supporters met him at his home to celebrate his 75th birthday.
</TEXT>
