<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AIDS-Deaths     11-08 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Deaths,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 1,000 Deaths from AIDS in Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 people have died from AIDS in
Britain and Northern Ireland, the Department of Health said Tuesday.
   Another 68 cases were reported in these regions last month,
bringing the total to 1,862 cases, said the department. The number
of deaths from the disease climbed to 1,002 last month, it said.
   Health Minister David Mellor called the figures ``a somber
milestone in the fight against AIDS and only the first, I fear, in
what will be a series of such milestones in the future.''
   The Soviet Union, meanwhile, has recorded its second AIDS death _
a 4-month-old baby apparently infected by its mother, Tass said
Tuesday.
   The baby's 19-year-old mother had sexual contact with almost 20
partners and became pregnant after becoming infected with the AIDS
virus, the official news agency said.
   It did not give the sex of the baby or provide any more details
about it or the mother, except to say she was from the Odessa region
on the Black Sea.
   Twenty-nine people, 19 of them foreigners, are registered as
having the AIDS virus in Odessa, a major port city, Tass said.
   The first AIDS death in the Soviet Union, that of a 29-year-old
pregnant prostitute, occurred Sept. 5, Tass reported earlier this
month.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to
infections and cancer. It is spread most often through sexual
contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood
or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
