<DOCNO> AP881108-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 1239EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ELN--ElectionRdp 1stAdd a0579 11-08 1065</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ELN--Election Rdp, 1st Add, a0579,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHN: congressional candidates.</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: This add will stand.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Experts estimated that nearly 129.5 million Americans were
registered to vote, or slightly less than 71 percent of the eligible
population, a decline from four years ago. On that basis, the
non-partisan Committee for the Study of the American Electorate
predicted turnout would fall to its lowest level in 40 years, or
slightly over 50 percent.
   That didn't deter the candidates who toed the starting line for
the 1988 presidential race in the days following Reagan's 1984
re-election landslide. The marathon eventually consumed hundreds of
millions of dollars.
   After the tumult of the primary campaigns _ Bush and Dukakis both
took early lumps before triumphing _ the presidential race came down
to a bare-knuckled battle between the 64-year-old vice president and
the 55-year-old Massachusetts governor.
   Not to mention their running mates _ the 41-year-old Quayle and
the 67-year-old Bentsen for the Democrats.
   It fell to them to produce the most riveting moment of the
campaign, doubtless to Quayle's undying regret. The Indiana senator
had just finished comparing himself favorably to John F. Kennedy
when Bentsen turned to him in campaign debate and said, ``Senator,
you're no Jack Kennedy.''
   Bush campaigned as the loyal, logical heir to Reagan and his
two-term conservative revolution. He promised to extend the peace
and prosperity the president claimed as their legacy, but with an
emphasis on education, child care and other issues that would make
America a ``kinder, gentler nation.''
   But he also turned on his rival with commercials of unsurpassed
toughness and employed tough-guy rhetoric in made-for-television
campaign appearances. He said his reply to the Democrats in Congress
would be, ``Read my lips, no new taxes.''
   He trashed Dukakis freely, evoking images of Jimmy Carter when he
said, ``Let's not gamble on another liberal governor coming out of
nowhere who will take us back to the bad old days.''
   Behind in the polls as the summer conventions were ending, he
flicked on the attack ads. Soft on crime, soft on defense, soft on
the Pledge of Allegiance and soft on the environment _ the Bush ads
depicted Dukakis as a quintessential Massachusetts liberal, a man
``outside of the mainstream.''
   Bush made Massachusetts furlough escapee Willie Horton a
household name, and one memorable advertisement depicted the state's
prison system as a revolving door.
   Dukakis had won the Democratic nomination as the architect of the
``Massachusetts Miracle`` and touted his accomplishments in housing,
welfare reform, mandatory health insurance and other concerns. And
he set out to win the fall campaign the same way.
   He absorbed Bush's punishing blows for weeks before heeding the
pleas of Bentsen and other prominent Democrats to fight back. By the
time he did he was far behind in the polls and in need of another
miracle.
   After a lackluster performance in the second and final
presidential debate, he charted a new, populist course and began
waving Republican brochures in the air to dramatize his complaints
that Bush was resorting to ``garbage'' to defeat him.
   ``I'm on your side,'' he said over and over to the average man
and woman. Bush ``wants to help the people who have it made, I want
to help every American family make it,'' he added.
   He attacked Quayle as a risky man to have so close to the Oval
Office, and made the unprecedented move of placing his own running
mate on network television for a five-minute commercial. Dukakis
criticized Bush and Quayle in new, tougher ads.
   All this was a far cry from the man who stood before the
Democratic National Convention and said the election ``isn't about
ideology. It's about competence.'' Bush swiftly rebutted that at his
own political coronation, saying the race was about ``the values we
honor.''
   Bush had a campaign machine that hummed _ even while spitting
political nails at Dukakis.
   The Dukakis machine was a clunker in the judgment of many
Democrats around the country who faulted its advertising, speeches
and scheduling, and finally its candidate.
   By the end, the polls agreed the election was turning voters off.
   Still, neither Bush nor Dukakis hit the level of Senate
Republican candidate Jay Wolfe in West Virginia. He aired a
commercial juxtaposing Byrd and a bloody fetus, and the Republican
Senatorial Campaign Committee ordered him to stop airing it.
   Bush hoped for a ``mainstream mandate,'' but if there was a
national trend in was difficult to discern in advance.
   Some Democrats in Senate races in Florida and elsewhere distanced
themselves from Dukakis, fearing they would be swept away if they
did not. But in Ohio and Washington, Democrats ran as liberal and
proud.
   Some of the most powerful and best known members of Congress were
retiring voluntarily.
   The list ran to Democrat John Stennis in Mississippi; William
Proxmire in Wisconsin and Lawton Chiles in Florida _ committee
chairmen all. The roster also included Republican Rep. Jack Kemp,
who made a career of espousing conservative causes and harbors
presidential hopes of his own, as well as Democratic Rep. Peter
Rodino. He led the House Judiciary Committee impeachment hearings
against President Richard Nixon in 1974.
   The prediction was that whoever the new president was, the
Congress that greeted him would be Democratic.
   Eighty-one incumbents faced either no major part opposition or
only third-party rivals. That included 61 Democrats and 20
Republicans.
   Republicans said they hoped to eat into the Democrats' Senate
majority, but had scarcely the faintest hopes of re-creating the
Reagan landslide in 1980 that swept a dozen Democrats out of office.
   Reagan turned the White House into an arm of the Bush campaign.
   He appointed Cabinet officers that would be attractive in an
election year and swallowed his objections to Democratic-inspired
plant closing legislation that Bush didn't want vetoed for fear of
the damage to his campaign.
   With a final campaign stop in California the day before the
election, the president racked up 25,000 miles for Republican
candidates.
   ``We need you to ride with us,'' he told a crowd at a rodeo
center in Texas. ``And if you would, I hope you'll help win just one
more for the Gipper.''
   Some sounded like they couldn't wait to saddle up for another
ride.
   Jesse Jackson spoke for ambitious Democrats everywhere when he
said a few days before the election that if Dukakis lost on Tuesday,
``the next political season will begin on Wednesday.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
