<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-Britain     11-08 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Britain,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>1989 Match with Britain Endorsed by Foreign Minister Caputo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICENTE L. PANETTA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The national soccer team should
accept an invitation to play in Britain, even though hard feelings
still exist with the country because of the 1982 Falklands War, the
foreign minister.
   ``It seems to me that we should get closer in sports activities
while looking for a (political) dialogue, keeping in mind that
that's not going to produce magic solutions,'' Foreign Minister
Dante Caputo said Monday evening in a radio interview.
   The Argentine Soccer Association was invited last month to
participate in the 1989 Sir Stanley Rous Cup.
   No Argentine soccer team has played in Britain since the war,
although players from both countries have competed against each
other in soccer, tennis, boxing and golf.
   In the 1986 World Cup quarterfinals in Mexico City, Argentina
defeated Britain 2-1, en route to victory over West Germany, 3-2, in
the finals.
   The 1982 war was fought over the Falkland Islands that Britain
has ruled since 1833. Argentina claims it inherited the archipelago
it calls the Malvinas, located off its south Atlantic coast, upon
asserting independence from Spain in 1810.
   Argentina invaded the islands in April. Britain recovered them 74
days later. About 1,000 soldiers from both sides lost their lives in
the fighting.
   Argentina has refused to end hostilities with Britain, which has
substantially fortified its military positions on the islands.
Diplomatic relations broken in 1982 have not been resumed.
</TEXT>
