<1ST_LINE>r a Brites     11-08 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Brites,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALDOSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scores of novice anglers are attracted to a
course at Valdosta State College that allows students to earn
college credits while fishing.
   Titled Freshwater Fishing 315, the course is filled to capacity
each quarter with students who want to bait hooks and reel in
catfish, bluegill, perch and bass.
   ``It's a fun course,'' said instructor Lindy Evans, 45. ``The
homework is excellent _ meaning go fishing.''
   Evans covers all the basics of the sport, from matching rods with
reels to selecting appropriate fishing lines, lures, hooks and bait.
His classes also focus on techniques for catching fish.
   Before graduating from the course, students make one or two
visits to fishponds in the area to test their skills.
   Evans' two-credit-hour course is sponsored by the college's
Physical Education Department as a leisure activity, a category that
also includes such things as golf and tennis.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Want a take-out supper? Maybe the hospital
could suit your palate.
   Hospital food may not have the world's greatest reputation, but
Lawrence Memorial Hospital, for one, is promoting a new frozen
dinner that it says offers healthy, tasty and quick eating.
   On Monday, the hospital began selling ``Light and Right''
dinners, created especially for sale through hospitals by Baxter
Health Care of Chicago.
   The meals, similar to those sold in grocery stores, are low in
calories, sodium, fat and cholesterol, said Nancy Donahey, dietitian
at the hospital.
   She said the meals are largely for the convenience of people
going home from the hospital on special diets.
   ``It may be the answer for their recuperation period when they
are not able to get up and prepare meals,'' she said.
   However, the dietary office at the hospital will sell the meals
to the public as well. Hospital employees were recently treated to a
sampling, and Judith Hefley, director of community relations, said,
``I liked them, actually.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It started with the sending of a few pictures to
people on the other end of his fax line, but Paul Hohendorf got into
correspondence in a big way after his story appeared in a Chicago
newspaper.
   Hohendorf, 33, is vice president of Roostertail catering in
Detroit, and the office facsimile machine normally is used for
business. Sometimes, his business dealings are with women.
   ``I get to know people and talk to them maybe 50 times, and I
send them a picture of myself,'' he said. In one instance, Hohendorf
said he met a woman who ended up accompanying him on a trip to New
York.
   A Chicago Sun-Times column earlier in the week detailed
Hohendorf's fax exchanges and published the number. Hohendorf got
300 responses from Chicago women.
   ``We had to hire an extra secretary just to staple fax papers
together,'' said Hohendorf's boss, Tom Schoenith.
   ``Let's see what you got, big guy,'' one message read.
   ``I can't believe it: I get to pick and choose _ finally _ my
women,'' Hohendorf said. He said he plans to put together a party in
Chicago to meet his new fax friends.
</TEXT>
