<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ELN--Massachusetts     11-08 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ELN--Massachusetts,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Returns Home, Where His 20-Month Marathon Began</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Polls close at 8 p.m. EST; matter below dash will stand.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, home for the final count after an
exhausting marathon run for the presidency, looked to Massachusetts
Tuesday for a safe 13 electoral votes in his Democratic column.
   Massachusetts voters also were deciding whether to ban nuclear
power in the state, mandate ``humane treatment'' of farm animals,
repeal a legislative pay raise and repeal a state law requiring
union wages on public construction projects.
   Dukakis, governor here for 10 of the past 14 years, led a
traditionally strong Democratic ticket in Massachusetts, where
voters were expected to re-elect Sen. Edward M. Kennedy to a sixth
term over Republican challenger Joseph D. Malone, along with all
incumbents in the state's liberal House delegation. Those
congressmen included Kennedy's nephew, Joseph P. Kennedy II, who was
seeking a second term.
   Dukakis was favored in the last Massachusetts opinion polls by a
double-digit margin over Republican George Bush, who was also born
in Massachusetts but turned the state's liberal reputation against
Dukakis in the general election.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   With a home-state candidate, Massachusetts politics was dominated
by the presidential contest, even though Dukakis rarely visited his
home state after Labor Day.
   Republicans, seeking to cast doubt on Dukakis' effectiveness,
pointed to problems his administration was encountering in balancing
the state budget. Bush fueled that campaign by venturing into Boston
twice in the campaign, to highlight the pollution of Boston Harbor
and to claim the Boston police union's endorsement.
   By late August, Dukakis saw his lead in Massachusetts polls
evaporate. But with a late counter-offensive of radio advertising,
field organizing and appeals to home-state pride, Dukakis regained
the edge by mid-October and widened it in the closing days.
</TEXT>
