<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ELN--Michigan     11-08 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ELN--Michigan,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tight Presidential Race, Abortion Decision Draw Michigan Voters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Polls close at 8 and 9 p.m. EST; matter below dash will stand.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michigan voters cast ballots Tuesday in two hotly
contested races, a neck-and-neck Bush-Dukakis showdown for the
state's 20 electoral votes and a yes-or-no decision on banning
state-funded abortions.
   Late polls showed Republican nominee George Bush with only a
slight edge over his Democratic rival, Michael Dukakis, in the
presidential race in Michigan, an industrial state targeted by both
campaigns for personal appearances by the candidates in the final
days.
   Democratic Sen. Donald Riegle was favored as he sought a third
term against former Republican Rep. James W. Dunn Jr.
   In the U.S. House races, all incumbents _ 11 Democrats and seven
Republicans _ sought re-election.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Both presidential nominees visited Michigan in the campaign's
closing days. Massachusetts Gov. Dukakis made 11 trips here between
his nomination and Election Day, including a rally at dawn in
Detroit Tuesday before he flew home to Boston. Vice President Bush
made eight trips to Michigan.
   The outcome of Proposal A, the abortion proposition, was closely
watched by pro-choice and anti-abortion forces in other states as a
gauge of sentiment for their causes.
   At issue was about $6 million spent annually by the state for
about 18,600 abortions for poor women.
   Supporters of the ban argued state funding made Michigan an
advocate of abortion. Opponents said a ban would discriminate
against poor women.
   Riegle raised $4 million for his campaign, while Dunn was forced
to spend about $260,000 from his own pocket.
   Riegle's campaign stressed experience. Dunn accused the senator
of working in Washington for his own wealth and power at the expense
of Michigan interests.
</TEXT>
