<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WaywardBus     11-08 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wayward Bus,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Who Accepted Dare Pleads Guilty To Bus Theft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bus passenger who took the wheel after
the driver pulled over in a fit of anger, challenged him to take
over and stormed off the bus was fined $1,151 when he pleaded guilty
to a misdemeanor theft charge.
   James Biddle drove the bus, loaded with 31 passengers, for about
a mile and a half Oct. 19, making all the proper stops and
collecting all the proper fares, but a city attorney said it was
still wrong because the passengers could have been hurt.
   Biddle, 52, entered his plea to the misdemeanor charge Monday in
North Orange County Municipal Court. In addition to the fine, Judge
Robert Hutson placed Biddle on three years of informal probation.
   Biddle, a Hughes Aircraft engineer, took over the bus after an
argument with driver Kim Dale Miller, 36, who was later fired.
   Several passengers offered this account of what happened: Miller
was yelling at a passenger for his failure to board with the right
fare. When Biddle urged Miller to make smoother stops, Miller became
even more incensed, pulled the bus over to the curb, challenged
Biddle to drive and stormed off the bus.
   After driving for a while, Biddle flagged down a police officer
and told him what happened.
   ``Even though I pleaded guilty, it does not mean that I feel
guilty in my own eyes,'' Biddle said Monday.
   ``I had to relieve the other passengers of the jeopardy that the
driver was putting them in. I only wanted to get out of the area as
quickly and as far as possible,'' he said.
   Anaheim Deputy City Attorney Terese Scanlon disagreed. ``He
endangered the lives of all the other people,'' she said. ``I have
empathy with his frustration, but I can't condone his conduct. Two
wrongs don't make a right.''
   She agreed to dismiss a misdemeanor count of driving a bus
without a proper license in exchange for his guilty plea to the
charge of unlawfully taking a vehicle.
   Biddle said he chose to plea bargain after he talked to an
attorney who told him it would cost $1,500 in attorney's fees and he
might be fined up to $2,000 and sentenced to two years in jail if
convicted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
