<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Crash,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>MiG Crash Kills 3-Year-Old</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Indian MiG-21 fighter jet crashed into
a residential neighborhood on the outskirts of the capital on
Tuesday, killing a 3-year-old girl, a news agency reported.
   At least eight other people on the ground were injured, six of
them seriously, as the plane hit three houses, United News of India
said.
   The pilot of the single-seat plane, Squadron Leader R. Malhotra,
bailed out safely before it crashed and burned in a cluster of
houses near a state-run health center in Najafgarh, about 15 miles
west of central New Delhi, said Defense Ministry spokesman T.G.
Nallumuthu.
   The girl, identified as Sunita Singh, died of burns, UNI said.
   Press Trust of India, another news agency, said eight other
people remained hospitalized, six of them in serious condition.
   The plane was one of 24 scheduled to participate in a fly-by
salute as President Ramaswamy Venkataraman presented colors to an
air force squadron at New Delhi's Palam air force base. The fly-by
was canceled after the crash, an air force spokesman said, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   The cause of the crash was not known, but UNI said the plane was
hit by a bird. High-flying vultures and other birds of prey pose
hazards to aircraft in the New Delhi area.
</TEXT>
