<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hirohito     11-08 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor's Condition Worsening</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The condition of Emperor Hirohito deteriorated
Tuesday when his blood pressure plummeted, but it later improved
slightly, palace officials said.
   The 87-year-old emperor discharged a small amount of blood early
in the afternoon and his blood pressure fell, as it has several
times before. But this time it did not recover despite an emergency
blood transfusion, palace spokesman Kenji Maeda said.
   Later in the afternoon, Hirohito's blood pressure still was only
68 over 30, a level that can cause brain damage if not raised.
   ``This is not an unexpected development, but I'm concerned about
how it will turn out,'' Maeda quoted the emperor's chief physician,
Akira Takagi, as saying.
   Vice Grand Steward Iwao Miyao said the emperor's vital signs were
improving in the evening, and his upper blood pressure reading had
risen to about 90. A normal blood pressure reading is about 120 over
80.
   Maeda said the emperor remained conscious during and after the
blood discharge, which occurred while he was watching his regular
daily 15-minute television drama.
   His temperature, normally 95.9 degrees, soared to 102.2 degrees
this afternoon but dropped to 99.1 degrees by evening, palace
sources said.
   ``His condition has slightly improved since 5:30 p.m., but we are
still concerned about his condition and we will continue to monitor
it carefully and give necessary treatment,'' Maeda said.
   The 1.26-pint transfusion Tuesday brought the total amount of
blood Hirohito has received to more than 41 pints since he first
began suffering from internal bleeding Sept. 19.
   Palace sources say it will be difficult to continue giving him
blood because doctors are having difficulty finding suitable veins
to administer the transfusions.
   Also Tuesday, Prince Aya, the emperor's 22-year-old grandson,
visited Hirohito with his family. Aya has been studying at Britain's
Oxford Univerity and returned to Japan on Monday.
   Aya's return ``was rather hastily decided because of the
emperor's worsening condition,'' Maeda said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
