<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hamadi 1stLd-Writethru a0585 11-08 0794</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0585,0815</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Confessed TWA Hijacker's Parents Testify at Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 21st graf pvs, ``His age ...'' with 2 grafs to ADD
sentences Hamadi faces if 21, or younger.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of Mohammed Hamadi
testified at his trial Tuesday, with his father saying the confessed
hijacker was under 21 at the time of the incident and his mother
saying he was innocent.
   The defendant burst into tears when his mother entered the
courtroom.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, is charged with murder and air
piracy in the June 1985 hijacking of a TWA jetliner to Beirut. U.S.
Navy diver Robert Stethem, 23, was killed and 39 Americans were held
hostage for 17 days.
   Stethem's parents also attended the trial Tuesday. His father,
Richard, took notes and his mother, Patricia, watched the
proceedings with little show of emotion.
   Chief Judge Heiner Mueckenberger told Hamadi's mother, Fatima,
that relatives can refuse to testify ``because it's easy to give
false statements out of love.''
   She replied: ``I know that my son is innocent. I know that he's
very young and that we live under terrible conditions'' in Beirut.
   Of the case itself, she said: ``I don't know anything about this.
I can't read or write.''
   Hamadi has admitted taking part in the hijacking but denied
killing Stethem.
   Fatima Hamadi and her 59-year-old husband, Ali Hassan, traveled
to Frankfurt from Beirut last week to testify. When she walked into
the courtroom Tuesday, in a black dress with a white shawl covering
her head, Mohammed Hamadi stood up until she was seated in the
witness stand.
   He held his hand to his heart and bowed as she began replying to
Mueckenberger's questions in a soft, shaky voice, then suddenly he
burst into tears and dried his eyes with handkerchief.
   Those accused of terrorism in the Middle East seldom face trial
and it is even rarer for parents of a defendant to appear in court.
   Ali Hassan Hamadi testified his son fought with the Shiite
militia Amal in Beirut ``because war had begun and everyone fought.''
   ``Mohammed was injured in the fighting,'' said the father. ``He
was hit in the head and we all thought we had lost him.''
   Asked by Mueckenberger if he thought the young man had recovered
fully from the head injuries, he replied: ``I don't know exactly if
he's right in his head.'' His son and others in the court laughed at
the response.
   Both parents testified in Arabic, which was translated into
German by a court interpreter.
   The judge asked Ali Hassan Hamadi about the work of Mohammed's
older brother, Abdul Hadi Hamadi, Beirut security chief for the
Shiite group Hezbollah, which is allied with Iran and is believed to
be an umbrella group for those holding foreign hostages in Lebanon.
   ``I know about Amal and I know about Hezbollah, but I don't know
who works for them and I'm not interested,'' the father said.
   He said he lives in Bourj el-Barajneh. The south Beirut district
is a Hezbollah stronghold.
   Court records show Mohammed Hamadi was born June 13, 1964. The
father, when asked the birthdate, said:
   ``He was born on Lebanon's Independence Day, Nov. 22, in 1964. I
can remember because it's a holiday and I did not have to work that
day.''
   His age at the time of the hijacking _ whether he was an adult _
is important in determining the length of the prison sentence if
Mohammed Hamadi is convicted.
   If it is determined that he was 21 at the time of the hijacking,
he faces a maximum sentence of life in prison; if it is found that
he was younger at the time of the crime, the maximum sentence is 15
years in prison.
   The defendant's Lebanese wife, Najad, said in the spectator
section, which is separated from the main courtroom by bulletproof
glass, wearing a black chador that covered her hair but not her
face. They were married in late 1986.
   His oldest brother, Adnan, also was present. The father said
Adnan was born ``sometime in 1951'' and all the family's 11 children
were delivered at home by midwife.
   Mohammed Hamadi was arrested at the Frankfurt airport Jan. 13,
1987, after customs agents found liquid explosives in his luggage.
The United States requested extradition but West Germany refused,
fearing for the lives of two West German hostages held in Beirut at
the time.
   Abbas Hamadi, 29, was convicted by a Duesseldorf court in April
of planning the kidnappings to gain Mohammed's freedom and was
sentenced to 13 years in prison.
   He also was arrested at Frankfurt airport in January 1987, two
weeks after his brother. Both West German hostages have been
released.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
