<HEAD>Chun Ready to Surrender Assets, Party Sources Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Chun Doo-hwan is ready
to surrender his wealth to stop escalating demonstrations demanding
his punishment, ruling party sources said Tuesday.
   The officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Chun
would surrender most of his assests if President Roh Tae-woo ensures
the former president's safety.
   ``Mr. Chun still thinks he has no ill-gotten wealth, but he is
willing to donate most of his assents if he is assured that it would
quiet down the raging public protests,'' the ruling party sources
said.
   Chun has about $5.7 million in personal assets, including a $1.4
million residence in Seoul, the sources said.
   Chun and his family have been embattled by allegations of
corruption and human rights abuses under his government. The
National Assembly is conducting an unprecedented investigation into
the allegations.
   Chun, a former general who took power in 1980 and left in
February after seven years of authoritarian rule, denies embezzling
public funds.
   Thousands of people took to the streets last week and battled
riot police to press for Chun's arrest. Dissidents plan more
protests this week.
   The mounting public pressure caused the ruling Democratic Justice
Party to persuade Chun to atone for his misrule, surrender his
wealth and move out of Seoul to live in the countryside, party
officials said.
   In the southern city of Kwangju, violent protests broke out in
downtown streets after college students attacked a government tax
office with firebombs and rocks, according to Yonhap, the South
Korean news agency. No injuries were reported.
   High school students and grade-school kids in Kwangju joined
protesters, Yonhap said, adding bands of youths armed with firebombs
and rocks battled riot police, shouting ``Arrest Chun Doo-hwan!''
and ``Drive out U.S. imperialists!''
   Chun also is under parliamentary investigation for his alleged
role in putting down a 1980 civil uprising in Kwangju in which
nearly 200 people were killed. Dissidents claim the United States
condoned the South Korean army's suppression of the uprising.
   Also on Tuesday, police arrested eight students who briefly
occupied a government prosecutor's building in the central city of
Taejon and demanded Chun's arrest.
</TEXT>
