<2ND_LINE>AM-ELN--Briefs,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Gets Nod In Nation's First Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DIXVILLE NOTCH, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neither snow, nor wind nor midnight
darkness kept the 38 registered voters of Dixville Notch from
observing tradition and casting their ballots as the nation's first
voters Tuesday.
   The townsfolk trooped to the polls in a room at the Balsams
resort just after midnight, as they have done in every presidential
election since the early 1970s.
   Results showed they favored Republican George Bush over Democrat
Michael Dukakis 34-3, with one write-in vote for Rep. Jack Kemp of
New York, a conservative who had sought his party's presidential
nomination.
   Dixville Notch, located in extreme northern New Hampshire, has 28
registered Republicans, six Democrats and four independents. It
incorporated only for the purpose of staging the early vote.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DiPrete's Son Arrested For Tearing Down Sundlun Campaign Signs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 21-year-old son of Rhode Island's
Republican Gov. Edward DiPrete, was arrested Tuesday for allegedly
tearing down a sign belonging to his father's Democratic opponent
from the second story of a house.
   But campaign workers for Democrat Bruce G. Sundlun were also
red-faced after they were caught pulling down DiPrete's signs,
officials said.
   The two candidates have been competing fiercely in a close race.
   Thomas DiPrete was arrested on charges of malicious mischief
after Richard Simons, an auctioneer, said he saw DiPrete face to
face through his second-story window. Simons said the Providence
College student climbed scaffolding outside his East Side house.
   DiPrete was arrested and ordered to appear in court Nov. 15,
according to the police report. Simons said he would not press
charges. Providence police would not comment.
   ``I have severly reprimanded my son Thomas,'' the governor said.
``He has gone at my request to the Sundlun headquarters personally
to apologize for what he did, to make restitution and offer to put
the sign up.''
   John Taylor, a staffer in the governor's press office, caught two
of Sundlun's campaign staffers tearing DiPrete signs off telephone
polls, said DiPrete spokeswoman Nanci Martin.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Sprout Makes it 20 in a Row</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FOSTORIA, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harry Sprout voted early for president
Tuesday. In the past he has voted often: it was his 20th consecutive
presidential election.
   Sprout, who will be 98 on Dec. 17, said he first voted for
Woodrow Wilson in 1912, helping elect the Democrat to the first of
two consecutive terms. He said he has never missed a presidential
election since.
   Sprout refused to say how he voted this year.
