<HEAD>Texans Could Vote for Two Favorite Sons</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Polls close at 8 and 9 p.m. EST; matter below dash will stand.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVAN RAMSTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush was the favored favorite son of Texas
going into Tuesday's presidential election, but polls showed the
other Texan on the national ballot, Lloyd Bentsen, leading in his
second race _ for re-election to the U.S. Senate.
   Final opinion polls showed the Republican with a double-digit
lead in his adopted home state over Democratic presidential nominee
Michael Dukakis. The Massachusetts governor chose Bentsen as his
running mate in a bid to win Texas' 29 electoral votes, the
third-largest haul in the country.
   Bentsen, up for a fourth term, consistently led in his Senate
contest against Rep. Beau Boulter, who was outspent almost 6-to-1.
   In congressional races, Democrats were hoping to pick up one or
two seats to expand their 17-10 lead in the Texas delegation in the
U.S. House.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Texas' best-known congressman, House Speaker Jim Wright, was
headed for his 18th term with no opposition in his Fort Worth
district, despite being the target of a House Ethics Committee
investigation.
   Democrats urged Texans to vote for Bentsen twice. The double
entry was permitted under a 1959 law passed to allow Lyndon Johnson
to seek re-election to the Senate and run for the White House at the
same time.
   In choosing Bentsen as his ticketmate, Dukakis tried to revive
the 1960 ``Boston-Austin axis,'' when John F. Kennedy chose Johnson
as his vice presidential nominee. But several Democratic politicians
noted that Bentsen's double entry allowed his Texas supporters to
vote for Bush and still vote for Bentsen, on the Senate line.
   Bush, born in Massachusetts, maintains a hotel suite in Houston
that he claims as his voting address.
</TEXT>
