<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Cambodia     11-08 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Cambodia,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Skeptical Of Vietnamese Promise Of Pullout From Cambodia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is doubtful that Vietnam will
keep its promise to pull 50,000 troops out of Cambodia this year,
and the Soviet Union has refused to press its Vietnamese allies for
a detailed withdrawal timetable, the State Department said Tuesday.
   Spokesman Charles Redman said Assistant Secretary of State Gaston
Sigur and Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister Igor Rogachev discussed the
matter last week. The two met for 10 hours in Paris to discuss the
Cambodian situation and the recent thaw between North and South
Korea, he said.
   In an unrelated development, Redman announced that Sigur had
canceled a planned trip to Tokyo, Beijing and Seoul because of
``pressing business here.'' He declined to elaborate and said he did
not know whether the visit would be rescheduled.
   Those governments will be briefed on the Sigur-Rogachev meeting
by other U.S. officials, he said.
   Sigur urged Rogachev to press Vietnam for an exact timetable on
the withdrawal from Cambodia, Redman told reporters.
   ``The Soviet side expressed confidence that Vietnamese military
forces will be out of Cambodia by early 1990, but declined to make a
commitment to urge Hanoi to adopt a detailed withdrawal timetable,''
the spokesman said.
   Earlier this year Vietnam said it would pull all its estimated
120,000 troops from Cambodia by 1990, 50,000 of them by the end of
this year. But Redman said that since June 1, only 10,000 to 15,000
have left.
   ``There are signs that Vietnam is preparing to withdraw more
troops in coming months, but we remain skeptical that the 50,000
pledge will be met,'' Redman said.
   U.S. officials were hoping that a Vietnamese timetable would help
move forward talks between the three major opposition groups and the
Vietnamese-installed government in Cambodia on a peace settlement.
   The United States is especially seeking to prevent a return to
power of the Chinese-backed Khmer Rouge, a faction that ruled
Cambodia in the late 1970s and is believed to have killed as many as
1 million Cambodians. The Khmer Rouge is one of the three major
opposition groups conducting the talks on the country's future.
   Sigur ``emphasized the importance of effective safeguards to
prevent the Khmer Rouge from regaining control of Cambodia, and the
need for an international presence to monitor any settlement,''
Redman said.
   ``Both the United States and the Soviet Union are prepared, along
with other countries, to participate in international guarantees,
and favor international monitoring of the implementation of
agreements among the parties to the conflict,'' he added.
   The United States had hoped that a credible Vietnamese pullout
schedule would put pressure on China to end its support for the
Khmer Rouge. The Soviet Union, in talks expected to lead to the
first Sino-Soviet summit in 30 years, has also discussed with the
matter with the Chinese.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
