<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Contras     11-08 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contras,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebel Leader Says Contras `Far From Defeat'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Contra leader insisted Tuesday that the Nicaraguan
rebels are far from defeat despite the cutoff of U.S. aid, their
mass retreat to Honduras and the pessimism of some of their own
leaders.
   The divided rebel movement has appeared stalled since Congress
voted to cut off military aid in deference to the Central American
peace plan sponsored by Costa Rican President Oscar Arias Sanchez.
   Contra Director Alfredo Cesar last month called for further peace
talks with the Sandinistas, saying the military fight against
Nicaragua's leftist rulers is no longer viable.
   But on Tuesday, Wilfredo Montalvan, another of the Contras' seven
directors, strenuously denied the rebels have lost their war against
the Sandinistas.
   ``Some believe we suffered a hard blow with the suspension of
U.S. military aid, but we are far from being defeated,'' Montalvan
said.
   The Contras, he emphasized, are not merely instruments of U.S.
policy in Central America, to be discarded when they are no longer
useful in pressuring the Sandinista government.
   ``We cannot and should not permit our people to continue
sacrificing themselves only for pressure,'' Montalvan warned. ``That
is immoral. When wars are waged, it is to win or to lose, nothing
else.''
   He called for renewed military aid to the Contras, saying the
Soviet Union was giving the Sandinistas $40 million a month. And he
said he would meet with whoever wins the U.S. presidential election
to get a definition of U.S. policy toward Nicaragua.
   Since the aid cutoff, the vast majority of Contra troops, as many
as 10,000, have retreated from Nicaragua in favor of camps along the
Honduran border.
   Their host, Honduras' President Jose Azcona Hoyo, said last week
the lack of military aid had resulted in ``the defeat of the
Nicaraguan Contras.''
   The movement, known formally as the Nicaraguan Resistance, has
long been divided between hard-line and moderate factions, and now
they no longer appear to be communicating with each other.
   ``Many in the resistance see now this isn't working; the
resistance is withering, this is lost,'' said former Contra
spokeswoman Marta Sacasa, who lost her job to the hard-line wing
earlier this year.
   But the Contras' current spokesman, Bosco Matamoros, dismisses
the divergent views within the movement as simply ``an exploration
of new strategies.''
   And he insists that the rebel army, despite its problems, remains
viable.
   ``Our forces are still intact,'' he said. ``There is still
command and control.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
