<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ELN--Florida     11-08 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ELN--Florida,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mack, MacKay, Seek Senate Seat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Polls close at 7 p.m. EST; matter below dash will stand.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Connie Mack, conservative grandson of a
Baseball Hall of Famer, and Kenneth ``Buddy'' MacKay, a Democrat
loaded down with endorsements, battled Tuesday for a U.S. Senate
seat from Florida.
   It was a test of George Bush's coattails, since the Republican
vice president was confident of claiming Florida's 21 electoral
votes in his presidential race against Democrat Michael Dukakis.
   MacKay called himself the logical successor to the retiring Sen.
Lawton Chiles, a three-term Democrat. Mack's late-campaign strategy
was based on Bush's large lead in the Florida opinion polls, and on
President Reagan's popularity here.
   Floridians also voted on a proposition to make English the
official state language, a measure controversial in a state with a
large Hispanic population.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Mack, 48, a former Cape Coral bank president, and MacKay, 55, an
Ocala lawyer, both were elected to the U.S. House in 1982. They
offered different philosophies and styles.
   Mack's campaign commercials often had the tag line: ``Hey Buddy,
You're Liberal,'' and President Reagan did a five-minute satellite
feed for Mack on Monday that charged MacKay had a record that was
``liberal, liberal, liberal.''
   MacKay blasted Mack as an ideologue with a far-right agenda that
was ``anti-Florida.'' He cited his endorsements from senior
citizens' groups, children's advocates, women's groups, teachers,
the state Fraternal Order of Police, and 27 of 30 Florida daily
newspapers that made recommendations.
   MacKay jumped into the Senate race after longtime ally Reubin
Askew, former two-term governor, dropped out. The ensuing six-way
Democratic race led to a runoff in which MacKay defeated 1980 Senate
nominee Bill Gunter.
   Mack had gotten into what appeared to be a longshot race against
Chiles in October 1987. He is the namesake of a grandfather who was
the beloved owner and manager of the Philadelphia Athletics baseball
team.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881108-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 1500EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     11-08 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>9,000 Tourists Evacuated After Theatened Hotel Attacks By
Extremists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese extremists threatened to
attack resort hotels on Sri Lanka's south coast, prompting the
evacuation of nearly 9,000 foreign tourists, officials said.
   A senior official of the government tourist board called the
evacuation an ``unnecessary panic.'' The government and embassies
denied reports that all foreign tourists were advised to leave the
country.
   The tourist official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
the board only had instructed tourists to avoid travel in the south.
He said southern hotels had been advised to transfer their guests
north to Colombo and Negombo.
   Most of the evacuated tourists were from West Germany, Britain,
France and Italy.
   The tourist board issued its warning after 10 hotels in the
Kalutara district received leaflets or telephone calls threatening
attacks unless the tourists left. The district is 25 miles south of
Colombo, the capital.
   Hotel staffers who spoke on condition of anonymity said the
threats were issued by the People's Liberation Front.
   The front called a four-day strike starting Monday to press its
demands for the resignation of President Junius R. Jayewardene and
his government. Most businesses heeded the strike call.
   Authorities have blamed the radical Sinhalese group for the
killings of more than 550 people, mostly Sinhalese who support the
government, in the last 15 months.
   The government said the front had killed 16 people in a series of
attacks in southern and central Sri Lanka on Monday and Tuesday.
   The front is not known to have singled out any foreigners since
it launched a series of bombings and assassinations following the
government's announcement of a peace accord for the island nation's
Tamil ethnic minority on July 29, 1987.
   The front denounced the accord, saying President Junius R.
Jayewardene, a Sinhalese, had sold out the interests of the
Sinhalese majority in his attempts to pacify Tamil separatist
guerrillas.
   More than 8,000 people _ mostly Sinhalese _ have been killed
since Tamil rebel groups mounted their campaign of civilian
massacres and attacks against the government in 1983.
   The mainly Hindu Tamils, who compose about 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million population, say they are discriminated against by
the Buddhist Sinhalese majority.
   Tourism this year is running about 50 percent below what it was
before ethnic tensions turned violent in 1983.
   Despite the trouble, Sri Lanka's beaches and mountain retreats
have drawn 200,000 foreign visitors so far this year, compared with
182,000 for all of 1987, according to tourist board figures.
   The evacuated tourists filled hotels in Colombo and in the beach
resorts in Negombo, 20 miles north of Colombo.
   Negombo's mixed population of Sinhalese and Tamils have lived
peacefully together for many decades.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
