<DOCNO> AP881108-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 1507EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DeficitCommission     11-08 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deficit Commission,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deficit Commission Will Miss First Deadline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The high-level advisory commission on the
federal budget deficit, beset by deep divisions among panel members,
may delay issuing its recommendations for several months, the
co-chairman of the group said Tuesday.
   Democrat Robert Strauss, one of two leaders of the bipartisan
National Economic Commission, said the group's report may not be
issued until March 1 or later.
   This would mark a turnabout from the commission's original goal
of issuing its recommendations by Dec. 21, in time to influence the
first budget submitted by the incoming administration.
   Strauss, in a speech to an investment conference sponsored by the
American Stock Exchange and in later comments to reporters, said the
timing of the panel's report would be left up to the wishes of the
next president.
   Supporters of the 12-member commission, created by Congress last
December, believed that it offered the best hope of breaking through
the seven-year political deadlock over reducing the federal budget
deficit. The commission was expected to come up with a package of
spending cuts and tax increases that would be acceptable to the
White House and Congress.
   Congress gave the commission a deadline of March 1 for issuing
its recommendations. The law allows the next president to extend
that deadline to Sept. 1.
   However, at its first meeting last May, the commission announced
it had agreed to an accelerated schedule that would have a final
report completed by Dec. 21 so the panel's recommendations could
help shape the president-elect's first budget submission to Congress.
   Strauss' comments Tuesday were the first public confirmation of
reports that the commission would not meet that self-imposed
deadline.
   Strauss conceded that the panel was a ``rather stormy
commission'' and said ``we are going to have a hard time'' coming up
with an acceptable package.
   He said that while he was concerned, he was not pessimistic that
the commission would be able to draft a deficit-reduction plan by
the March 1 deadline or Sept. 1, if the new president decides to
extend the deadline.
   Two members of the panel, former defense secretaries Caspar
Weinberger and Donald Rumsfeld, have made it clear that they favor
faster growth in military spending than Congress has allowed while
at the same time they oppose higher taxes.
   Another panelist, Dean Kleckner, president of the American Farm
Bureau Federation, has said in speeches that he would work to block
recommendations for tax increases.
   In comments to reporters after his speech, Strauss said he was
not totally ruling out an attempt by the commission to complete its
work by the Dec. 21 date, but he said such an effort would not be
launched without approval from the president-elect, who will appoint
the final two members of the panel.
   ``Whatever he wants, he can have,'' Strauss said of the
president-elect.
   Republican presidential nominee George Bush has been openly
skeptical of the commission, saying he would not accept
recommendations for tax increases.
   Strauss refused comment when asked about reports that he has
discussed the commission's role with Bush campaign chairman James A.
Baker III.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
