<HEAD>New York: Horserace for Dukakis-Bush; Runaway for Moynihan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Polls close at 9 p.m. EST; matter below dash will stand.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state where Democrats once hoped for landslide
numbers, New York instead became a cliffhanger Tuesday for Michael
Dukakis in his presidential battle against George Bush.
   But New York's two-term Democratic senator, Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, appeared headed for an easy re-election over Republican
Robert McMillan.
   New York's 36 electoral votes, second-biggest prize after
California, were up for grabs, according to pollsters and political
professionals.
   Going into the election, Democrats held a 19-14 congressional
edge, with one vacancy created by the resignation of Bronx Democrat
Mario Biaggi following his Wedtech racketeering conviction.
   While Biaggi remained on the general election ballot on the
Republican line, he did not campaign and Democratic state
Assemblyman Eliot Engel was expected to capture the seat.
   Upstate, Republican Assemblyman L. William Paxon was favored over
Erie County Clerk David Swarts, a Democrat, for the Buffalo-area
House seat surrendered by former Buffalo Bills quarterback Jack Kemp
when he decided to run for the GOP presidential nomination.
   New Yorkers were also voting on Democratic Gov. Mario Cuomo's $3
billion bond issue proposal for highway work.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   With Moynihan's seat appearing safe _ he had 10 times the money
of his challenger _ attention centered on the Dukakis-Bush struggle.
   In the campaign's early stages, with the popular Cuomo heading
his New York campaign and a 3-2 Democratic enrollment edge, Dukakis
appeared in little danger here.
   By mid-October, however, polls indicated Bush had a shot at New
York and Dukakis began devoting valuable campaign time to the state.
Meanwhile, Cuomo spent at least one day a week crisscrossing the
nation for Dukakis with stops in such key states as Texas,
California and Illinois.
</TEXT>
