<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PostalMoney     11-08 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Postal Money,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Post Office May Offer High-Speed Money Transfers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Postal Service is considering
launching a high-speed money order service that would allow people
to transfer funds anywhere in the country almost instantly.
   The service would compete with Western Union's widely advertised
money transfer service.
   Postmaster General Anthony M. Frank said Tuesday that the agency
is preparing to file a request with the independent Postal Rate
Commission for permission to launch the new ``express money order''
service.
   The service would permit a customer to purchase a money order in
one office for delivery, ``within minutes,'' to someone in another
location, anywhere in the country.
   ``We plan to provide express money order service at postal
windows on a cash basis, through an 800, toll-free telephone number
with a major credit card and through qualified independent service
providers,'' Frank told the monthly meeting of the service's board
of governors.
   ``A postal express money order will, in effect, extend the
benefits of emergency funds transfer to virtually every American,
regardless of location or banking status, and we see this as a
valuable public service,'' Frank said.
   No date for filing the formal application to start the service
was disclosed, and consideration by the Postal Rate Commission can
take several months.
   Western Union's service permits consumers to transfer money
instantly among 12,000 outlets across the country.
   That service handled about 10 million transactions last year,
moving $3 billion from one place to another and netting the company
about $200 million in revenues, according to Western Union.
   Western Union officials had no immediate comment about the
potential competition from the Postal Service.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
