<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ELN--Maryland     11-08 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ELN--Maryland,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Close Call on Maryland Gun Law Referendum</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Polls close at 8 p.m. EST; matter below dash will stand.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ROLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A referendum on Maryland's unique gun control
law came down to a dead heat Tuesday after the most expensive
election campaign in the state's history.
   The battle over the gun law dominated a campaign that also
produced a close race between George Bush and Michael Dukakis for
Maryland's 10 electoral votes. Late opinion polls showed the
presidential contest too close to call.
   Democratic Sen. Paul S. Sarbanes was a strong favorite to win a
third term against Republican Alan L. Keyes. The eight incumbent
members of the House of Representatives were also favored to win
re-election. 6-2.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The gun law, passed last April, set up a nine-member board
appointed by the governor to prepare a list of handguns that could
be sold in the state. Maryland gun groups, with the backing of the
National Rifle Association, collected enough petition signatures to
force a referendum on the law.
   The bill was intended to ban Saturday Night Specials, cheap
handuns that supporters of the law say are often used by street
criminals and young teen-agers.
   Faced with early polls showing that almost 80 percent of voters
favored the law, the NRA mounted a $4-million-plus campaign to
convince Marylanders that the board could ban sales of all handguns,
a claim hotly disputed by supporters.
   Backers of the law had only about one-tenth as much money to
spend as the NRA, and by Election Day their early lead in the polls
had all but evaporated.
   Both sides said the outcome in Maryland could affect the future
of gun control efforts nationally.
   ``Either way it goes, it's going to have some impacts in other
states,'' said Richard Gaardiner, an NRA counsel in Washington.
   Michael Beard of the National Coalition to Ban Handguns called
the referendum ``the most significant vote in the last five to 10
years'' on gun control.
</TEXT>
