<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HospitalKidnapping     11-08 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hospital Kidnapping,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Leaves Hospital; Search Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES JEFFERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman whose newborn baby was abducted
from her arms at a hospital by a phony nurse went home Tuesday, and
authorities said they were no closer to finding the frail infant.
   A week after the kidnapping at Doctors Hospital, Annette
Thomas-Jones appealed to the woman who took the baby to ``call a
friend, call the police, call a minister and tell them ... `I've
done something wrong.'''
   Ten-day-old Christopher Michael Jones was born six weeks
premature. Doctors have said he could die if he did not get proper
medical attention.
   Mrs. Thomas-Jones, 32, called for a nationwide effort to find her
child.
   ``It's a matter of a whole country being involved. This is
something that could happen to anyone,'' she said.
   Flashing a brief, subdued smile when she and her husband, Willie
Jones, 39, appeared at a hospital news conference Tuesday, she said
she would never give up hope that her son would be found.
   ``I leave with a charge to continue the search, continue the
fight. Once my health gets to the stage where I can physically, if
it's necessary, search every home in Little Rock, I'm going to find
my child,'' she said.
   Mrs. Thomas-Jones, who previously had maintained her composure in
public, then broke into tears. Later, outside the hospital, she
sobbed freely.
   Authorities said a woman dressed in a white sweater and white
pleated skirt and posing as a nurse went to Mrs. Thomas-Jones' room
on the night of Nov. 1 and took the baby, saying he needed to be
weighed. A hospital employee discovered the baby missing about a
half-hour later and notified police.
   Police Lt. R.L. Jenkins said the police department had received
hundreds of calls about the case, but none had produced a
significant lead to the baby's whereabouts.
   ``A number of calls looked very promising when we got them, but
fizzled out,'' Jenkins said.
   ``At this point in time, to be perfectly candid, when that woman
left the hospital with that baby, we're not a whole lot closer to
finding the baby than we were then,'' Jenkins said.
   Hospital administrator Perry Kinder said a $26,500 reward being
offered for the baby's safe return would be in effect indefinitely.
He said the hospital would continue to provide assistance to the
family in keeping the case before the public ``as long as it takes.''
   He said that while Mrs. Thomas-Jones was sent home by her
doctors, her son would probably not have been well enough to have
accompanied her if he were still in the hospital's nursery.
</TEXT>
