   But Republicans appeared in far better shape in the presidential
race, in which George Bush was expected to defeat Michael Dukakis to
claim the state's 16 electoral votes.
   Opinion polling in May had shown Dukakis with a 14-point
advantage, but then the Democrat radically cut back his campaigning
here in an effort to outflank Bush elsewhere. The vice president,
meanwhile, visited the state eight times and built a commanding
lead, which rose to 19 points in a poll released Monday.
   In the 10th U.S. House district, Democrat Donald Payne of Newark
was considered an easy favorite to become the state's first black
congressman. The city councilman would replace Democrat Peter
Rodino, who is retiring after 40 years in the House.
   New Jersey currently has seven Democrats and six Republicans in
the House.
