<HEAD>Crowded Ballot Topped By Biggest Presidential Prize</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Polls close at 11 p.m. EST; matter below dash will stand</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush appeared to be the slight favorite
over Michael Dukakis on Tuesday as Californians awarded the nation's
biggest batch of electoral votes _ 47 _ and settled 29 statewide
ballot issues ranging from AIDS to auto insurance.
   Republican Sen. Pete Wilson sought a second term against a
longshot Democratic challenger, Lt. Gov. Leo McCarthy, a race dubbed
the ``battle of the blands'' because neither candidate excited much
enthusiasm.
   Five conflicting initiatives on auto insurance reform, sponsored
by insurers, trial lawyers and consumer groups, were the subject of
a $76 million campaign, the most expensive state initiative contest
ever. Other ballot propositions included two AIDS-reporting measures
and a proposed 25-cents-per-pack cigarette tax hike.
   Little change was expected in the makeup of the congressional
delegation of 27 Democrats and 18 Republicans.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Wilson, a former San Diego mayor who won his office in 1982 by
defeating former Gov. Edmund G. Brown Jr., was bucking a jinx that
has seen nearly 40 years go by without anyone winning re-election to
his Senate seat.
   Wilson led McCarthy by comfortable margins in every poll over the
past 21 months, with the final pre-election survey giving the
freshman Republican a 14-point edge.
   Bush had trailed Dukakis by margins of up to 17 percentage points
in every poll of California voters until their final debate in Los
Angeles Oct. 13. That catapulted Bush into a narrow lead which stood
at 6 percentage points in the final pre-election poll.
   Reagan, his popularity remaining high in his home state, made a
final campaign swing to California Monday on behalf of Bush.
</TEXT>
