<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Windy And Wet In The Pacific Northwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain and a little snow blew across the Northwest on Tuesday, and
rain was spread over a wide area of the East. Clouds covered much of
the nation.
   A cold front spread showers and gusty wind across the Northwest
and a gale warning was posted along the coast.
   Parts of Washington state got snow showers, and snow continued
through the day at higher elevations of the Cascade Range.
   Early in the morning, Spokane, Wash., got its first measurable
snow of the season, accumulating to as much as an inch.
   In the East, showers developed along and ahead of a cold front.
Showers were scattered from southern Louisiana to east-central
Georgia, and from northern Virginia to New York state.
   A cold front in the central part of the nation created a few
showers in the central Rockies, and more than 6 inches of snow was
possible in the central and northern mountains of Colorado.
   As that cold front moved eastward, showers and thunderstorms were
expected to develop across much of the Plains and Mississippi Valley
during the night and into Wednesday.
   By contrast, Midland, Texas, equaled its record high for the date
of 87 degrees by early afternoon. But afternoon temperatures were
only in the 30s and 40s around the Great Lakes and in the 30s in the
northern Rockies.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 28
degrees at Yellowstone National Park to 89 at Harlingen, Texas.
Tuesday morning's official low was 9 degrees above zero at Gunnison,
Colo.
   For Wednesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
across much of the Great Plains region and Mississippi Valley.
Showers were forecast from the northern and central Pacific Coast to
the northern Rockies. A few rain and snow showers were forecast for
northern Maine.
   High mostly in the 40s were predicted from eastern Washington
state through Montana and Wyoming to Upper Michigan, and across
northern New England; above 70 from southern California through much
of Texas to the southern Atlantic Coast; in the 80s in the desert
Southwest, and from the Rio Grande Valley of Texas through Louisiana
and southern Arkansas to Florida; and in the 50s and 60s in most of
the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
