<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Palestinian     11-08 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Palestinian,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Prosecutor Seeks Extradition of Palestinian</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor on Tuesday called for the
extradition of a Palestinian wanted by the United States for the
1982 bombing of a Pan Am jetliner.
   Mohammed Rashid is charged with planting a bomb that exploded
aboard a Pan American World Airways jetliner on a Tokyo-Hawaii
flight. A Japanese teen-ager was killed and 15 other people were
injured.
   Panayiotis Theodoropoulos, president of the five-member Supreme
Court panel, said a decision on the extradition would be issued Nov.
15.
   United States officials have said they view the extradition of
Rashid, 39, as a test of Greece's determination to fight terrorism.
   ``The prosecutor's view is a blow against the Palestinian people
and the Palestine Liberation Organization,'' Rashid told the court.
   He was arrested at Athens Airport on May 29 with a forged Syrian
passport and says he is Mohammed Hamdan, an officer in the military
wing of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   A PLO diplomat based in Athens told the court his organization
believes that ``the American evidence and charges are false. We know
he is Hamdan, a soldier since 1967 and an officer in our army.''
   Moustafa Batik, a second secretary at the PLO mission in Athens,
said, ``I don't believe he had anything to do with the bombing.''
   Defense lawyers argued the Greek Constitution forbids the
extradition of foreigners ``prosecuted for their actions as freedom
fighters.''
   But on Oct. 10, a lower court approved the extradition and said
sending Rashid to the United States was not unconstitutional.
   A Supreme Court decision to extradite the Palestinian would have
to be approved by Justice Minister Agamemnon Koutsogiorgas before it
can be carried out.
   Police believe Rashid may also be linked to the attack on the
City of Poros cruise ship July 11 that killed nine people and
injured 98.
   American officials claim Rashid also was involved in the 1986
bombing of a TWA jetliner over southern Greece that killed four
Americans. The TWA blast is not mentioned in the extradition request.
</TEXT>
