<DOCNO> AP881108-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 1706EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Baltics 1stLd-Writethru a0640 11-08 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baltics, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0640,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delegation Heads to Moscow, People's Front Holds Joint Meeting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to shorten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A delegation of Estonians headed to Moscow on
Tuesday to complain about President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
constitutional reforms, Baltic activists said.
   Representatives of the People's Front in the Baltic republics of
Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia complain the reforms are a step
backward in their drive for greater autonomy.
   ``Historians, representatives of the People's Front, all the
people, say it's worse than the Stalin constitution of 1934,'' Felix
Undusk, an editor for state-run Estonian television and official of
the People's Front said in a telephone interview from Tallinn, the
Estonian capital.
   He said two members of the Estonian People's Front left for
Moscow on Tuesday evening along with Communist Party and government
officials to attend a Wednesday meeting on the topic at the
Presidium of the Supreme Soviet.
   The Presidium is the Soviet Union's collective presidency, and
Gorbachev is its chairman.
   Undusk said he understood that representatives of five other
republics were called to the meeting, but that could not be
confirmed.
   In Riga, Latvia, a spokesman for that republic's People's Front
said representatives from Latvia, Lithuania and Estonia gathered for
a one-day meeting Tuesday to determine their response to the
proposed constitutional changes.
   The Latvia organization has come out strongly against them.
   Latvian spokesman Janis Dinevich said the results of the meeting
at the headquarters of the Latvian creative unions would not be
known before Wednesday morning.
   The constitutional reforms create a new national legislature and
a powerful presidency _ changes Gorbachev proposed in June to the
Communist Party conference in Moscow.
   But the Estonian and Latvian People's Fronts have condemned the
plan, saying it removes their constitutional right to secede from
the Soviet Union, and shifts control of the economy and other
aspects of the republic's life to the central government.
   The People's Front organizations that sprang up in the Baltics
earlier this year have been striving for just the opposite: greater
local control and autonomy from Moscow. Some members privately say
their eventual goal is independence from Moscow.
   Top Soviet officials generally have praised the People's Front as
a healthy outgrowth of Gorbachev's effort to restructure Soviet
society and encouragement of greater openness.
   But Gorbachev's top Politburo adviser, Alexander N. Yakovlev, was
quoted in an interview late last month as saying Moscow would not
permit them to take any major steps toward independence.
   The traditionally Westward-looking Baltic states were independent
after the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution until 1940, when Soviet tanks
rolled in on the basis of a secret agreement between the Soviet
Union and Nazi Germany that carved Eastern Europe into spheres of
influence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881108-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 1706EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Cookbook     11-08 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cookbook,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>College Stuck With 94,000 Cookbooks And Printing Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICOPEE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small women's college launched a
cookbook project a year ago with hopes of bringing in $1 million but
is now stuck with 94,000 copies of the book and a $400,000 bill from
the printers.
   The cookbook, compiled by officials of Our Lady of the Elms
College in this Connecticut River city, included more than 400
recipes, many contributed by local and state politicians.
   The Roman Catholic school had planned to use the money raised for
student financial aid and to bring some attention to the 750-student
college, founded in 1928 by the Sisters of St. Joseph.
   College officials ordered 100,000 copies printed. But since last
fall they have sold only 6,000 copies at $10 a copy.
   Sister Mary Dooley, college president, was attending board
meetings of the Association for Independent Colleges and
Universities and could not be reached for comment Tuesday. Sister
Mary Lou Lacey, director of public relations, said no other college
officials would have any comment on the cookbook.
   Earlier, Sister Dooley told New England Monthly magazine that
``we probably did make a mistake in over-ordering.'' She then
provided the magazine with the telephone number at the college at
which orders could be placed. ``They're very attractive,'' she said
of the cookbooks.
   Thomas D. Murphy Jr., chairman of the board of trustees, who
earlier had said a special committee has been established to
``examine all possibilities _ including going outside the state and
country'' to market the book, declined further comment Tuesday.
   The Chicopee attorney said that he and other trustees have been
instructed by their lawyer not to comment on the affair.
   ``It is a very, very sensitive issue for the college,'' he said,
adding that lawyers for the college and the printer were attempting
to resolve the matter of the bill ``and I would hate to say anything
that would thwart those efforts.''
   Earl Alpert, an attorney for the printer, Michael J. O'Malley, a
former trustee of the college, said that his client took the job on
credit and is now looking for his $400,000. He has received
``nothing of consequence'' from the college on the bill, Alpert said.
   Alpert said college officials initially wanted to order more
copies, and O'Malley ``talked them down to 100,000.''
