<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PoliceTraining     11-08 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Police Training,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Director Moves Quickly To Overhaul Massachusetts Police
Curriculum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRUDY TYNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new director of the state's police
training program that has been blamed for the death of a cadet vowed
Tuesday to have a proposal for totally revamped training ready by
month's end.
   ``I have attended a number of police funerals, and never have I
felt the depth of feeling as in that church and outside,'' Peter W.
Agnes Jr. said after the services Monday for cadet Timothy Shepard,
25. ``As the bishop (Joseph Maguire of Springfield) said in his
eloquent message, we can't miss the opportunity to use this
tragedy.''
   ``We have a great need to demonstrate to the public quickly and
in a most decisive way possible that the training programs will be
made safe and the best they can be,'' Agnes said in a telephone
interview from his Boston office.
   Agnes, assistant secretary of public safety, took over the
Criminal Justice Training Council following the resignation last
week of director Gary Egan. Shepard of Pittsfield died the same day.
   He had lingered for 44 days and undergone a liver transplant
after collapsing with heat stroke on the first day of training at
the state's Agawam police training academy.
   State Attorney General James Shannon has sought an inquest into
Shepard's death to determine whether criminal charges should be
brought against State Police instructors. He blamed the rigorous day
of stress training, including punishment laps and pushups, and
inadequate water, for the hospitalization of Shepard and 15 other
cadets out of the class of 50.
   After he was named, Agnes outlawed the use of physical activity
as punishment and asked for the resignation of Agawam director Earl
Harrington. When Harrington declined to quit, Agnes transferred him
and began dismissal proceedings.
   ``We will not teach someone to cope with stress by putting them
under stress. We will do it by giving them the skills and
reinforcement they need,'' Agnes said Tuesday.
   ``We want the people who graduate and become police officers to
continue a lifelong regimen of physical fitness. We don't want them
to think of pushups and situps as some part of hazing or a hellish
experience.''
   Hundreds of Pittsfield residents, unable to squeeze inside the
church, silently lined the street outside during Shepard's funeral
Monday. Many said they did not know the young man, but were outraged
by his death.
   Agnes said Tuesday that he planned to have an outline for the new
curriculum ready for the council's Nov. 30 meeting. It could be
launched as a pilot program beginning in January.
   ``It would be a terrible mistake to put this on hold and study it
for a year,'' Agnes said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
