<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cambodia     11-08 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government, Rebels To Set Up Panel on Peace Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Cambodia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHE CACHERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   FERE-EN-TARDENOIS, France (AP) _ The leaders of two Cambodian
rebel factions and the Cambodian premier agreed Tuesday to establish
a ``working commission'' to pursue peace efforts.
   Participating in the two-day meeting at this village 70 miles
east of Paris were Vietnamese-backed Premier Hun Sen and resistance
leaders Prince Norodom Sihanouk and Son Sann of the anti-communist
Khmer People's National Liberation Front. Their talks ended Tuesday.
   They said the new commission will be based in the former
Cambodian Embassy building in Paris and would include three to six
representatives from each group.
   The radical communist Khmer Rouge, which has the largest
guerrrilla force in Cambodia, did not participate in the talks but
the three said it would be invited to send representatives to the
commission.
   The Khmer Rouge had been invited to join in the talks here, but
the three other leaders rejected the organization's proposed envoy
saying he was not ``qualified'' for a summit meeting. The Khmer
Rouge had said it would send Ok Saukun, a delegate to the U.N.
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization.
   In a joint statement the three men said they supported calling an
international conference on Cambodia and were prepared to meet again
in France next year.
   No date was set for that meeting but Sihanouk's son, Prince
Norodom Ranariddh, told reporters it would not be before September.
   Ranariddh said some means had to be found to include the Khmer
Rouge in the negotitiations on Cambodia's future despite its brutal
rule from 1975-l979.
   ``We shouldn't drive the Khmer Rouge into the forest,'' Ranariddh
said. ``To exclude the Khmer Rouge would be to pass from a war
against Vietnamese occupation to a civil war.''
   The Khmer Rouge came to power in the spring of 1975, defeating
the U.S.-backed government. Hundreds of thousands of Cambodians
perished as the Khmer Rouge purged opponents and forced millions of
people from the cities in an effort to establish an agrarian
communist society.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978, ousted the Khmer Rouge
and established another communist government. The Khmer Rouge,
Sihanouk and Son Sann formed an uneasy alliance to battle more than
100,000 Vietnamese troops in Cambodia.
   Hun Sen, speaking at a news conference, said Cambodians must be
vigilant against a Khmer Rouge return to power ``or else they will
be the instrument of future massacres.''
   ``The Khmer Rouge must put down their arms in exchange for a
political role,'' he said.
</TEXT>
