<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Powell     11-08 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Powell,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Powell Says It's Too Soon To Judge Gorbachev</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's national security adviser,
paraphrasing one of Vice President George Bush's campaign phrases,
said Tuesday it is uncertain whether Mikhail Gorbachev's reform
policies will ``lead to a kinder, gentler Soviet Union.''
   In a speech prepared for delivery to the American Stock Exchange
Conference on U.S. Perspectives, Lt. Gen. Colin L. Powell said the
United States may applaud the Soviet leader's appraisal of his
country's problems but ``must nevertheless reserve judgment on both
his economic goals and how he intends to achieve them.''
   ``It is the failure of past Soviet policies _ because there was
effective resistance to their aggression _ that led the Soviets to
reassess those policies,'' Powell said.
   ``Will perestroika, to paraphrase words used in our election
campaign, lead to a kinder, gentler Soviet Union?'' he asked. ``What
advice should the U.S. government give its businessmen who wish to
compete in the Soviet Union?''
   ``These are tough questions,'' he said. ``We cannot forget that
our overall relationship continues to be both competitive and
adversarial. This is unlikely to change within our lifetimes.''
   While the Soviet leaders ``are still Leninists, who think very
much in political terms ... it should be possible _ and may even be
desirable _ to improve economic relations,'' Powell said.
   Nevertheless, he said, ``a system of centralized state control
and planning is inconsistent with both vigorous entrepreneurship and
political freedom.''
   ``Even under perestroika, the Soviets have recognized this truth
only partially,'' Powell said.
   ``It is wrong to think that economic relations by themselves will
moderate Soviet foreign policy,'' he added.
   Powell took issue with what he called ``a groundswell of opinion
that says `help Gorbachev _ sell him whatever he needs'.''
   ``The Soviet Union shows no evidence as yet of changing its basic
military force structure, its emphasis on expanding and modernizing
its weapons systems, or its aggressive, illegal program for
acquiring strategic technologies,'' he said.
   ``Until the Soviets can establish convincingly that it has made
significant changes in these areas, it is not in our interest to
change our policy.''
   ``Some officials seem to be suggesting that we might even have an
obligation to help ensure the success of perestroika,'' the national
security adviser said.
   However, he said, it might be decades before the West has firm
evidence that Gorbachev's policies will ``lead to a more open,
peaceful and democratic society.''
   ``Until we do, those whose legitimate business it is to make
profits through international trade will have to recognize national
security guidelines,'' he said.
   Asked whether he believes Gorbachev aims at world domination by
the Soviet Union, Powell said, ``As a personal matter, I don't think
he does that. I thin he is fully committed to a political philosophy
that has that as its original and continuing goal, but I think it's
a goal that he knows is not achievable.''
   He said one of his major recommendations to the new
administration will be to seek more economic and security aid funds
for countries of Central and South America and for African
countries, principally below the Sahara.
   ``I am going to list it in my transition notes as a number one
item for the next administration to engage the Congress on,'' he
said.
   Asked whether he foresaw resumption of diplomatic relations with
Cuba, he said, ``Not in the near future. Not without significant
change in the nature of the regime.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
