<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SSGuard     11-08 0172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SS Guard,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Moves To Strip Citizenship of Man Accused of Hiding Nazi Past</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department on Tuesday moved to
strip U.S. citizenship from an Illinois man for concealing his
alleged service as an armed SS guard at a Nazi concentration camp in
World War II.
   The department instituted denaturalization proceedings against
Michael Schmidt, 65, of Lincolnwood in U.S. District Court in
Chicago.
   The department's complaint said Schmidt hid from U.S. immigration
authorities when he came to this country in 1952 his membership
during the war in the SS Death's Head Battalion. It said he hid the
activities from authorities again in 1968 when he applied for U.S.
citizenship.
   Schmidt served at the Sachsenhausen concentration camp in
Oranienberg, Germany, the scene of executions and grotesque
pseudo-medical experiments on Jews, Slavs and political prisoners,
Neal Sher, director of the department's Office of Special
Investigations, said in a statement.
   Thirty Nazis have been stripped of U.S. citizenship as a result
of investigations by the Justice Department's Nazi-hunting unit.
</TEXT>
