<1ST_LINE>r i AM-LiteraryPrize     11-08 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Literary Prize,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rushdie Wins Literary Prize for Book Moslems Denounced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salman Rushdie's novel ``Satanic Verses,'' banned
as blasphemous in India and some Arab countries, won the Whitbread
literary prize Tuesday.
   ``We knew about the controversy but we didn't take any notice of
it and we judged the novel on literary merit only,'' said John
Hitchin, one of three judges.
   Hitchin, novelist Fay Weldon and literary editor Nicholas
Shakespeare of the London Daily Telegraph chose the novel from a
list of 80 for the prize, which carries an award of $2,650.
   The novel is named for verses the prophet Mohammed removed from
the Koran, the holy book of Islam, on grounds they were inspired by
Satan.
   Rushdie, 41, was born in Bombay and has won prizes for earlier
novels, including ``Midnight's Children'' in 1981.
   He said Tuesday he had received death threats from Moslems when
``Satanic Verses'' was published in September.
   ``I hope the prime minister of India, Rajiv Gandhi, is
listening,'' Rushdie said. ``I'm still optimistic that the ban will
be lifted and every bit helps. This prize certainly will.''
   Hitchin, manager of a bookstore chain, said in a telephone
interview: ``There have been protests in our shops by Moslems. We
have had threats of boycotts, picketing and arson.''
   He described the novel as ``remarkable and totally exceptional,
with wonderful passages about Asian communities in London. There's
nothing blasphemous in it against any religion.''
   Ms. Weldon, who announced the winner in a ceremony at
Whitbread's, a brewing company, called the novel an ``extraordinary
outburst of literary energy.''
   It is about the conflict of good and evil, represented by two
Indian survivors from an airliner blown up by terrorists. The
survivors take on the attributes of the angel Gabriel and Satan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
