<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Mitchelson     11-08 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Mitchelson,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mitchelson Calls Bar Investigation A `Witch Hunt'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Famed celebrity divorce lawyer Marvin
Mitchelson says a State Bar investigation of his conduct is ``a
witch hunt.''
   The bar is investigating complaints that he files frivolous legal
appeals and mishandles his clients' money.
   ``There is no question this is a witch hunt,'' Mitchelson said
Monday as he emerged from a two-hour mandatory conference with two
bar prosecutors and a referee.
   Mitchelson, 60, gained fame with his landmark ``palimony''
lawsuit on behalf of Michelle Triola Marvin, who sued her former
live-in boyfriend actor Lee Marvin in 1976.
   Mitchelson has since represented many celebrities and the wives
and girlfriends of actors and sports stars. He represented Joan
Collins in her divorce earlier this year from Peter Holm, and he
counseled Carrie Leigh, former playmate to Playboy founder Hugh
Hefner.
   The bar, which said it had more than 20 complaints about
Mitchelson, contends the attorney failed to deposit clients' funds
in trust accounts; charged ``unconscionable'' fees; failed to
perform promised work; lied to a client; and twice improperly asked
a client to withdraw her complaint to the bar over the return of
unearned fees.
   Mitchelson was represented at the meeting by Arthur Margolis, who
said Mitchelson will face a disciplinary hearing, probably in
January, since the allegations were not resolved at the conference.
</TEXT>
