<1ST_LINE>d p AM-ELN--Kentucky     11-08 0129</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ELN--Kentucky,0134</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Wins Heavily Democratic State</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush won Kentucky's nine electoral
votes Tuesday, continuing the state's Republican habits in
presidential elections despite the Democrats' 2-1 edge in
registration.
   With 47 percent of precincts reporting, Bush had 353,706 votes or
57 percent and Michael Dukakis had 262,536 votes or 43 percent.
   The Massachusetts governor was hurt by his liberal image in
Kentucky, especially on the issues of gun control and crime, while
Bush benefited from President Reagan's popularity.
   Kentucky has gone Republican in five of the last seven
presidential elections.
   The only statewide contest to generate interest was a proposal to
lift the constitutional ban on a lottery.
   All four Democrats and three Republicans in the state's House
delegation appeared headed for re-election.
</TEXT>
