<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 1911EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     11-08 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Say Soviet Moves May Have More Political Than Military Significance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's deployment of new
weapons in Afghanistan and the delay of its troop withdrawal may
have more political than military significance, Western diplomatic
sources said Tuesday.
   The diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
Soviets appeared to be pressing for a political solution of the war
while trying to boost the morale of beleaguered Afghan communists
with a ``wonder weapon.''
   Soviet forces on Nov. 1 rolled two SS-1 Scud-B missiles on their
massive launchers through the streets of Kabul, the Afghan capital.
It was the first time they had been seen there.
   Rebel and Western sources had reported a few days earlier the
deployment of new Soviet MiG-27 fighter-bombers in western
Afghanistan.
   Last Friday the Soviet first deputy foreign minister, Alexander
Bessmertnykh, said in Moscow that his country had suspended its
military withdrawal because of the ``current political situation in
Afghanistan.''
   But neither he nor other Kremlin officials backed off the Soviet
commitment to complete the withdrawal by Feb. 15.
   The Soviet Union agreed under a U.N.-mediated accord in April to
remove its more than 100,000 combat troops from Afghanistan between
May 15, 1988, and Feb. 15, 1989. U.N. observers said the Soviets met
their promise to withdraw half of the force by Aug. 15 but that no
major units have left since then.
   ``The Soviet announcement ... was not a surprise,'' said one
diplomatic source in Islamabad.
   ``There has been no evidence on the ground for preparation of
further withdrawal for nearly three months now. The announcement
probably has more political than military significance.''
   Another diplomatic source said the remaining Soviet troops could
be evacuated in a matter of weeks.
   The Soviet Union sent troops into Afghanistan in December 1979 to
help the Marxist government battle anti-communist rebels.
   About nine Scud missiles reportedly have been fired in
Afghanistan since Nov. 1 but there have been no reports of major
damage.
   The Western sources said the missiles, with a range of 100-175
miles, are not suited for guerrilla warfare.
   One source said the Scud ``was designed as a nuclear delivery
vehicle ... (and) is not a precision weapon. The purpose of Scud
seems to be to bolster the morale of the regime with a wonder
weapon.''
   Afghanistan's official news media said the Afghan army acquired
the missiles and new jet fighters to counter increases in U.S. and
Pakistani arms deliveries to the rebels.
   Western diplomats said the latest developments reflect a
worsening political and military situation for the Afghan government.
   One said he saw the developments ``more as a political maneuver,
designed to foster a political settlement, than as a prelude to a
Soviet decision not to withdraw from Afghanistan.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
