<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Haiti     11-08 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Ex-Wife, Housekeepers in Paul's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Police said Tuesday they have
arrested the ex-wife, maid and gardener of Jean-Claude Paul, the
former army colonel who died over the weekend after eating a bowl of
soup.
   Col. Georges Valcin, the Port-au-Prince police chief, said the
three suspects would be held for questioning until the circumstances
of Paul's death were clarified. No charges had been lodged as of
late Tuesday.
   Paul, a 29-year army veteran who until his forced retirement in
September was one of Haiti's most powerful commanders, died Sunday
at his surburban Fermathe home. Paul had been under indictment in
the United States on drug charges.
   Initial reports said Paul, 49, died of a heart attack, but a
family friend speculated he was poisoned.
   Radio Metropole, an independent station, reported Tuesday that
the leftover soup was sent to a Miami laboratory for analysis. It
did not say which laboratory.
   Paul's brother, Antonio, an auto mechanic, said in an interview
Tuesday with independent Radio Metropole that his brother died one
hour after eating a bowl of soup for lunch.
   He did not speculate on the cause of death, but said Paul
appeared in good health before the meal. Afterwards, Paul complained
that ``since I drank that soup my body feels stiff,'' Antonio Paul
said. He said his brother went to bed and had severe convulsions
before dying in his arms.
   Radio stations reported Tuesday that Mireille Delinois, twice
divorced from Paul and mother of his 13-year-old son, was arrested
along with an unidentified maid and gardener at Paul's residence. It
was believed the couple, who had divorced, were living together at
the time of Paul's death.
   Ms. Delinois initially was under police protection for fear of
reprisals from Paul's relatives, but was arrested Monday, Radio
Metropole said.
   In March, a federal grand jury in Miami indicted Paul on three
charges of conspiring to import 220 pounds of cocaine into the
United States. Ms. Delinois and Antonio Paul were named in the same
indictment.
   Federal authorities had sought to put Paul on trial, but the
United States and Haiti have no extradition treaty.
   An autopsy on Paul's body was performed Monday at a state-run
morgue. Valcin, the capital's police chief, said Tuesday that the
results would be made public within 48 hours.
   A government official said Paul's funeral was tentatively set for
Thursday.
   Haiti's new military leader, Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril, fired Paul
on Sept. 30 in a purge of repressive commanders who served under Lt.
Gen. Henri Namphy.
   Avril replaced Namphy as president in a Sept. 17 coup that was
led by rank-and-file officers demanding democratic reforms and an
end to state-sponsored violence.
   Paul was commander of the Dessalines Barracks, the most powerful
and brutal unit in Haiti's 7,000-member army, and was linked to the
Tonton Macoutes, the dreaded private police of the 29-year Duvalier
dictatorship.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
