<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Army 1stLd-Writethru a0636 11-08 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Army, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0636,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Raps Army For Conditions At Tent Prison</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th pvs `In the occupied ...' UPDATING
with call for general strike and includes death toll. PICK up 5th:
The Supreme Court... Subs 16th: `In Taibe...' with 1 graf UPDATING
with one Arab also injured and 13 arrested.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's Supreme Court criticized the army
Tuesday for overcrowding at its main prison for Palestinian
activists but rejected claims that detainees were being held in
violation of international law.
   In the Arab village of Taibe in northern Israel, residents
angered by the demolition of 15 houses built without permits threw
firebombs and stones at police who fired tear gas, the Itim news
agency said.
   It was the first serious riot by Israeli Arabs since January
protests in solidarity with the 11-month uprising of their
Palestinian brethren in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   In the occupied territories, Israeli soldiers shot and wounded 12
Palestinians, including a 16-year-old who was in serious condition
with a plastic bullet in the head, Arab hospital officials said. The
army confirmed seven wounded in clashes, but did not provide details.
   Underground Palestinian leaders called for a general strike in
the occupied lands Wednesday to mark the beginning of the 12th month
of the uprising. At least 309 Palestinians and 11 Israelis have been
killed since the uprising began last Dec. 8.
   The Supreme Court rejected an appeal by 14 Palestinians from the
occupied territories held at the Ketziot tent prison in Israel's
southern Negev Desert.
   The detainees had argued they were being held illegally because
Geneva conventions on human rights bar the transfer of prisoners
across borders.
   About 1,700 prisoners are at Ketziot, including 1,558 detained
for up to six months without trial in administrative detention.
   The United States has criticized administrative detention as a
violation of due process.
   In a 45-page ruling, Chief Justice Meir Shamgar singled out
administrative detentions, noting 28 percent of administrative
detentions have been overturned on appeal.
   ``Negating freedom without the approval of a judicial authority
is ... a drastic and serious step which the law allows only where
there are essential ... security concerns,'' he wrote.
   Shamgar also appeared to criticize Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin
for scrapping a requirement in January that administrative detainees
be seen by a judge within 96 hours of their arrest.
   Detainees have the right to appeal detention orders, but urged
the army to ensure that appeals are heard within three weeks of
arrest.
   Shamgar, who toured the Ketziot in August, wrote that complaints
about overcrowding were justified.
   The justices found 28 men into a tent at Ketziot where inmates
were forced to sleep pushed against each other with no room for
personal belongings.
   The court decision was expected to have little impact because the
army said the number of prisoners has been sharply reduced in recent
weeks.
   In Taibe, Arabs threw firebombs and stones at hundreds of police
who responded with tear gas. Two police officers and an Arab were
injured and 13 people were detained, Israel radio reported.
   Taibe residents went on strike Tuesday to protest Monday's house
demolitions.
   In the West Bank shantytown of Jiftlic, the army bulldozed about
a dozen shacks of Palestinian migrant workers in retaliation for a
stabbing attack in which an Israeli soldier was killed by an Arab
laborer Monday, the army said. About 100 people were left homeless,
Arab reports said.
   Jiftlic is about 25 miles northeast of Jerusalem.
   In Haifa, police detained a 27-year-old American Jewish woman who
tried to smuggle weapons into the country, Israel radio reported. It
described the woman as a U.S. citizen who had an apartment in
Jerusalem.
   The woman, whose name was not released, was detained on Monday
after tax authorities found two Soviet-designed Kalashnikov assault
rifles, a pistol and ammunition in her luggage, it said.
   The woman claimed she needed the weapons for self-defense, the
radio said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
