<HEAD>Bitter U.S. House Race Highlight in Georgia; Bush Takes State</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Rep. Pat Swindall fought to save his
political career Tuesday as George Bush captured all 12 electoral
votes in Georgia, the state where the Democrats nominated Michael
Dukakis.
   With 13 percent of the precincts counted, Bush had 75,278 votes,
or 56 percent, to Dukakis' 58,133 votes, or 44 percent. Only John
Kennedy in 1960 and native son Jimmy Carter in 1976 and 1980 have
broken the GOP candidates' string of wins in Georgia since 1960.
   Swindall was expected to lose his 4th Congressional District seat
to Democratic challenger Ben Jones, a recovered alcoholic who played
``Cooter'' in TV's the ``Dukes of Hazzard'' and narrowly lost to
Swindall in 1986.
   This year's race, called one of the nation's nastiest, was marked
by Swindall's references to Jones' drinking and arrest record, and
Swindall's indictment on federal perjury charges stemming from a
grand jury investigation of drug money-laundering. Jones says he
hasn't had a drink since 1977 and that the arrests date to his
drinking days.
   Democrats hold eight of the state's 10 U.S. House seats.
</TEXT>
