<HEAD>Government Building Fire Forces Transfer Of 1,800 Jail Inmates</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to CORRECT that fire forced transfer of
1,800 inmates, sted 1,600, UPDATES with 36 people treated for smoke
inhalation and inventory to be taken to determine loss of narcotics.
Picks up 7th graf pvs, `The inmates...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire started by a welder's torch in an
evidence storage room at the Los Angeles County Hall of Justice
forced authorities to evacuate the building Tuesday and transfer
1,800 jail inmates.
   No one was seriously injured, but 30 firefighters and six
sheriff's employees were treated at hospitals for smoke inhalation,
said Fire Department spokesman Dean Kathey.
   Sheriff Sherman Block said narcotics, particularly cocaine,
burned in the 45-minute blaze. Authorities will conduct an inventory
of the evidence to determine how much was lost, he said.
   The blaze began in a seventh-floor storage room that contained
documents and narcotics seized as evidence in sheriff's department
investigations, said Vince Marzo, a city fire department spokesman.
   Greg Acevedo, a fire dispatcher, said officials were concerned
that runoff water from the storage room might be contaminated by the
narcotics evidence.
   Heavy, black smoke poured from the building, in the Civic Center
district of government and public buildings.
   An estimated 1,800 county prisoners were housed in the upper six
floors of the 13-story building, which is more than 60 years old,
county officials said.
   The inmates were transferred to the county's main jail, the Men's
Central Jail, a few blocks away, Sheriff Sherman Block said at an
impromptu news conference.
   The sheriff said there was no automatic sprinkler system in the
building, although he noted that fire hoses were installed on each
floor.
   The building was originally the county's main justice building,
holding jail, courts and law enforcement offices. Now, courts are in
other buildings and the hall is used primarily as headquarters of
the sheriff's department and a jail for short-term prisoners.
   The building shares a busy intersection with City Hall, the
Criminal Justice building and the U.S. District Courthouse.
</TEXT>
