<HEAD>Dukakis Wins Democratic Bastion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis won the District of Columbia's
three electoral votes Tuesday with a wide margin over Republican
George Bush.
   With 100 percent of the precincts counted, Dukakis had 75,494
votes or 84 percent and Bush had 14,564 or 16 percent.
   The Democratic candidate had piled up big majorities among the
overwhelmingly black voting population in each of the last five
presidential elections since residents gained the right to vote in
national contests in 1961.
   For example, Walter Mondale received 85 percent of the vote in
1984, while he was trounced nationally by President Reagan.
   Walter Fauntroy, the city's non-voting delegate to Congress,
appeared on the way to easily retain his seat. The Democrat, a black
minister and veteran of the civil rights movement, had only token
opposition to his bid for a 10th term.
