<HEAD>Dole Says Quayle Fine But Bush Could Have Found More Able Person</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole said Tuesday
night he hasn't changed his opinion that George Bush could have
found a more qualified running mate, but he also said Dan Quayle
would be a good vice president.
   After the Bush-Quayle ticket was sealed at the Republican
National Convention last summer, Dole said of the Indiana senator:
``You could find better qualified people.''
   In an interview on CBS Tuesday night, Dole said, ``I didn't say
anything critical of Dan Quayle. He's an outstanding young man. But,
let's face it, if you're looking for the ablest person, I assume
that George Bush could have found others.''
   ``But Dan Quayle has done a good job. He's going to be a good
vice president,'' he added.
   Dole, R-Kan., had been on Bush's short list of possible running
mates after his own bid for the GOP presidential nomination failed.
   On another subject, the Senate Republican leader said on NBC
Tuesday night that the deficit and long-term health care will be at
the top of Congress' agenda next year.
   He said Bush's promise not to raise taxes may be difficult to
keep if that means ruling out all revenue sources.
   ``My view is that we don't have to touch tax rates on individuals
or corporations. But when you rule out everything _ user fees,
excise taxes, any kind of a tax that might even support a program _
that's going to be difficult to do.''
   ``But George Bush has said, `No new taxes.' I'll be willing to
help him in that effort, and we'll see what the Democrats have to
say,'' Dole said.
</TEXT>
