<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evan Bayh became the first Democrat in 20
years to win the Indiana governorship, but Sen. Daniel Quayle's home
state voted solidly for Republican George Bush in the presidential
race Tuesday.
   Two-term Republican Sen. Richard Lugar also was re-elected.
   Bayh, the 32-year-old son of former Sen. Birch Bayh, defeated
two-term Republican Lt. Gov. John Mutz. With 60 percent of the
precincts reporting, Bayh had 622,148 votes, or 53 percent, and Mutz
had 533,771 votes, or 47 percent.
