<2ND_LINE>AM-ELN--North Carolina, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0812,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republican Governor, Bush Win In North Carolina</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with four grafs to UPDATE with Martin re-elected, later
returns. Picks up 5th graf pvs `Martin, 52....'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Jim Martin on Tuesday became the first
Republican chief executive ever re-elected in North Carolina, and
Vice President George Bush carried the state.
   Martin defeated Democratic Lt. Gov. Bob Jordan, who charged the
governor with presiding over an unethical and incompetent
administration.
   With 31 percent of the precincts reporting, Martin had 304,056,
or 57 percent, and Jordan had 232,926, or 43 percent.
   Bush defeated Democrat Michael Dukakis for the state's 13
electoral votes. Bush had 311,277, or 59 percent, and Dukakis had
212,861, or 41 percent.
   Martin, 52, is a former college chemistry professor and six-term
congressman. Jordan, 56, is a millionaire lumber company executive
who served four terms in the state Senate.
   In the hottest congressional race, Rep. Howard Coble, a
Republican from Greensboro, faced a stiff challenge by former state
legislator Tom Gilmore, a Democrat. Coble won a second term in 1986
by 79 votes in one of the nation's most volatile districts. The
state currently is represented by eight Democrats and three
Republicans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
