<DOCNO> AP881108-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 2129EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d p AM-ELN--Vermont     11-08 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ELN--Vermont,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jeffords Poised to Move to Senate, Sanders Bidding for House Seat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Rep. James Jeffords easily
captured the seat of retiring Sen. Robert Stafford on Tuesday, while
Bernard Sanders, the socialist mayor of Burlington, was leading in
the race for Jeffords' old seat.
   With 11 percent of the precincts in, Democratic Gov. Madeleine
Kunin was ahead with 55 percent of the vote over state legislator
Michael Bernhardt, and seemed headed for a third two-year term as
Vermont's first woman governor.
   In the presidential race for Vermont's three electoral votes,
Republican George Bush had 12,895 votes, or 51 percent, to 12,323
votes, or 49 percent, for Michael Dukakis.
   Jeffords had 17,582 votes, or 71 percent, to 7,058 votes, or 29
percent, for Democrat William Gray, a former U.S. attorney making
his first run for statewide office. Jeffords had been heavily
favored.
   Sanders, running as an independent, was making strong showing in
some of the state's largest communities and holding his own in some
of the smallest. He had 39 percent of the vote. Republican Peter
Smith, a former lieutenant governor, was second, with 36 percent and
Democrat Paul Poirier was in third with 25 percent.
</TEXT>
