<HEAD>Bush Wins Delaware In Republican Sweep</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with Bush victory.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush won Delaware's
three electoral votes Tuesday, completing a Republican sweep that
returned Gov. Michael Castle and Sen. William Roth to office.
   With 62 percent of the precincts reporting, Bush had 88,255
votes, or 58 percent, while Democrat Michael Dukakis had 64,981
votes, or 42 percent.
   With 71 percent of the precincts in, Castle had 59,812 votes, or
71 percent, to win a landslide over Democrat Jacob Kreshtool, who
had 59,812 votes, or 29 percent.
   Roth had 89,394 votes, or 64 percent, to defeat Democratic Lt.
Gov. S.B. Woo, the nation's highest ranking elected official of
Chinese descent, who had 50,857 votes, or 36 percent.
   The one bright spot for Democrats appeared to be the race for the
state's lone congressional seat, where Rep. Thomas R. Carper
captured 66 percent of the vote in breezing to his fourth term,
defeating Republican challenger James P. Krapf. Carper received
89,975 votes to 45,408 for Krapf.
</TEXT>
