<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 2156EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PalauElection     11-08 0165</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Palau Election,0170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President's Race Still Undecided</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KOROR, Palau (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ngiratkel Etpison held a 108-vote lead over
fellow governor Roman Tmetuchl with up to 1,400 votes still to be
counted in this western Pacific island nation's presidential
election.
   Etpison had garnered 2,127 votes to Tmetuchl's 2,019 in the
seven-way election conducted Nov. 2, election officals said Tuesday.
   President Thomas Remengesau was third with 1,549 votes.
   Remengesau took office after President Lazarus Salii was found
dead at his home Aug. 20 with a gunshot wound to the head. A
government probe determined the wound was self-inflicted.
   Salii, 51, was the second elected president of the tiny island
republic, and the second to die violently.
   Salii was elected in August 1985 to succeed Haruo I. Remeliik,
who was assassinated two months earlier. Three Palau men convicted
in connection with Remeliik's death were acquitted on appeal.
   Meanwhile, in the separate election for vice president, Sen.
Kuniwo Nakamura led Rep. Kazuo Aganuma 4,654 votes to 2,947 votes.
</TEXT>
