<1ST_LINE>d p AM-ELN--Maine     11-08 0165</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ELN--Maine,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic Sen. Mitchell Wins Re-election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Sen. George J. Mitchell won a
second term by a landslide Tuesday, and Vice President George Bush,
who has a Kennebunkport summer home, was running nearly even for the
state's four electoral votes.
   With 11 percent of the precincts in, Mitchell had 23,821, or 85
percent, to 4,293, or 15 percent of the vote for Jasper S. Wyman, a
former Democratic state legislator turned Republican. Wyman, who
heads the conservative Maine Christian Civic League, challenged
Mitchell after more established GOP figures declined.
   In a state that has voted Republican in all but three
presidential elections in the past century, Bush carried a lead of
10 percentage points in opinion polls. In the election, Bush had
13,490 votes, or 49 percent, to 13,790 votes, or 51 percent, for
Democrat Michael Dukakis.
   Both congressional incumbents were expected to win re-election _
Democrat Joseph E. Brennan, a former two-term governor, and
Republican Olympia J. Snowe.
</TEXT>
