<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 2234EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ELN--GovernorsRdp 9thLd-Writethru a0914 11-08 1016</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ELN--Governors Rdp, 9th Ld - Writethru, a0914,1035</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Oust GOP in Indiana, W.Va. Statehouses</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with Republican winning in New Hampshire and latest
figures; COMBINES pvs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE BROWN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Evan Bayh, the 32-year-old son of a former U.S. senator, was
elected Indiana's first Democratic governor in 20 years and the
youngest governor in the nation Tuesday, while a newcomer ousted
West Virginia's GOP warhorse, Gov. Arch Moore.
   Democrats also fought to oust Republican governors in Rhode
Island and Utah, while Montana offered the GOP its best hope of
retaking the office there as voters in 12 states filled their top
office.
   With 71 percent of the vote counted, Bayh, who as the son of
former Sen. Birch E. Bayh is heir to a popular name in Indiana
politics, defeated Republican Lt. Gov. John M. Mutz, 761,768 votes
or 53 percent to 672,003 votes or 47 percent.
   In West Virginia, Gaston Caperton, a wealthy insurance executive
seeking his first political office, denied the 65-year-old Moore an
unprecedented fourth term in a state with a slumping economy.
Caperton, 48, styled himself an outsider with a businessman's
approach to the job and portrayed Moore as an old-school politician.
   With 48 percent of the vote counted, Caperton led 157,940 votes
or 60 percent to 103,621 votes or 40 percent for Moore.
   In scoring the Democrats' first victory in an Indiana
gubernatorial race since 1964, Bayh overcame a GOP landslide for
George Bush and Sen. Richard Lugar in vice presidential candidate
Dan Quayle's home state.
   Bayh, Indiana secretary of state, succeeds Robert D. Orr, who at
70 is the nation's second oldest governor. The youngest U.S.
governor in office is John R. McKernan Jr. of Maine, who was not up
for re-election Tuesday. He is 40.
   Democrats held 27 of the 50 governorships and hoped for a net
gain Tuesday of two to four seats, which would put the party in good
position to influence the state congressional redistricting battles
after the 1990 census.
   Nine incumbents _ six Republicans and three Democrats _ were on
the ballot. Orr is barred by law from a third term; Montana Democrat
Ted Schwinden and New Hampshire Republican John Sununu are retiring.
   In Rhode Island, businessman Bruce Sundlun began his second
effort to unseat Gov. Edward DiPrete as a distant underdog, but
turned the race into a cliffhanger by pressing allegations of
unethical conduct against the incumbent. Utah Gov. Norm Bangerter,
stigmatized by a big tax increase, battled back and reached Election
Day in a tight race against Democrat Ted Wilson, former mayor of
Salt Lake City. Independent Merrill Cook, who ran on a
tax-limitation platform, battled for the support of conservatives.
   Montana's Thomas Judge, Democratic governor in 1973-81, battled
former GOP state Sen. Stan Stephens over how best to revive the
state's farm and railroad economy.
   In other races:
   DELAWARE _ Republican Gov. Michael N. Castle trounced Democrat
Jacob Kreshtool, a retired labor lawyer and political newcomer. With
86 percent of the vote, Castle had 139,044 votes or 71 percent, to
Kreshtool's 57,173 votes or 29 percent.
   MISSOURI _ Republican John Ashcroft was re-elected by a
landslide. With 45 percent of the vote in, Ashcroft received 339,721
votes or 61 percent to 217,958 votes or 39 percent for Democratic
state Rep. Betty Hearnes, wife of a former governor.
   NEW HAMPSHIRE _ Republican Judd Gregg, a congressman and son of a
former governor, defeated Paul McEachern, a lawyer and fierce
opponent of the Seabrook nuclear plant who nearly rode the issue
into the governor's office two years ago. With 42 percent of the
vote counted, Gregg received 82,508 votes or 62 percent to
McEachern's 50,291 votes or 38 percent.
   NORTH CAROLINA _ Republican Jim Martin was re-elected over Lt.
Gov. Bob Jordan, a Democrat. With 64 of the vote counted, Martin had
700,730 votes or 56 percent to Jordan's 546,273 votes or 44 percent.
   NORTH DAKOTA _ Gov. George Sinner expected a landslide victory
over Republican Leon Mallberg, a businessman making his first run
for statewide office.
   VERMONT _ Democrat Madeleine Kunin, the state's first woman
governor, was elected to a third two-year term. With 33 percent of
the vote counted, Kunin received 26,787 votes or 54 percent to
22,423 votes or 45 percent for House GOP Leader Michael Bernhardt.
   WASHINGTON _ Democratic Gov. Booth Gardner expected a landslide
victory over Republican state Rep. Bob Williams.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The GOP hoped a big Bush-Quayle victory in Quayle's home state
would help pull Mutz through in Indiana, where Bayh was favored by a
margin that had narrowed dramatically in the closing days of the
race. It was Quayle who ousted the elder Bayh from the Senate in
1980.
   Mutz claimed credit for the state's prosperity and argued that
Bayh was too inexperienced and saw the governor's office as ``one
more jewel for his political crown.'' The Democrat argued that Mutz
should be held responsible for the two biggest tax increases in
state history and that he negotiated deals that gave away too many
economic development incentives to foreign companies.
   The coattail effect of the Republican national ticket resulted in
a net loss of five Democratic governorships in 1980 and one in 1984,
said Charles H. Dolan Jr., executive director of the Democratic
Governors' Association.
   In West Virginia, Caperton, an insurance executive who portrayed
the election as a referendum on state's slumping economy, led by
double digits throughout the campaign against Moore, who sought an
unprecedented fourth term in predominantly Democratic West Virginia.
   In Rhode Island, Sundlun, a communications executive who lost to
DiPrete by a landslide in 1986, robbed the governor of an early,
commanding lead in the polls by raising questions about DiPrete's
private business deals, alleged favoritism in the awarding of state
contracts and the hiring of the ex-wife of a reputed mobster for a
state job. DiPrete stressed the state's economic recovery.
   The Bangerter campaign in Utah also counted on a strong showing
by Bush. The governor's comeback from an early, 30-point deficit in
the polls largely coincided with Bush's surge since the Republican
National Convention in August.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
