<HEAD>Sen. Bob Byrd Wins Sixth Term, Gov. Moore Loses Bid for Fourth Term</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to update with Dukakis winning, updated
figures.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insurance executive Gaston Caperton
ousted three-term Gov. Arch Moore as Democrats swept West Virginia
on Tuesday.
   Michael Dukakis won the state's six electoral votes and Sen.
Robert Byrd handily won a sixth term.
   With 48 percent of the precincts counted, Byrd, who intends to
step down as Senate majority leader, had 173,807 votes or 68 percent
and freshman GOP state Sen. Jay Wolfe had 82,854 or 32 percent.
   In the governor's race, with 48 percent counted, Caperton had
157,940 votes or 60 percent and Moore had 103,621 votes or 40
percent.
   Dukakis had 147,038 votes or 56 percent with 48 percent counted,
and Bush had 115,40-3 votes or 44 percent.
   Caperton, a Charleston insurance executive seeking his first
political office, spent $2.1 million to win a seven-way primary and
more than $1.7 million against Moore.
   The state faces high unemployment and has had to borrow $80
million to keep operating this year.
   All four of the state's Democratic congressman were returned to
office.
</TEXT>
