<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881108-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 2300EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ELN--ElectionRdp 13th-1stadd a0942 11-08 0746</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ELN--Election Rdp, 13th-1st add, a0942,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New with Burdick; Chafee; Gregg.</NOTE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: South Carolinian.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush, who first ran for the White House a decade ago and lost in
the 1980 primaries to Reagan, awaited the nation's verdict in
Houston. He said ``no predictions'' as he voted earlier in the day,
and described and described the election as ``a referendum on a
philosophy, a way of life,'' and then awaited returns with family
members in his hotel suite.
   Dukakis campaigned even as the vote totals mounted. ``It's a
fight to the finish, a cliffhanger,'' he said. ``It reminds me of
1960,'' when John F. Kennedy and Richard M. Nixon battled down to
the finish, Dukakis said before concluding a final round of TV
interviews fed back to the battleground states.
   But as the night wore on, it looked less and less like 1960 _ and
more like four of the five previous White House elections that ended
in Republican victory.
   Bentsen said on ABC that Republicans ``did a job on Michael
Dukakis with the negative ads....And they distorted his record, to a
remarkable degree.'' Bentsen was a cinch to win a new term in the
Senate from Texas no matter which side claimed the White House.
   Quayle wanted the last laugh after being on the receiving end of
endless Democratic jokes and sharp public scrutiny. Dole wasn't the
only Republican who expressed concern that the 41-year-old Indiana
senator was not seasoned enough to be vice president.
   But for all the controversy Quayle provoked, election-place polls
suggested this election held to form, with the running mates swaying
few votes.
   Democrats were renewing majorities in both the House and Senate
that will comprise the 101st Congress. The two parties vied for
gains in 12 gubernatorial contests, races that held significance for
a nationwide redistricting that takes place after the 1990 census.
   Democrats held a 54-46 edge in the old Senate and an overwhelming
255-177 advantage in the old House, with three vacant seats.
   Democratic senators winning re-election included Edward Kennedy
in Massachusetts; Paul Sarbanes in Maryland; James Sasser of
Tennessee; Daniel Patrick Moynihan in New York and Don Riegle in
Michigan, Howard Metzenbaum in Ohio, Jeff Bingaman in New Mexico and
Quentin Burdick in North Dakota. Frank Lautenberg fought off a
spirited challenge from Pete Dawkins to hold his New Jersey seat.
   Robert Byrd of West Virginia also won, as did Maine's George
Mitchell _ one of three men who hope to succeed him as Senate
Majority Leader.
   Republican senators re-elected were Richard Lugar in Indiana,
John Danforth of Missouri, John Heinz of Pennsylvania, William Roth
in Delaware and John Chafee in Rhode Island.
   There were tougher races, of course.
   Republicans hoped to spring an upset in Montana against John
Melcher and Democrats targeted Malcoln Wallop in Wyoming.
   Democratic millionaire Herbert Kohl led state Sen. Susan
Engeleiter in early returns in Wisconsin. Rep. Mike Lowry battled
former GOP Sen. Slade Gorton for an open Republican seat in
Washington.
   Political pros on both sides agreed the House would live up to
its reputation as a citadel of security for lawmakers seeking
re-election. Dozens of Democrats and Republicans had either no
opposition or only minor party rivals.
   Democratic Speaker Jim Wright of Texas was among them, even
though he is under investigation by the House ethics committee. GOP
Leader Bob Michel of Illinois faced a rematch against his close 1982
rival, G. Douglas Stephens.
   The most powerful among the endangered incumbents was Rep.
Fernand J. St Germain, a 28-year congressional veteran from Rhode
Island under fire for allegedly accepting gifts and trips from
savings and loan industry officials subject to his committee's
jurisdiction.
   Second-term Republican Pat Swindall, under indictment for
perjury, fell to Ben Jones in a rematch of their 1986 Georgia race.
   Most of the mystery surrounding House races concerned the 27 open
seats, 15 held by Republicans and 12 by Democrats.
   Democrats hoped to improve their current 27-23 numerical
superiority in the statehouses, and Bayh and Caperton got them off
to a fast start.
   Republican Gov. Michael Castle won a new term in Delaware. Ditto
Jim Martin in North Carolina and John Ashcroft in Missouri. Judd
Gregg kept the New Hampshire statehouse in Republican hands.
   Madeleine Kunin kept Vermont safely Democratic.
   Reagan, still popular after eight years in the Oval Office, was a
full participant in the Republican campaign effort, crisscrossing
the country for Bush and the GOP congressional candidates.
</TEXT>
