<1ST_LINE>a a PM-ReligionintheNews Adv11   11-08 0814</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Religion in the News, Adv 11,0833</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Fri PMs Nov. 11, or thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Vatican Crackdown Claimed Against Progressive Brazilian Church</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN LEHMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite Vatican denials, theologians
here say Pope John Paul II is out to discipline the predominantly
progressive and independent-minded church in the world's largest
Roman Catholic country.
   Jose Queiroz, a theologian and philosopher at Sao Paulo's
Catholic University, said in an interview ``the Holy See has
embarked on an offensive to force the Brazilian church to follow the
conservative positions he favors.''
   On Oct.19, the Vatican officially denied reports, published in
the Brazilian press, of the existence of a so-called ``conservative
offensive'' against Brazilian bishops considered too progressive.
   The pope repeatedly has stressed he wants the church to
concentrate on its traditional role of spiritual salvation. Queiroz
and other theologians say the pope seeks to curb the largely
left-of-center leaders of Brazil's church.
   The pope recently appointed conservative cardinals to head two
key Brazilian archdioceses. He is reported preparing to pull the rug
out from under one of Brazil's most influential clergymen, the
outspoken and highly progressive archbishop of the city of Sao
Paulo, Cardinal Paulo Evaristo Arns.
   Theologians say the Vatican plans to divide Sao Paulo's huge
archdiocese, the largest in the world. This would open the way for
the appointment of new bishops who would toe the pope's dogmatic
line, and it would undermine Cardinal Arns' influence.
   Also irritating the pope is the growth of the activist liberation
theology in Brazil _ a grass-roots theology based on Jesus' concern
for the poor. It promotes greater social, political and economic
awareness among poor people.
   The Vatican has said there is no place in the church for the
political-religious cocktail promoted by some liberation theologians
and has censured Brazil's leading exponents of that approach, the
Rev. Leonardo Boff and Spanish-born Bishop Pedro Casaldaliga.
   A leading spokesman for the progressive wing of the church, the
Most Rev. Tomas Balduino, bishop of the city of Goias, said in a
telephone interview:
   The Vatican is ``determined to restore the centralized and
authoritarian structure of the church _ a structure which does not
tolerate original thought or any divergence from the traditional
doctrine of saving souls.''
   The Most Rev. Luciano Cabral Duarte, archbishop of the
northeastern city of Aracaju and a conservative, says the church in
Brazil was divided ``between those who remain faithful to the
ecclesiastical institution such as Christ created it, and those who
want a more modern church which would work as a democracy.''
   The second option is not valid ``because the church was never
meant to be a democracy'' Duarte said in a signed opinion column in
the influential conservative newspaper, O Estado de S. Paulo. ``The
apostles were not elected by popular vote. The church is a
hierarchy.''
   Queiroz said, ``The conservative forces in the Vatican are slowly
but surely gaining ground.
   ``This became very clear when the pope named Cardinal Lucas
Moreira Neves as archbishop of (the large northeastern city of)
Salvador and Cardinal Jose Freire Falcao as archbishop of Brasilia
(the capital).''
   He also sees in the rumored carving up of the Arns' archdiocese
of Sao Paul a move to curtail the influence of the progressive wing
of the church in Brazil.
   Arns, an ardent defender of liberation theology and human rights,
currently exercises his influence over an area inhabited by some 15
million people.
   ``According to the Vatican's plan, the archdiocese would be cut
to just five districts concentrated in the city's metropolitan
area,'' Queiroz said.
   ``The rest of greater Sao Paulo, inhabited by the kind of
low-income workers pro-liberation theology forces want to reach,
would be divided into four separate dioceses with their bishops
named by the Vatican.''
   Arns has declined comments on the planned division of his
archdiocese.
   The Most Rev. Boaventura Kloppenburg, bishop of the city of Novo
Hamburgo in the southern state of Rio Grande do Sul and another
recognized conservative, welcomed the division of Sao Paulo's
archdiocese for the same reasons progressives condemned it.
   In a phone interview, he said the Vatican was concerned with
Brazil's liberation theologians ``who refuse to follow the pope's
guidelines and who adopt positions that are irreconcilable with the
official doctrine.''
   Kloppenburg said it was ``evident'' and ``obvious'' that by
naming new conservative cardinals and by splitting up Cardinal Arn's
archdiocese ``the pope will reassert his authority over Brazil's
church.''
   ``The church's goal is to bring about mankind's spiritual
salvation and not, as liberation theology would have it, create a
social consciousness among the people,'' Kloppenburg said.
   Queiroz says, ``There are reactionary forces inside the Vatican
trying to nullify the church's active participation in the social,
economic and political problems of the country. In this sense they
are trying to restrict and police the actions of the progressive
clergy.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Nov. 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
