<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A secret that many churches and
communities prefer to ignore is the shame carried by families of
alcoholics, says a counselor who works with adults whose parents
were alcoholics.
   ``The pain that is hidden in Southern Bapltist congregations
would astound most pastors,'' Sara Hines Martin told a seminar at
Travis Avenue Baptist Church here. ``In families where one of the
parents is alcoholic, the family system is shame-bound.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many American Jews foresee new efforts to stiffen
definitions of ``who is a Jew'' as a result of the recent Israeli
elections, which have given additional leverage to the country's
religious parties.
   ``We strongly urge the leadership of both major parties ... not
to use the Law of Return as a bargaining chip to form a new
coalition,'' says Robert K. Lifton, president of the American Jewish
Congress.
   Orthodox Jewish parties want the law admitting Jews limited in
regard to converts to those converted under Orthodox requirements,
which are stricter than those for Conservative and Reform Jews.
   Lifton says, ``Any action to change this law would be a grave
error, a betrayal of Jewish unity and would certainly alienate the
American Jewish community.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MONTREAT, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evangelist Billy Graham, who turned 70 on
Monday, says people must ``work toward the elimination of all these
arms that are draining the world of its energy and its strength.''
   He has just completed a crusade at Hamilton, Ontario, in which he
told students at McMaster University:
   ``We're spending billions and billons on bombs that will never be
used, and yet millions of people are on the verge of starvation or
are actually starving. We cannot justify that from a Christian point
of view.''
</TEXT>
