incidents, but as state policy.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official of the National Conference of
Catholic Bishops discounts a survey claiming Catholic women have
disproportionately more abortions than Protestant or Jewish women.
   The Rev. John W. Gouldrick, head of the NCCB pro-life offices,
says the survey by the Alan Guttmacher Institute was flawed since it
failed to gauge the degree of church involvement of the women
counted as Catholic.
   He says an investigation into a similar 1981 survey found that
most of the women identified as Catholics actually described
themselves as ``non-practicing'' Catholics or ``ex-Catholics.''
   That survey, like the new one, found that women with no religious
affiliation have the highest abortion rates.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EDINA, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most modern architects don't seem to know
much about what a church should look like, according to leaders of a
conference here that sought to draw more of them into the field.
   ``We have been troubled in recent years by the number of new
church buildings that end up looking more like roller skating rinks
or doughnut shops,'' said officials of a division of the United
Church Board for Homeland Ministries, which sponsored the Nov. 3-6
conference.
</TEXT>
