<1ST_LINE>a i AM-ReligionToday ADV11   11-08 0822</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Today, ADV 11,0839</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, Nov. 11, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Repeat for all needing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Traditionalist Movement Seems Undeterred By Vatican Sanctions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICKENBACH, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four months after Archbishop
Marcel Lefebvre was excommunicated from the Roman Catholic church,
his traditionalist supporters seem largely undeterred by papal
warnings that they will face the same punishment if they do not
break with him.
   The titular head of Lefebvre's St. Pius X Fraternity of Priests
says a total of 15 priests and 18 seminarians _ less than 10 percent
_ have left the movement since the rebel prelate consecrated four
traditionalist bishops June 30 in defiance of the Vatican.
   Lefebvre and his followers say that the church has embarked on a
course of ``auto-destruction'' since the Second Vatican Council of
1962-65. They reject many reforms introduced then, including the
replacement of Latin with the vernacular in the liturgy and
relations with Protestant churches.
   The archbishop argues that he continues to recognize papal
authority but that the consecrations were a legitimate ``emergency''
act to save the church and that therefore the excommunications were
invalid.
   The defections leave 210 priests in the fraternity and 255
students in the fraternity's six theological schools in Australia,
the United States, France, Switzerland, and West Germany, according
to the Rev. Franz Schmidberger.
   ``Percentage-wise, the number who left us is small but every
defection hurts us, of course,'' Schmidberger, who succeded Lefebvre
as superior general of the fraternity in 1984, said in an interview.
``It hurts particularly at a time when we need more and more priests
to help us in our work.''
   That need is growing, he said, because of a growing attendance at
traditionalist services in the churches, chapels and other places of
worship founded by the fraternity.
   ``We estimate that attendance at holy Mass celebrated in our 530
centers worldwide has increased between 5 to 10 percent since the
consecration,'' Schmidberger said.
   ``In some places, like in St. Louis which I visited during a
recent tour of the United States, the increase is even higher, the
local priest told me.''
   Schmidberger said Lefebvre had expected that attendance would
decline by 25 percent while the Vatican had figured that 80 percent
would renounce links with the archbishop should he defy the pope.
   There is no firm figure on the number of Lefebvre's active
supporters, as they do not register. The Vatican estimates the
number at between 60,000 to 80,000. But two years ago, a
pro-Lefebvre petition addressed to the Vatican was backed by 135,000
signatures. Estimates have put sympathizers in the millions.
   The consecration of the four bishops created the first major
schism in the church in more than a century. It resulted in the
automatic excommunication, or expulsion from the church, of Lefebvre
and the four bishops, and of Monsignor Antonio de Castro Mayer, a
Brazilian prelate who assisted Lefebvre in the ceremony at the Swiss
seminary in Econe, birthplace of the fraternity.
   Pope John Paul II, in an apostolic letter made public two days
later, warned Lefebvre's followers that they, too, will be
excommunicated if they stay with him. At the same time, he promised
the church will permit their traditionalist practices if they remain
loyal to Rome.
   A special eight-member commission was set up by the pope to bring
Lefebvre's priests back into the church. A new ``St. Peter's
Fraternity'' features tradionalist liturgy under the Vatican's
auspices.
   But the inauguration of the fraternity's first seminary in West
Germany has run into problems because of reported disagreements
between the superior, the Rev. Joseph Bissig, and the local
hierarchy. Bissig, former head of a Lefebvre seminary, broke with
the archbishop the day after the consecration.
   ``That fraternity will never get off the ground,'' said
Schmidberger. ``These people sit between all chairs.''
   He voiced confidence that the traditionalist movement will
continue to grow. By the end of the year, he said, all four new
bishops will have ordained 15 new priests, in Switzerland, West
Germany, Argentina and Australia, where a seminary opened only
recently. In 1989, about 40 new ordinations are scheduled and the
level of enrollment at the seminaries is unchanged, he said.
   The fraternity's activities are exclusively funded by private
donations, according to Schmidberger. ``We do not benefit from the
church tax. In fact, our followers, for example in Germany and in
some Swiss cantons, pay twice.'' The church tax is collected by
authorities in some countries on behalf of the church from
registered members of religious community.
   Schmidberger, a German national, is also confident that
eventually the Vatican will seek a new dialogue with his fraternity.
He estimates that at least 10 of the 156 members of the College of
Cardinals secretly sympathize with the traditionalists
   ``But we will not take the initiative,'' he said. ``We are not
under time pressure. And we are in a relatively strong position.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Nov. 11</NOTE>
