<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   11-08 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0571</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's largest newsprint maker, pressured by
weak demand and resistance from American newspapers, says it is
reducing and delayint its latest announced price hike.
   Abitibi-Price Inc. of Toronto said Monday it had told its
customers it decided to increase prices for newspaper customers by
$30 to $680 a metric ton effective Feb. 1.
   Last September, Abitibi announced it was raising its newsprint
prices to $695 a metric ton, a 6.9 percent increase, effective Jan
1. Several other manufacturers, including Bowater Inc., the largest
U.S. producer, followed suit.
   But newspaper officials balked, arguing that the price hikes were
unjustified because of weak demand for newsprint stemming partly
from a drop in advertising.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ted Turner has announced the sale of CNN Center
for $170 million, almost three times what he paid for the struggling
office-hotel-shopping complex when he bought it two years ago and
renamed it after his Cable News Network.
   Turner said Monday the complex was purchased by 66 Properties
Inc., a unit of Herrick Co., a real estate investment firm based in
Morristown, N.J.
   Turner will use the proceeds to pay down the massive debt rung up
by the $1.5 billion purchase in 1986 of the MGM film library.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Last week's computer virus attack, the biggest
ever, has caught the attention of leaders in business and government
and should lead to improvements in computer security, according to
several consultants.
   Security consultants said Monday they had received far more
inquiries than usual since the end of last week.
   But they said computer security is a wide-ranging matter that
cannot be solved simply by assigning passwords and installing some
anti-viral software.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maurizio Gucci, an heir of the founder of the
Gucci luxury goods company, has been convicted of attempted tax
fraud and given a $750 fine and a one-year suspended sentence.
   Vittorio Ajello, the lawyer for Gucci, said Monday's decision
means Gucci will regain control of shares that will give him half of
the company.
   Gucci was accused of having arranged the falsification of the
signature on the documents to avoid paying inheritance taxes by
making it appear that his father, Rodolfo, transferred ownership of
the shares before his death in 1983.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. says it has agreed tentatively on a
joint venture with the Italian magazine publisher Arnoldo Mondadori
Editore to publish an Italian edition of Fortune magazine.
   Time and Arnoldo Mondadori said Monday they would each have a
half-interest in the venture, which was expected to produce its
first monthly issue in early 1989 with an initial circulation of
about 50,000.
   It would be the second such joint venture involving a
foreign-language edition of Fortune in Europe. Fortune France was
launched in February as a joint venture of Time and Hachette
Filipacchi, a Paris-based publisher.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices tumbled Monday as investors awaited the outcome of
the presidential election. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
fell 21.16 points to 2,124.64.
   The dollar finished sharply lower. Gold prices rose.
   Bond prices fell.
   Precious metals rose; grains were mostly higher while soybeans
finished lower; livestock and meat were mixed; and energy futures
rose.
</TEXT>
