<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     11-08 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks, Dollar Falls in Advance of Preidential Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Uncertainty about the results of today's presidential election is
keeping the lid on activity in the stock and foreign exchange
markets.
   Stock prices tumbled and the dollar fell in restrained
election-eve dealings on Monday.
   The Dow Jones Industrial average lost 21.16 points to close the
day at 2,124.64. In the broader market, four issues fell for every
one that gained in nationwide trading of New York Stock
Exchange-listed stocks.
   Analysts said investors withdrew from the market early on Monday,
neither buying nor selling, to await the outcome of today's vote.
They said while Wall Street felt relatively certain of a victory by
Republican George Bush, investors were cautious after weekend polls
suggested Democrat Michael Dukakis had narrowed the gap in some
areas.
   Those concerns also were cited for a decline in the dollar
against all major currencies except the Canadian dollar.
   The dollar finished lower in European trading and continued to
drift steadily downward as activity shifted to the United States.
Despite the depth of the currency's drop, trading was quiet.
   In the bond market, prices slipped and interest rates rose.
   Rates also finished at the highest levels in more than three
years at the regular weekly Treasury bill auction.
   The Treasury Department sold $7.2 billion in three-month bills at
an average discount rate of 7.54 percent, up from 7.37 percent last
week. Another $7.2 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average
discount rate of 7.71 percent, up from 7.48 percent last week.
   The rates were the highest since May 13, 1985, when three-month
bills sold for 7.69 percent and six-month bills averaged 7.9 percent.
   Separately, the Federal Reserve said in a new economic report
that Americans took out $1.88 billion more in consumer debt than
they paid off in September, the smallest advance in 10 months.
   The September increase in consumer debt was down from an August
rise of $5.32 billion and was the smallest monthly advance since a
$1.79 billion rise in November 1987.
   While much of the decline in September was traced to weak auto
sales, economists said the pattern of the past several months
indicated consumers had grown more cautious in their buying plans.
   From July through September, consumer debt rose at an annual rate
of 6.75 percent, down significantly from a 10.2 percent growth rate
in the first six months of the year.
</TEXT>
