<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 0058EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Pillsbury Bjt   11-08 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury, Bjt,0679</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Analysts Skeptical Of Pillsbury Plan To Spin Off Burger King</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Analysts say they doubt whether Pillsbury
Co.'s plan to spin off its troubled Burger King subsidiary will
thwart Grand Metropolitan PLC's $5.23 billion hostile takeover bid,
but a judge's ruling may have given the company more time to fight.
   Pillsbury announced Monday morning that it would spin off
Miami-based Burger King as a separate public company owned by
Pillsbury shareholders, under a plan approved by the board of
directors.
   In trading Monday on the New York Stock Exchange, Pillsbury fell
$1.37{ to $59 a share.
   After the market closed, a Delaware judge denied Grand Met's
request Met to block Pillsbury from using its ``poison pill''
takeover defense against the tender offer. Grand Met's takeover bid
was conditioned on the defense being lifted.
   But retired Justice William Duffy sided with Pillsbury in
Delaware Chancery Court. He ruled that the company's directors, 12
of whom are independent of the company, were abiding by their
fiduciary responsibilities in keeping the plan in place.
   Ian Martin, chief of Grand Met's U.S. operations, said his
company has asked Duffy to reconsider his ruling because it did not
take into consideration Pillsbury's plan to spin off Burger King.
   Steve Carnes, a former Pillsbury executive who is an analyst for
Piper Jaffray & Hopwood Inc. in Minneapolis, said Monday's events
favored Pillsbury, but the food and restaurant company's battle
against Grand Met was far from over.
   Carnes and other analysts criticized the Burger King plan. They
said it would weaken the already troubled restaurant chain and
amount to a combined $40 value for shareholders, compared with the
$60 in cash Grand Met has offered for each share of Pillsbury common
stock.
   Under the plan, Pillsbury said it would distribute one share of
Burger King common stock for each share of Pillsbury common stock,
payable on Jan. 27 or earlier for shareholders of record on Dec. 2.
   The company also said Burger King would declare special dividends
of cash and securities payable after the spin-off. The size of the
special dividends was not disclosed.
   Pillsbury has the right to cancel the dividends, but the company
said the payout would provide ``immediate value to shareholders
while at the same time allowing Burger King to grow and develop
values in the future.''
   Pillsbury's board also directed management to continue exploring
other alternatives for boosting shareholder values.
   Martin said Pillsbury's plan is ``vague and does not contain
sufficient information to evaluate the separate Pillsbury and Burger
King companies.''
   He also said debt resulting from the plan would weaken both
companies, possibly leading to large-scale layoffs, plant closings
and a reduction in philanthropy.
   Carnes and analyst Malcom Knapp, who heads his own firm in New
York, said the debt the plan would add to an already troubled Burger
King would make a turnaround of the world's second-largest
restaurant chain less likely.
   ``It's a desperate thing,'' Knapp said. ``It doesn't make any
sense.''
   Burger King accounts for about one-third of Pillsbury's sales and
about two-thirds of its profits but has not done well recently. In
the fiscal year ended May 31, the chain's pre-tax profits plunged
more than 50 percent from a year earlier, to $48.2 million.
   The company's stagnant sales have been blamed partly on
inconsistent advertising. Burger King dumped its advertising agency,
J. Walter Thompson, last fall after an association of 11 years.
   Burger King Chairman Jerry W. Levin acknowledged the marketing
problems but praised the new business arrangement at a news
conference in Miami, where the chain is based.
   ``We think it makes us best equipped to create a full turnaround
for Burger King,'' he said.
   Separately, Pillsbury Chairman Philip Smith said the company's
remaining operations will be streamlined, with its well-known brands
becoming its principal business. Products included in Pillsbury's
packaged foods unit are Green Giant vegetables and Haagen-Dazs ice
cream, among others.
</TEXT>
