<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BurgerKing Bjt   11-08 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burger King, Bjt,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second-Largest Fast-Food Chain To Be Reborn As Independent Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRACY FIELDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co.'s proposal to spin off its Burger King
fast-food business to shareholders would relieve it of a prized
business that has caused Pillsbury problems with its weakening
earnings.
   Pillsbury announced the planned spinoff on Monday, as part of its
strategy to try to thwart a $5.23 billion hostile buyout bid by
British conglomerate Grand Metropolitan PLC.
   Jerry W. Levin, Burger King chairman, told a news conference
Monday that the plan marked a positive change for the chain, which
he said apparently had suffered from marketing problems and
inability to achieve consistency in all its 5,578 outlets.
   ``It is clear we're going to have to change. There should be some
corporate streamlining,'' he said.
   Burger King will be adding departments to replace corporate
services formerly provided by Pillsbury even as it eliminates other
positions to tighten its operation, Levin said.
   Analysts say Burger King, which accounts for about one-third of
Pillsbury's sales and two-thirds of its profits, is a prime example
of the parent company's recent problems with some of its food
operations.
   Since Pillsbury took over the Miami-based chain in 1967, it has
had five chairmen and eight presidents. Most recently, Charles S.
Olcott resigned the presidency last month after two years.
   William Maguire, an analyst with Merrill Lynch & Co. in New York,
said Olcott ``wasn't a marketing man when they needed a marketing
man badly.''
   Burger King's pre-tax profits were down more than 50 percent in
the year ended May 31, to $48.2 million, from $119.2 million in the
previous year.
   Its systemwide sales rose 7 percent to $5.40 billion in the year
ended May 31, but net sales _ which includes sales only at
company-owned restaurants as well as royalties and fees from
franchised restaurants _ dropped 5.4 percent to $1.84 billion from
$1.95 billion the previous year.
   Average sales per store also fell 1 percent to just over $1
million.
   The company concedes that part of the problem has been
inconsistent marketing.
   Burger King dumped its advertising agency, J. Walter Thompson,
last fall after an association of 11 years.
   Thompson had created advertising in the early 1980's that
compared Burger King's flame-broiled approach to cooking with that
used by McDonald's. The campaign was credited for helping lift
Burger King sales.
   But campaigns in more recent years failed to provide the same
spark. Burger King's search for the nerdy Herb bombed, and its
subsequent ``This is a Burger King Town'' and ``Best Food for Fast
Times'' failed to produce sales gains.
   In late September 1987, Burger King selected N.W. Ayer & Co. as
its new agency. In early 1988, it rolled out its new ad theme ``We
Do It Like You'd Do It.'' The company said that the campaign has
helped boost awareness of Burger King's name even if sales have not
shot higher.
   Other problems also have arisen. Last month, twelve of the
chain's black franchisees sued the company on the grounds it
assigned black operators unprofitable locations, reserving more
lucrative outlets for white franchise holders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
