<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Stable, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was slightly lower but stable against
most major currencies in lethargic European trading this morning as
the market awaited the outcome of the U.S. presidential election.
   Gold prices rose.
   Dealers said the market was focused almost exclusively on the
election, leaving little room for other factors to influence the
dollar.
   They predicted that if Vice President George Bush is elected as
is expected, the dollar would fall by a few pfennigs against the
West German mark.
   ``I can imagine that the dollar will drop to 1.75 marks and then
we'll have to see at what point the central banks step in,'' said a
dealer at a large Frankfurt bank.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.34 yen to a closing 124.73 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at a higher rate of 125.25 yen.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.7780 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.7755 late Monday.
   Other mid-morning dollar rates in Europe, compared with late
Monday's rates, included: 1.7825 West German marks, down from
1.7840; 1.4950 Swiss francs, down from 1.4965; 6.0815 French francs,
unchanged; 2.0060 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0148; 1,324.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,327.75; and 1.2330 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2374.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $422 a troy ounce, up
slightly from a late bid price of $421.75 on Monday. At mid-morning,
the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$421.85.
   In Zurich, gold rose and was trading at a mid-morning bid
$422.05, compared with $420.65 late Monday.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market, where the metal
was trading at a mid-morning bid price of $6.48 a troy ounce,
compared with Monday's $6.45.
</TEXT>
