<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Stocks Bounce Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar lost ground against the Japanese yen
today and share prices rebounded on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 124.73 yen, down 0.34 yen from Monday's
close of 125.07 yen. Opening lower at 124.50 yen, the currency moved
between 124.45 and 124.75 yen.
   Currency trading was cautious ahead of today's U.S. presidential
election, said Takamasa Yamasaki with the Daiwa Bank.
   ``But I guess traders in Tokyo seemed to have bought too many
dollars, considering it's right before the election,'' he said.
   Although the dollar moved below the 125-yen level all day, the
Bank of Japan did not intervene, Yamasaki said, ``probably because
the central bank did not want to make any move before the election.''
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 180.39-point
loser the previous day, regained 140.91 points, or 0.51 percent, to
move back to 28,007.27. The index was lower in early trading but
gradually recovered afterwards. On Monday, the Nikkei closed at
27,866.36 points.
   Market players also had been quite cautious ahead of the U.S.
election, but the index started to recover as more people came to
believe Republican Vice President George Bush will win, said a
dealer with Daiwa Securities in Tokyo.
   ``Investors are expecting no major change in the U.S. monetary
policy if Bush wins,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The election pits Bush against Democratic Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis.
   Trading volume on the first section was estimated at 900 million
shares, with high-tech issues attracting investors.
</TEXT>
