<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NorthwestPilots     11-08 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northwest Pilots,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest Pilots Begin Strike Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 4,800 unionized pilots for Northwest
Airlines have begun voting on whether to support a strike deadline
set by their negotiators, a union spokesman said.
   Pilots have until 3 p.m. CST Thursday to cast their ballots for
or against the strike deadline of midnight Sunday. The deadline was
set after contract talks between the Eagan-based airline and the Air
Line Pilots Association reached an impasse Nov. 1. No new talks are
scheduled.
   ``We're very encouraged at the participation level to this
point,'' Jim Halverson, an ALPA representative, said Monday. ``There
are a lot of pilots who are still out and about and flying.''
   Results won't be announced until balloting closes, he said. A
majority of those voting must support the strike deadline for the
measure to pass.
   Nothwest has said it is considering mediation as an option to
settle the dispute, but spokesman Red Tyler said Monday that no
request has been made. Halverson said the union isn't interested in
mediation.
   Talks have been held 102 times during the last 19 months and
Halverson said more than half the contract issues are unresolved.
   The carrier and union are negotiating for a combined contract
covering 2,800 pre-merger Northwest pilots and 2,000 former Republic
pilots. The two pilot groups have been working under separate
contracts since Northwest's acquisition of Republic in 1986.
   There are differences over wages, work schedules, fringe benefits
and length of contract.
   Tyler said Northwest does not expect a work stoppage, regardless
of the outcome of the strike vote.
   Northwest wants a contract effective through June 30, 1993, while
the union is seeking a pact that expires June 30, 1990.
   Under the Railway Labor Act, airline contracts continue in effect
until they are amended by the parties or until efforts to reach new
contracts are exhausted.
</TEXT>
