<2ND_LINE>BC-Defense Fraud,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Fined $725,000 in Defense Fraud Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A maker of components used in high-tech
weapons systems has been ordered to pay $725,000 in fines and
restitution for selling untested parts to the U.S. Navy and Coast
Guard.
   Genisco Technology Corp. was also placed on five years probation
Monday after company officials pleaded guilty last month to one
count of conspiracy to defraud the government.
   Genisco, based in Rancho Dominguez, about 12 miles south of
downtown Los Angeles, also pleaded guilty to three counts of
submitting false statements in 1986 and 1987 to the Navy regarding a
torpedo and underwater target device.
   Three former Genisco employees pleaded guilty to the charges and
were scheduled for sentencing Nov. 21.
   In another defense fraud case, a company vice president pleaded
guilty Monday to submitting false claims for payment on a military
contract, causing more than $220,000 in losses to the Defense
Department.
   Howard Garner, 45, of Diversified Container Corp. admitted
wrongdoing on two counts, Assistant U.S. Attorney Brian Hennigan
said.
   The company was awarded a contract to build floodlights for the
Defense General Supply Corp. in Richmond, Va., and submitted claims
saying 90 percent of the job had been completed.
   The company, based in La Puente, about 20 miles east of downtown
Los Angeles, received more than $226,000 as a result and later went
bankrupt after delivering only a few floodlights.
</TEXT>
