<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Stocks Higher in Light Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were higher Tuesday, but institutional
buying interest was light amid uncertainty over how the market will
react to the outcome of the U.S. presidential election.
   Market makers were busy marking prices higher in an attempt to
generate excitement and draw buyers into the market, dealers said.
But there were few takers, and much of the turnover came as market
makers moved to trim their books ahead of the election results, they
said.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index was up 15
points, or 0.8 percent, at 1,834.7 at midday.
   Volume was light, as 288.3 million shares changed hands, compared
with 186.4 million shares at the same time Monday.
   Traders generally expected a U.S. election victory by Vice
President George Bush. While confirmation of these expectations
could give the market a temporary boost, questions lingered about
whether the new U.S. president would take the necessary measures to
correct the country's economic ills, especially the massive budget
and trade deficits, they said.
   ``A post-election skepticism is already creeping into the
market,'' said one equity salesman. ``Is he (Bush) really the man to
change things?''
