<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 0925EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Marvel-Perelman     11-08 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Marvel-Perelman,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marvel Entertainment Reported Close To Being Sold For $82.5 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New World Entertainment Ltd. said it has
reached a tentative agreement to sell its Marvel Comics division for
$82.5 million to a company controlled by Revlon Chairman Ronald O.
Perelman.
   New World, which is trying to come back after losses in 1987 and
the first half of this year, said Monday said it expected to close
the deal soon.
   Marvel makes comic books featuring such characters as Superman,
G.I. Joe, the Incredible Hulk and Spiderman. The sale will not
include the company's Marvel Productions unit, which produces two
Saturday morning animated cartoon programs, New World said.
   At a price of $82.5 million, New World would make a sizable
profit on its investment of $46 million paid less than two years ago
when it acquired Marvel from Cadence Industries.
   In 1987, Marvel generated $2.3 million in operating income, while
New World's other core businesses showed an operating loss of $4.1
million.
   Last year, New World lost $18.5 million on revenue of $384.3
million. It lost $24.2 million on revenue of $203 million in the
first half of 1988.
</TEXT>
