nervousness about the election's outcome.
   ``In some sense it's a no-win situation in the election,'' said
Larry Wachtel, vice president of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
``If Dukakis wins the market is down 100 points. If Bush wins, the
market yawns.''
   Analysts said today's market appeared to be bouncing back from
declines the two previous days sparked by recent economic reports.
An unexpectedly low jobless rate for October combined with other
data suggested the economy might be heating up again.
   A stronger economy could signal higher inflation and, in turn,
higher interest rates if the Federal Reserve moves to slow the
economy.
   This morning's early rebound also came on technical factors as
bond prices opened higher on the first day of the U.S. Treasury's
refunding, analysts said.
