<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SharonSteel     11-08 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Sharon Steel,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trustee Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARRELL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Under pressure from creditors who threatened
court action to oust him, the trustee appointed to run Sharon Steel
Corp. during the company's reorganization in bankruptcy court
announced his resignation Tuesday.
   ``The job has been far more demanding than I expected, and I
don't want to continue in a role that takes such a heavy toll on my
life,'' trustee James W. Toren said.
   His resignation, filed Monday in Erie with U.S. Bankruptcy Judge
Warren Bentz, takes effect when a successor is appointed and
confirmed by the court.
   Creditors told Toren, 73, at an Oct. 7 meeting that they would
petition the court for his removal if he did not resign.
   Toren, who was appointed in January, infuriated creditors in June
when he suspended negotiations in which the company was seeking
contract concessions from 2,100 members of the United Steelworkers
union. He reasoned that the workers should not be asked for
concessions until the company's financial condition was clear.
Creditors argued that enough was known to seek wage and benefit
givebacks.
   Among other actions, Toren sued Sharon Chairman Victor Posner for
the return of 14 Norman Rockwell paintings that hung in Posner's
Miami Beach office and for a refund from the $16.2 million Posner
paid himself between 1983 and late 1987.
   Chief Operating Officer Walter Sieckman says Sharon, whose lone
steel plant is in this western Pennsylvania community, is marginally
profitable. Creditors claim the company is still losing money.
   Employment at the Victor Posner Works has increased by several
hundred in recent months to about 2,500.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
