<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Coleco     11-08 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Coleco,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coleco Closing Canadian Subsidiary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coleco Industries Inc. plans to close
its Canadian subsidiary and rely on a Toronto toy company to market
its products in that country.
   The move, announced Monday, is part of cost-cutting steps by
Coleco, which filed in July for protection from its creditors under
Chapter 11 of the Federal Bankruptcy Act.
   About 50 employees of Coleco (Canada) Ltd. will be affected by
the closing.
   J. Brian Clarke, Coleco's president and chief executive officer,
said sales from the Canadian subsidiary are typically about 10
percent of Coleco's total sales.
   Coleco had total sales of $504 million in 1987.
   The West Hartford toymaker said it reached an agreement with
Irwin Toy Ltd. to become the exclusive distributor in Canada of toys
and games sold by Coleco.
   Coleco's major products include Cabbage Patch Kids and ALF
stuffed toys.
   The agreement with Irwin is subject to approval of bankruptcy
Judge Prudence Abram in New York, who is handling Coleco's case.
</TEXT>
