<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Mixed In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly higher,
then turned mixed in early trading today on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   Follow-through buying from Monday's late rally evaporated shortly
after the opening, leaving prices to drift in narrow ranges.
   ``It's a pretty quiet affair,'' said Dale Gustafson, an analyst
with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   The rally that ended Monday's session was based on a news report
that the Soviet Union was considering buying 2 million metric tons
of U.S. soybeans or soybean meal, analysts said. After Monday's
close, the Agriculture Department announced the Soviets had
purchased 300,000 metric tons of meal.
   The sale announcement ``doesn't seem to have much influence in
today's market,'' Gustafson said.
   Traders were exercising caution ahead of Wednesday's USDA crop
production report, which is expected to show slight increases since
last month in the government's estimates for 1988 U.S. corn and
soybean production.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent lower to 2 cents higher with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.19 a bushel; corn was {
cent to 1} cents lower with December at $2.77 a bushel; oats were 3
cents lower to { cent higher with December at $2.22 a bushel; and
soybeans were 1\ cents lower to 2{ cents higher with November at
$7.88 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent to .33 cent higher with December at
73.82 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .30 cent higher
with November at 81.75 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent lower
to .08 cent higher with December at 42.15 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .30 cent to .45 cent higher with February at 46.42
cents a pound.
   Cattle settled mostly higher on Monday while pork futures were
mixed.
