<DOCNO> AP881108-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 1148EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-US     11-08 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-US,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC: Ban On Hormone-Treated Meat Is On</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community said
Tuesday a ban on imports of hormone-treated meat will take effect as
planned Jan. 1, despite threats of retaliation from the United
States.
   ``One must count on a total ban of hormones from the beginning of
next year,'' a spokesman for the EEC executive Commission said.
   Clayton Yeutter, the U.S. trade representative, and Richard Lyng,
the U.S. agriculture secretary, are to arrive in Brussels Nov. 18 to
discuss the hormone ban and other trade issues with senior EEC
Commission officials.
   The EEC ban on meat treated with growth hormones stems from fears
such meat causes cancer.
   But the United States claims there is no scientific justification
for a blanket ban on hormones in meat and argues the EEC ban amounts
to an unfair trade practice.
   The ban was to have taken effect Jan. 1, 1988 but was delayed by
a year in the hope a compromise solution could be negotiated.
   But as negotiations reached a deadlock in recent months, five
U.S. industry groups have asked the administration to restrict or
cutoff imports of EEC meat or meat products if the EEC imposes its
hormone ban.
   President Reagan has already announced, but not enacted, 100
percent tariffs on EEC meat and meat products if the ban is imposed.
   The United States exports about $100 million worth of meat and
meat products to the EEC each year. By comparison, EEC exports to
the United States total some $450 million.
   The EEC Commission spokesman reiterated the EEC view that growth
hormones must be banned from meat for health reasons and that no
proof has been offered to show that the use of hormones is safe.
``There are no new elements as far as we're concerned,'' he said.
   He added Italy, Denmark, West Germany and Belgium had already
banned domestic sales of hormone-treated meat before the EEC
decision was implemented EEC-wide on Jan. 1 of this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
