<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 1239EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Harris-GE     11-08 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Harris-GE,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harris Announces Definitive GE Semiconductor Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MELBOURNE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harris Corp. on Tuesday said it has signed
a definitive agreement covering its previously-disclosed plan to buy
General Electric Co.'s solid state semiconductor business for $206
million.
   Purchase of the unit, initially announced Aug. 15, will boost
Harris' semiconductor sales by $550 million to $850 million, said
John T. Hartley, Harris chairman and chief executive officer.
   Harris, which had overall sales of $2.1 billion last year,
supplies information, communication and semiconductor systems,
products ansd services to government and commercial markets
worldwide.
   The deal has come under fire from some Wall Street analysts who
question the company's commitment to the volatile semiconductor
market, and say that the purchase will dilute earnings.
   ``You either want to be in the semiconductor business or you
don't, and we do,'' Hartley responded. ``This is a chance to take a
major step forward, a giant leap to become one of the major American
players in the semiconductor business.''
   The new division, which takes the name Harris Semiconductor, will
make Harris the nation's sixth largest producer of semiconductors,
the company said.
   Hartley said the GE business was particularly attractive because
of its close fit with Harris, adding an international dimension to
company sales _ especially in Europe and the Pacific Rim _ and
expertise in specialized market sectors, such as high-power
conductors used in the automotive industry.
   He acknowledged that the semiconductor market was cyclical in the
short run, but said it has shown excellent long-run growth, and that
Harris has learned to manage around the sector's volatility.
   Another doubt surrounding the deal is the forecast for flat or
declining budgets in the Defense Department, one of the industry's
largest clients.
   But Hartley said while defense expenditures overall are expected
to be stagnant, the electronic components sector is projected to
show modest growth.
   ``And it's a very large budget,'' he added.
   The company, which has committed itself to raising
earnings-per-share, said the purchase will not dilute shareholders'
return.
   ``We do not expect this to be dilutive,'' Hartley said. ``We
expect this to be a contributor to earnings in both the long run and
the short run.''
   Hartley said he expects to sign a financing agreement for the
deal in 30 days. He said Harris expects to have some increase in
debt, which could come from some combination of public financing,
bank borrowing or internal cash generation.
   Hartley also said that while Harris does not currently compete
directly with the Japanese, who dominate the high-volume,
lower-price end of the semiconductor market, the purchase positions
Harris to fend off any future such competition.
   ``I think you have to be a certain size to fight with the
Japanese, and this will help,'' Hartley said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
