<HEAD>Shares Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing figures thruout.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose sharply Tuesday on the London
Stock Exchange on speculation that Republican George Bush would win
the presidential election in the United States.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index rose 20.9
points, or 1.1 percent, to 1,840.6. The narrower Financial Times
30-share index was up 16 points at 1,491.
   Volume rose to 502.8 million shares from 334.5 million shares
Monday.
   Over the past several sessions, shares fell as polls showed
Democratic candidate Michael Dukakis was closing the gap on Bush.
But, with voting under way, market watchers bet on Bush.
   ``Suddenly, there seems to be a bit more confidence seeping into
the market and with another Republican in the White House, buying is
back in style,'' one market maker said.
   Another market-maker said, ``People seem to have come to the
conclusion that if Bush wins, we'll see some sort of rally, so we're
all a bit loath to get caught short.''
