<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Manville-Holophane     11-08 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Manville-Holophane,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manville Plans To Sell Holophane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manville Corp. on Tuesday announced it plans to
sell its Newark, Ohio-based Holophane lighting systems division.
   Alfred B. Gough, who heads Manville's Specialty Products Group,
said Holophane has been profitable but its ``specific market niche
no longer strategically fits our core businesses or future growth
plans.''
   Holophane is expected to have sales in excess of $100 million
this year, Manville said.
   Gough said Manville, which has just emerged from Chapter 11
bankruptcy protection, has received considerable unsolicited
interest in Holophane in recent years.
   Holophane designs and makes lighting fixtures and accessories for
commercial and industrial use. It employs more than 1,200 people at
plants in Edison, N.J.; Newark, Pataskala, Utica and Springfield,
Ohio; Brampton, Ontario; St. Hyacinthe, Quebec; and Milton Keynes,
England.
   Manville makes fiber glass, forest products and specialty
products including mining, filtration and roofing products. It
acquired Holophane, which was founded in 1895 in Paris, in 1971.
</TEXT>
