<HEAD>Belgium's Biggest Holding Company Boosts Stake in Zinc Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Societe Generale de Belgique announced
Tuesday that it has purchased an additional 40 percent interest in
the zinc company Vieille-Montagne, raising its stake in the metals
concern to 90 percent.
   Societe Generale said that it made the purchase at the price of
about $320 per share. Since Vieille-Montagne has 810,000 shares
outstanding, the total value of the latest purchase was about $103.7
million.
   The investment is one of the largest investments made by Societe
Generale in the wake of the unsuccessful takeover attempt earlier
this year by Italian entrepreneur Carlo De Benedettti. Societe
Generale is Belgium's largest holding company and Vieille-Montagne
is a major metals processor.
   The decision was made ``in conformity with the strategy of SGB to
reinforce its presence in the non-ferrous metals sector,'' according
to a company statement.
   SGB has a wholly-owned subsidiary, Union Miniere, through which
it held its previous stake of 50 percent in Vieille-Montagne.
</TEXT>
