<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were up slightly in dull afternoon
trading with blue-chip issues nearly flat as the market moved into a
holding pattern to await the outcome of the presidential election.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 7.12 points to
2,131.76 at 3 p.m. EST. The blue-chip indicator had advanced more
than 11 points by 10 a.m. but declined shortly after.
   Trading was relatively quiet with many banks and insurance
companies closed for election day. Analysts said activity in
blue-chip issues was duller than in the broader market with
institutional trading at a near standstill.
   Advancing issues outpaced declining issues by about 7 to 5 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 818 issues up, 562 down and 530
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 114.57 million shares.
   Observers said the market was in a holding pattern awaiting the
results of the presidential vote after opening stronger in
anticipation of a George Bush victory.
   But even with a Bush win, analysts said that investors were
restrained as they began looking ahead to the post-election economy.
   ``The market has given back earlier gains because even if Bush
wins, the outlook for interest rates is higher,'' said C. Beth
Cotner of Kemper Financial Services.
   Bond prices had opened higher, adding support to the stock
market, but by mid-afternoon those early gains had faded.
   The New York Stock Exchange composite index was up 0.65 to
154.93. At the American Stock Exchange, the composite market index
gained 1.04 to 294.51.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, RJR Nabisco, which is
in the middle of a takeover battle, was up ] at 87}, General
Electric had gained 1 point to 44| and Union Carbide had advanced [
to 26~.
   Sears Roebuck, which recently announced a major restructuring,
was down 1] to 42] and Pillsbury, which is reorganizing and spinning
off its Burger King unit, had lost | to 58].
