<HEAD>Grains, Soybeans Close Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed mostly higher
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid rumors of new export
sales of wheat and expectations of a new long-term grain agreement
with the Soviet Union.
   Analysts cited speculation that the Agriculture Department was
prepared to target China for a large amount of wheat at subsidized
prices. Rumors of upcoming wheat sales to China and Iraq also
surfaced.
   Also, with the U.S. presidential race over, many traders expected
the United States and the Soviet Union to finalize a new long-term
grain agreement within the next 10 days, said Dale Gustafson, an
analyst in Chicago with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   ``I think there seems to be a lot more expectation that next week
they'll meet again and settle their differences,'' he said.
   Corn followed wheat higher while the soybean market gained on
indications of increased overseas buying of vegetable oils, which
include soybean oil, Gustafson said.
   At the close, wheat was 2\ cents to 7{ cents higher with December
at $4.26{ a bushel; corn was \ cent to 2 cents higher with December
at $2.79 a bushel; oats were 2 cents lower to 1{ cents higher with
December at $2.23 a bushel; and soybeans were 4 cents to 9{ cents
higher with November at $7.96{ a bushel.
