<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     11-08 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0313</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose slightly in relatively quiet
trading today, as many investors stayed away from the market
awaiting the results of the presidential election.
   Analysts said the market opened higher on an enthusiastic note as
Wall Street anticipated a George Bush victory in the presidential
election. Stock prices declined throughout much of the day, but
regained some strength in the last half-hour of trading.
   Volume was light with many banks and insurance companies closed
for election day. Activity in blue-chip issues was duller than in
the broader market with institutional activity at a near standstill.
   The early excitement stemmed from a combination of factors,
including the results of a New Hampshire poll showing Bush an easy
victor. The polls closed in the tiny hamlet of Dixville Notch, N.H.,
while most people on the East Coast were still on their way to work.
   ``The market is waiting for the election results,'' said Eldon A.
Grimm, senior vice president at Birr, Wilson & Co. ``There are quite
a lot of people sitting on the sidelines waiting for movement one
way or the other.''
   The stock market had declined sharply in the previous two
sessions amid concerns that the economy is growing faster than
expected.
   Last Friday's Labor Department report showed that more people
found jobs in October than in the previous month, suggesting the
economy might be overheating. That report revived inflation worries
and concern that the Federal Reserve might move to slow the economy
by raising interest rates.
   This morning's early rebound came partly on technical factors as
bond prices opened higher on the first day of the U.S. Treasury's
refunding, analysts said. Those early gains later faded with many
Japanese investors withdrawing from trading activity to await word
on Emperor Hirohito's health.
</TEXT>
