<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-08 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0815</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precious Metals Prices Tumble On Election-Day Jitters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices of platinum, gold and silver futures fell sharply Tuesday
as nervous traders cashed out of the precious-metals markets to
await the presidential election results.
   On other markets, copper futures posted strong gains after three
days of declines; energy futures fell; grains and soybeans were
mostly higher; livestock and meat were mixed; and stock-index
futures advanced.
   The platinum market led the precious-metals complex lower, partly
on speculation that a likely Republican presidential victory would
mean continued low inflation and low investment demand for precious
metals, and partly on profit-taking by traders unwilling to bet on
the outcome of the presidential race.
   ``On the eve of the results of the presidential election, some
people just determined there was too much risk involved in having
any position and they went to liquidate,'' said Richard Levine, vice
president of precious metals and foreign exchange trading with
Elders Futures Inc. in New York.
   After a month of solid gains, traders who had bought platinum
futures in late September at prices below $500 a troy ounce realized
substantial profits.
   The contract for January delivery of platinum on the New York
Mercantile Exchange settled at $573 a troy ounce, $14.80 below
Monday's final price.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold was $3.60 to $3.70 lower
with December at $421.20 a troy ounce; silver was 9.7 cents to 10.6
cents lower with December at $6.425 a troy ounce.
   The dollar's gains Tuesday against other currencies and the
weakening oil market also contributed to the sell-off of precious
metals, said Peter Cardillo, commodities trading adviser with
Josephthal & Co. in New York.
   Despite Tuesday's decline, platinum supplies are tight and are
expected to remain so for the next several years.
   So ``no matter who wins, I would not be surprised to see the
rally pick up again,'' Levine said.
   Copper for December delivery jumped 3.4 cents to $1.423 a pound
on the Comex on reports of an escalation in the Peruvian miners'
strike.
   Late Monday, news circulated that banking and petroleum industry
workers might join the strike, which has brought copper mining and
smelting operations to a halt. The strike in Peru, the world's
seventh-largest copper producer, entered its fourth week on Tuesday.
   The price advance followed three days of declines and analysts
said the market was headed higher.
   ``Copper had three days of a good correction and the market is
just settling down and waiting for the next move to the upside,''
Cardillo said.
   Oil futures prices retreated in thin, choppy trading on the New
York Mercantile Exchange ahead of the Nov. 17 price-committee
meeting of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries and the
Nov. 21 gathering of the full cartel.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 6 cents to 26 cents
lower with December at $13.80 a barrel; heating oil was 16 cents to
60 cents lower with December at 43.53 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .35 cent to .85 cent lower with December at 46.40 cents
a gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures finished mostly higher on the Chicago
Board of Trade amid rumors of new export sales of wheat and
expectations of a new long-term grain agreement with the Soviet
Union.
   Talk circulated that the Agriculture Department was preparing to
target China for a large amount of wheat at subsidized prices,
analysts said. Rumors of upcoming wheat sales to China and Iraq also
surfaced.
   Also, with the U.S. presidential race over, many traders expected
the United States and the Soviet Union to finalize a new long-term
grain agreement within the next 10 days, said Dale Gustafson, an
analyst in Chicago with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Wheat settled 2\ cents to 7\ cents higher with December at $4.26\
a bushel; corn was unchanged to 2\ cents higher with December at
$2.78} a bushel; oats were 2 cents lower to 1{ cents higher with
December at $2.23 a bushel; soybeans were 4 cents to 9} cents higher
with November at $7.96\ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly higher while pork futures finished
mixed in thin, featureless trading on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent to .22 cent higher with December at
73.82 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .25 cent
higher with November at 81.45 cents a pound; live hogs were .35 cent
lower to .35 cent higher with December at 42 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .03 cent to .23 cent lower with February at 45.95
cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures advanced slightly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for December delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 finished .35 point higher at 275.05.
</TEXT>
