<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AlleghenyInternational     11-08 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Allegheny International,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Bidder Would Sell Sunbeam-Oster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York merchant banking group vying to
acquire troubled Allegheny International Inc. said Tuesday it is
confident the company's Sunbeam Appliance and Oster buisnesses can
be sold off as part of the deal.
   Gilliam Joseph Littlejohn & Levy has proposed acquiring Allegheny
International in a deal valued at $703.5 million, of which $662.3
million would be in cash.
   The offer comes a week after Allegheny International's board
agreed to merge with a corporation formed by the investment firm
Donaldson Lufkin & Jenrette for $698 million, $537.6 million of
which would be in cash.
   Paul S. Levy, a principal in Gilliam Joseph, said the sale of the
Sunbeam-Oster division would be necessary for ``a very, very safe''
leveraged buyout of Allegheny International.
   The company has been operating under protection from its
creditors under Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code since early
this year.
   In a leveraged buyout, loans used to buy the company are secured
by the company's assets.
   Allegheny International management declined comment on the Levy
offer, although management is know to oppose the sale of its
Sunbeam-Oster business. Divesting the flagship operation would
reduce the company to a maker of patio furniture, electric blankets,
barbecue grills, weather instruments and bathroom scales.
   Levy said the offer would expire on Dec. 1.
</TEXT>
