<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 1751EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   11-08 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Hold Slight Gains on Election Day</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JULIA MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market held on to slight gains after a
strong election-day opening Tuesday in anticipation of a victory by
Republican George Bush in the presidential vote.
   But analysts said that once the election is over, the market will
refocus on interest rates and other worries that have chilled the
market recently.
   The Dow Jones Industrial average advanced 2.85 points to close at
2,127.49, near its low of the day. The blue-chip indicator had
gained more than 14 points in early trading.
   In the broader market, advancing issues outpaced declines by
about 3-to-2 in nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed
stocks, with 852 issues up, 578 down and 532 unchanged.
   ``It's a strange thing. We almost have to get the election out of
the way in order to focus on the issues,'' said Hugh Johnson, senior
vice president for First Albany Corp. ``People are taking a deep
breath and just starting to think about that.''
   Analysts attributed the early burst of enthusiasm partly to
anticipation of a Bush win after the nation's first poll showed the
vice president an easy victor.
   ``There was a little rebound in the market with returns from New
Hampshire. Based on that the market popped up,'' said Emmanuel
Geronimous, senior vice president with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   The polls closed in the tiny hamlet of Dixville Notch, N.H.,
before most of the nation was awake.
   The stock market also got early support from higher bond prices
and a stronger dollar in foreign exchange trading as well as
technical factors. The market had declined sharply in two previous
sessions on what many analysts said was concern about the economy
and uncertainty about the outcome of the presidential election.
   Despite the early gains, stock prices faded early with few
institutional investors to lend the market support. Many banks and
insurance companies were closed for election day and volume was
relatively light.
   In addition, analysts said investors returned to a cautious mode,
preferring to wait for the election results before making new
commitments.
   ``It was kind of a fearful session,'' said Eldon A. Grimm, senior
vice president for Birr, Wilson & Co. ``After this long, bitter
election the market was waiting to get it over.''
   Analysts were mixed in their projections for Wednesday's market.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE totaled 141.66 million shares, up
from 133.87 million in Monday's session. Nationwide, consolidated
volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at regional
exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled 167.795
million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market was $2,710.343 billion, up
$10.180 billion, or 0.38 percent, in value.
   The NYSE composite index closed up 0.56 point at 154.84.
   Among blue-chip issues, IBM gained | to close at 119} and RJR
Nabisco rose ] at 87}. Pillsbury lost \ to 58} and Sears fell 1| at
42[.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index gained 1.39 to 316.75, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index rose 1.22 to 275.15.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market closed
up 2.33 to 378.84.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index rose 1.29
to 294.76.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881108-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 1841EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Zenth-Brookhurst     11-08 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zenth-Brookhurst,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zenith Amends Complaint Against Brookhurst</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zenith Electronics Corp. said Tuesday it
had amended its lawsuit against Brookhurst Partners LP to include
new challenges to the dissident shareholder group's plan to sell the
company.
   The amended complaint, filed late Monday in U.S. District Court
in Chicago, charges that Brookhurst's ongoing consent solicitation
continues ``a consistent course of bad faith'' designed to mislead
other Zenith shareholders and fraudulently manipulate the price of
the company's stock.
   Brookhurst said through spokesman Thomas Franco that it ``knows
of no basis for Zenith's allegations ... and intends to vigorously
defend itself against what the partnership believes is a baseless
lawsuit.''
   Zenith originally filed the lawsuit on Sept. 29.
   Brookhurst, an investment group headed by New York stock-market
speculators Herbert B. Abelow and Nicholas L. Ihasz, is seeking
written consents from a majority of Zenith shareholders to reduce
the size of Zenith's board of directors from 10 to six and to have
three of its own people named to the board.
   The Brookhurst board members would be committed to selling
Zenith's ailing television-manufacturing division and, failing that,
to selling the entire company.
   Shareholders have until Dec. 4 to respond to the consent
solicitation.
   Zenith, the nation's last major manufacturer of televisions,
claims Brookhurst is really interested only in driving up the price
of Zenith's stock so it can sell its 6.1 percent stake in the
company at a substantial profit.
   The amended lawsuit says Brookhurst is misleading other
shareholders with its consent solicitation and challenges
Brookhurst's characterization of Paul Street, a Brookhurst nominee
to Zenith's board, as an expert on the consumer electronics industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881108-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 1843EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SmithBarney-Glucksman     11-08 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smith Barney-Glucksman,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Lehman Brothers Exec Named Vice Chairman at Smith Barney</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lewis L. Glucksman, the onetime leader of the
investment firm Lehman Brothers, has been appointed as a vice
chairman of the brokerage Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co., it was
announced Tuesday.
   Starting Nov. 12, Glucksman will manage Smith Barney's capital
markets group which involves supervising principal trading in
fixed-income and equities securities. He will also chair Smith
Barney's credit policy committee, which oversees the firm's credit
decisions.
   ``Lew has demonstrated time and again an ability to achieve
outstanding results in all market conditions,'' said Frank G. Zarb,
chairman and chief executive of Smith Barney.
   Glucksman founded Glucksman & Co. in 1984 after leaving Lehman
Brothers, a predecessor to Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   He had served 21 years at Lehman Brothers, rising to the posts of
chairman and chief executive. Lehman Brothers was sold to
Shearson-American Express in May 1984.
   ``The opportunity to join Smith Barney and work with Frank Zarb
represents just the kind of challenge I've been looking for in the
industry I know and love best,'' Glucksman said in a prepared
statement. ...``I've thrived for many years for many years on
adapting to, and capitalizing on, the constant changes in this
industry, and look forward to the chance to do it again.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881108-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 1847EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f SaleofApexAssetstoHorshamCorp.ApprovedbyJudge     11-08
0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Sale of Apex Assets to Horsham Corp. Approved by Judge</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge has cleared the way
for the sale of assets of Apex Oil Co., including Clark Oil Co. and
the Copper Mountain ski resort, to a Canadian company, Horsham Corp.
of Toronto.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Barry S. Schermer approved the sale in a
68-page opinion issued late Monday afternoon. His ruling concludes a
key element of Apex's 10-month reorganization under Chapter 11 of
the federal bankruptcy lawes.
   Schermer overruled objections raised by Getty Petroleum Corp.,
which had a competing bid for the assets.
   Horsham will pay $536.5 million, while Getty was offering $588.5
million. But Horsham said its deal is worth an additional $150
million because of a discount it is getting on Apex's bank debt.
   Twelve banks agreed to sell $550 million in loans to Horsham for
$396 million, or 72 cents on the dollar. By buying the loans,
Horsham will eliminate bank liens on Clark, Copper Mountain and the
other assets it is buying, as well as on assets that will remain
part of Apex.
   Clark Oil owns three refineries, 1,000 service stations and 15
petroleum terminals. Copper Mountain is a ski resort in Colorado.
Horsham also is buying oil-exploration and -production companies and
interests in pipelines.
   The assets are expected to change hands by Nov. 25, which is a
deadline set by the banks for completion of the loan sale.
   Apex would be left with coal, real estate and shipping
operations. The company would remain in bankruptcy with proceedings
to focus on how much Apex's creditors would be paid.
   Unsecured creditors have filed about $900 million in claims
against Apex, one of the nation's largest private companies. Apex
filed for protection from its creditors under Chapter 11 of the
bankruptcy law on Dec. 24, 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881108-0276 </DOCNO>
