<FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 1918EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   11-08 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0551</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Office of the Comptroller of the Currency
is preparing guidelines requiring nationally chartered banks to
consider more carefully their involvement in leveraged buyouts.
   Within the next few weeks, the agency will be sending new
guidelines to its examiners and to banks to help them evaluate when
an institution is vulnerable because of highly leveraged lending,
Lee Cross, a spokeswoman for Comptroller Robert Clarke, said Tuesday.
   Clarke's office regulates 4,450 of the nation's 13,400 commercial
banks.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover strategist Carl Icahn is reemerging as a
potential suitor for ailing Eastern Airlines after abandoning an
earlier effort.
   Analysts said Tuesday they expect Icahn, the owner and chairman
of Trans World Airlines Inc., to keep pursuing Eastern in light of
his pledge to press for acquisitions that would expand TWA's route
system and fleet of aircraft.
   Icahn is believed to be interested in Eastern's north-south
routes, especially between New York and Miami, as possible feeders
into TWA's trans-Atlantic system.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court has upheld the authority of
the states to tax corporate income derived from sales of oil and
natural gas extracted from offshore wells under federal jurisdiction.
   By a 9-0 vote, the court approved Tuesday a tax method in Iowa
that is virtually identical to that used by most other states.
   The so-called unitary method, challenged unsuccessfully by Shell
Oil Co., allows a state to impose a tax on that portion of a
company's income calculated to come from the amount of business it
does within that state.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The scope of a key federal anti-racketeering
law was at issue when the Supreme Court was urged to revive a
lawsuit by Minnesota customers against Northwestern Bell Telephone
Co.
   ``This case involved bribery over five years,'' lawyer Mark
Reinhardt of St. Paul contended Tuesday.
   He told the justices that a federal lawsuit under the Racketeer
Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act should not be blocked just
because a public utility allegedly paid the bribes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The high-level advisory commission on the
federal budget deficit, beset by deep divisions among panel members,
may delay issuing its recommendations for several months, the
co-chairman of the group says.
   Democrat Robert Strauss, one of two leaders of the bipartisan
National Economic Commission, said Tuesday that the group's report
may not be issued until March 1 or later.
   This would mark a turnabout from the commission's original goal
of issuing its recommendations by Dec. 21, in time to influence the
first budget submitted by the incoming administration.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York merchant banking group vying to
acquire troubled Allegheny International Inc. says it is confident
the company's Sunbeam Appliance and Oster businesses can be sold off
as part of the deal.
   Gilliam Joseph Littlejohn & Levy has proposed acquiring Allegheny
International in a deal valued at $703.5 million, of which $662.3
million would be in cash.
   Paul S. Levy, a principal in Gilliam Joseph, said Tuesday that
the sale of the Sunbeam-Oster division would be necessary for ``a
very, very safe'' leveraged buyout of Allegheny International.
</TEXT>
