<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   11-08 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0521</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and former White
House chief of staff Howard Baker say they have conferred
professionally about Drexel's internal operations, but deny a report
that the discussions were related to a criminal investigation of the
Wall Street investment giant.
   The Washington Post said in Tuesday's editions that Drexel was
negotiating with Baker about him becoming its chairman, a move that
some of the firm's officials reportedly see as a way of escaping
criminal charges.
   Drexel has been under intense scrutiny for nearly two years by
Manhattan U.S. Attorney Rudolph W. Giuliani's office as a result of
its relationship with Ivan F. Boesky, the now-imprisoned insider
trader who has turned state's evidence.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rainy autumn helped ease the dryness in the
East and some Central states, but large areas of the Upper Midwest
are facing winter still in the grip of long-term drought.
   ``Subsurface soil moisture is still very low in a lot of
states,'' Douglas LeComte, a meteorologist with the Department of
Agriculture, said Tuesday. ``That could come back to haunt us next
spring.''
   The federal Climate Analysis Center lists conditions of extreme
long-term drought as continuing in North Dakota, Idaho, Wyoming,
most of Montana and portions of South Dakota, Minnesota, Iowa,
Oregon and California.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Postal Service is considering
launching a high-speed money order service that would allow people
to transfer funds anywhere in the country almost instantly.
   Postmaster General Anthony M. Frank said Tuesday that the agency
is preparing to file a request with the independent Postal Rate
Commission for permission to launch the new ``express money order''
service.
   The service would compete with the widely advertised money
transfer service from Western Union Corp.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Almost 3,000 Gulf service stations in Texas,
Louisiana, Arkansas and New Mexico will be converted to the Chevron
brand at a cost of more than $50 million, the company says.
   Chevron Corp. spokeswoman Sherri Zippay said Tuesday that the
switch should begin in January and be concluded in 1989 and will
give customers a ``consistent product coast-to-coast.''
   Chevron's predecessor Standard Oil Co. of California acquired
Gulf in 1984.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manville Corp. says it plans to sell its Newark,
Ohio-based Holophane lighting systems division.
   Alfred B. Gough, who heads Manville's Specialty Products Group,
said Tuesday that Holophane has been profitable but its ``specific
market niche no longer strategically fits our core businesses or
future growth plans.''
   Holophane is expected to have sales in excess of $100 million
this year, Manville said.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rose slightly after a strong election-day
opening Tuesday. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials closed up
2.85 points at 2,127.49.
   The dollar rose. Gold prices fell.
   Bond prices finished mostly higher.
   Copper futures posted strong gains; energy futures fell; grains
and soybeans were mostly higher; livestock and meat were mixed; and
stock-index futures rose.
</TEXT>
