<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0242 11-08 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0242,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Stocks Up In Tokyo Morning Session</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning Nikkei, later dollar
trading, comments. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar edged up against the Japenese yen
Wednesday morning, while share prices also rose on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange, encouraged by reports of George Bush's early lead in the
U.S. presidential election.
   The dollar by late morning was changing hands at 125.50 yen,
after opening at 125.52 yen, up from Tuesday's close of 124.73 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
140.91 points on Tuesday, was up another 154.98 points from
Tuesday's close at 28,162.25 to finish the morning session.
   The index rose on news of Republican Bush's early lead over
Democrat Michael Dukakis in the presidential election, he said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Many market players' expectations that a Bush victory would bring
no major change in the U.S. economic policy encouraged buying in the
Tokyo market, the dealer said.
   The dollar also was supported Wednesday by news of Bush's lead,
dealers said.
   However, many investors were waiting on the sidelines because of
concerns over a Japanese trade report due out Thursday, said a
dealer with a major commercial bank.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
